{"title_page": "Luiz Henrique Mandetta", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name              = Luiz Henrique Mandetta\n|image             = Luiz Henrique Mandetta em 29 de maio de 2019 (recorte).jpg\n|office            = [[Ministry of Health (Brazil)|Minister of Health]]\n|term_start        = 1 January 2019\n|term_end          = 16 April 2020 <ref name=\"Mandetta anuncia demiss\u00e3o\" />\n|president         = [[Jair Bolsonaro]]\n|predecessor       = [[Gilberto Occhi]]\n|successor         = Nelson Teich\n|office1           = Member of the [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Chamber of Deputies]]<br />for [[Mato Grosso do Sul]]\n|term_start1       = 1 February 2011\n|term_end1         = \n|birth_name        = \n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1964|11|30|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Campo Grande]], [[Mato Grosso]], Brazil<br /><small>(present-day [[Mato Grosso do Sul]])</small>\n|party             = [[Brazilian Democratic Movement|PMDB]] <small>(2002\u20132009)</small><br />[[Democrats (Brazil)|DEM]] <small>(2009\u2013present)</small>\n|mother            = Maria Olga Solari\n|father            = H\u00e9lio Mandetta\n|education         = [[Gama Filho University]]\n|profession        = \n|allegiance        = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazil]]\n|branch            = [[File:Coat of arms of the Brazilian Army.svg|15px]] [[Brazilian Army]]\n|rank              = [[File:Primeiro-Tenente-V.gif|15px]] [[Lieutenant]]\n}}\n'''Luiz Henrique Mandetta''' (born 30 November 1964) is a [[Brazil]]ian pediatric orthopedist and politician, member of the [[Democrats (Brazil)|Democrats]] (DEM). Mandetta was announced in 20 November 2018 as [[Ministry of Health (Brazil)|Minister of Health]] of the president-elect [[Jair Bolsonaro]], replacing [[Gilberto Occhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2018/11/20/bolsonaro-anuncia-deputado-mandetta-como-futuro-ministro-da-saude.ghtml|title=Bolsonaro anuncia deputado Mandetta como futuro ministro da Sa\u00fade|publisher=G1|language=pt|first=Guilherme|last=Mazui|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> Was fired in 16 April 2020, by President Jair Bolsonaro after disagreements over social isolation during the period of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brazil|COVID-19 in Brazil]].<ref name=\"Mandetta anuncia demiss\u00e3o\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2020/04/16/mandetta-anuncia-em-rede-social-que-foi-demitido-do-ministerio-da-saude.ghtml|title=Mandetta anuncia em rede social que foi demitido do Minist\u00e9rio da Sa\u00fade|trans-title=Mandetta announces on social network that he has been fired from the Ministry of Health|accessdate=16 April 2020|work=G1}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nMandetta is a graduated medic by the University Gama Filho, with specialization in orthopedics by the service of orthopedics of the Federal University of Mato Grosso do Sul and sub-specialization in pediatric orthopedics by the [[Old Scottish Rite Hospital|Scottish Rite Hospital for Children]] in [[Atlanta]]. He was military medic, as lieutenant,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-46282841|title=Governo Bolsonaro: Quem \u00e9 Luiz Henrique Mandetta, que ser\u00e1 ministro da Sa\u00fade|publisher=BBC|language=pt|first1=Andr\u00e9|last1=Shalders|first2=Matheus|last2=Magenta|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> in the Army Central Hospital.\n\n==Political career==\n===Member of Congress, 2010\u2013present===\nMandetta has been an elected federal deputy since the [[2010 Brazilian legislative election|2010 elections]] for the 54th Congress;<ref>Gabriel Stargardter and Lisandra Paraguassu (1 April 2020), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-brazil-minister-ne/one-brazilian-minister-shines-as-coronavirus-clobbers-bolsonaro-idUSKBN21J65E One Brazilian minister shines as coronavirus clobbers Bolsonaro] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref> he was reelected in 2014 for the 55th Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.camara.leg.br/deputados/pesquisa/layouts_deputados_biografia?pk=189093&tipo=0|title=Quem s\u00e3o|publisher=C\u00e2mara dos Deputados|language=pt|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time in Congress, Mandetta was most well-known for opposing health policies of the leftist Workers Party government, and in particular its \u201cMais Medicos\u201d program which brought Cuban doctors to Brazil\u2019s most far-flung corners. He voted for the [[Impeachment of Dilma Rousseff|impeachment]] of [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>Gabriel Stargardter and Lisandra Paraguassu (1 April 2020), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-brazil-minister-ne/one-brazilian-minister-shines-as-coronavirus-clobbers-bolsonaro-idUSKBN21J65E One Brazilian minister shines as coronavirus clobbers Bolsonaro]\u00a0''[[Reuters]]''.</ref><ref name=\"Votes\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/veja-como-deputados-votaram-no-impeachment-de-dilma-na-pec-241-na-reforma-trabalhista-e-na-denuncia-contra-temer.ghtml|title=Veja como deputados votaram no impeachment de Dilma, na PEC 241, na reforma trabalhista e na den\u00fancia contra Temer|publisher=G1|language=pt|date=2 August 2017|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> Later, he was in favor of the Constitutional Amendment n.\u00ba 95 of 2016, that established a new tax regime.<ref name=\"Votes\"/> On April 2017, voted in favor of the Labour Reform.<ref name=\"Votes\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/blogs/parlatorio/reforma-trabalhista-como-votaram-os-deputados|title=Reforma trabalhista: como votaram os deputados|publisher=Carta Capital|language=pt|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> On August 2017, voted for the progress of the complaint against president [[Michel Temer]].<ref name=\"Votes\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/politica/como-votou-cada-deputado-sobre-a-denuncia-contra-temer|title=Como votou cada deputado sobre a den\u00fancia contra Temer|publisher=Carta Capital|date=3 August 2017|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of Health, 2018\u2013present===\nIn 20 November 2018, Mandetta was confirmed by president-elect [[Jair Bolsonaro]] to assume the Ministry of Health.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/politica/noticia/2018/11/mandetta-e-confirmado-como-ministro-da-saude-cjopzkpg20f7o01pimja3nm36.html|title=Mandetta \u00e9 confirmado como ministro da Sa\u00fade|publisher=Ga\u00fachaZH|language=pt|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> About the accusations of irregularities when he was Secretary of Health of Campo Grande, Mandetta affirmed a week before the confirmation that he had talked to Bolsonaro about the details of the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saude.gov.br/o-ministro|title=O Ministro|last=Minist\u00e9rio da Sa\u00fade|website=www.saude.gov.br|language=pt-br|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> According to him, the president-elect said that only the complaint wouldn't be a reason to block his nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.campograndenews.com.br/politica/cotado-para-ministerio-mandetta-discutiu-caso-gisa-com-bolsonaro|title=Cotado para minist\u00e9rio, Mandetta discutiu \"caso Gisa\" com Bolsonaro|publisher=Campo Grande News|language=pt|first=Humberto|last=Marques|date=13 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> Mandetta is currently under investigation for alleged procurement fraud, influence peddling and undeclared campaign donations.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-46282841 Governo Bolsonaro: Quem \u00e9 Luiz Henrique Mandetta, que ser\u00e1 ministro da Sa\u00fade, BBC]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMandetta is Roman Catholic.<ref>https://aonca.com.br/siteprints/catolico-mandetta-representa-ms-em-cerimonia-de-canonizacao-de-santa-dulce/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gilberto Occhi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Health (Brazil)|Minister of Health]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Bolsonaro cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandetta, Luiz Henrique}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Campo Grande]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Democratic Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Democrats (Brazil) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies (Brazil) from Mato Grosso do Sul]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name              = Luiz Henrique Mandetta\n|image             = Luiz Henrique Mandetta em 29 de maio de 2019 (recorte).jpg\n|office            = [[Ministry of Health (Brazil)|Minister of Health]]\n|term_start        = 1 January 2019\n|term_end          = 16 April 2020 <ref name=\"Mandetta anuncia demiss\u00e3o\" />\n|president         = [[Jair Bolsonaro]]\n|predecessor       = [[Gilberto Occhi]]\n|successor         = Nelson Teich\n|office1           = Member of the [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Chamber of Deputies]]<br />for [[Mato Grosso do Sul]]\n|term_start1       = 1 February 2011\n|term_end1         = \n|birth_name        = \n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1964|11|30|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Campo Grande]], [[Mato Grosso]], Brazil<br /><small>(present-day [[Mato Grosso do Sul]])</small>\n|party             = [[Brazilian Democratic Movement|PMDB]] <small>(2002\u20132009)</small><br />[[Democrats (Brazil)|DEM]] <small>(2009\u2013present)</small>\n|mother            = Maria Olga Solari\n|father            = H\u00e9lio Mandetta\n|education         = [[Gama Filho University]]\n|profession        = \n|allegiance        = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazil]]\n|branch            = [[File:Coat of arms of the Brazilian Army.svg|15px]] [[Brazilian Army]]\n|rank              = [[File:Primeiro-Tenente-V.gif|15px]] [[Lieutenant]]\n}}\n'''Luiz Henrique Mandetta''' (born 30 November 1964) is a [[Brazil]]ian pediatric orthopedist and politician, member of the [[Democrats (Brazil)|Democrats]] (DEM). Mandetta was announced in 20 November 2018 as [[Ministry of Health (Brazil)|Minister of Health]] of the president-elect [[Jair Bolsonaro]], replacing [[Gilberto Occhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2018/11/20/bolsonaro-anuncia-deputado-mandetta-como-futuro-ministro-da-saude.ghtml|title=Bolsonaro anuncia deputado Mandetta como futuro ministro da Sa\u00fade|publisher=G1|language=pt|first=Guilherme|last=Mazui|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> Was fired in 16 April 2020, by President Jair Bolsonaro after disagreements over social isolation during the period of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brazil|COVID-19 in Brazil]].<ref name=\"Mandetta anuncia demiss\u00e3o\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2020/04/16/mandetta-anuncia-em-rede-social-que-foi-demitido-do-ministerio-da-saude.ghtml|title=Mandetta anuncia em rede social que foi demitido do Minist\u00e9rio da Sa\u00fade|trans-title=Mandetta announces on social network that he has been fired from the Ministry of Health|accessdate=April 16 2020|work=G1}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nMandetta is a graduated medic by the University Gama Filho, with specialization in orthopedics by the service of orthopedics of the Federal University of Mato Grosso do Sul and sub-specialization in pediatric orthopedics by the [[Old Scottish Rite Hospital|Scottish Rite Hospital for Children]] in [[Atlanta]]. He was military medic, as lieutenant,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-46282841|title=Governo Bolsonaro: Quem \u00e9 Luiz Henrique Mandetta, que ser\u00e1 ministro da Sa\u00fade|publisher=BBC|language=pt|first1=Andr\u00e9|last1=Shalders|first2=Matheus|last2=Magenta|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> in the Army Central Hospital.\n\n==Political career==\n===Member of Congress, 2010\u2013present===\nMandetta has been an elected federal deputy since the [[2010 Brazilian legislative election|2010 elections]] for the 54th Congress;<ref>Gabriel Stargardter and Lisandra Paraguassu (April 1, 2020), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-brazil-minister-ne/one-brazilian-minister-shines-as-coronavirus-clobbers-bolsonaro-idUSKBN21J65E One Brazilian minister shines as coronavirus clobbers Bolsonaro] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref> he was reelected in 2014 for the 55th Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.camara.leg.br/deputados/pesquisa/layouts_deputados_biografia?pk=189093&tipo=0|title=Quem s\u00e3o|publisher=C\u00e2mara dos Deputados|language=pt|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time in Congress, Mandetta was most well-known for opposing health policies of the leftist Workers Party government, and in particular its \u201cMais Medicos\u201d program which brought Cuban doctors to Brazil\u2019s most far-flung corners. He voted for the [[Impeachment of Dilma Rousseff|impeachment]] of [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>Gabriel Stargardter and Lisandra Paraguassu (April 1, 2020), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-brazil-minister-ne/one-brazilian-minister-shines-as-coronavirus-clobbers-bolsonaro-idUSKBN21J65E One Brazilian minister shines as coronavirus clobbers Bolsonaro]\u00a0''[[Reuters]]''.</ref><ref name=\"Votes\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/veja-como-deputados-votaram-no-impeachment-de-dilma-na-pec-241-na-reforma-trabalhista-e-na-denuncia-contra-temer.ghtml|title=Veja como deputados votaram no impeachment de Dilma, na PEC 241, na reforma trabalhista e na den\u00fancia contra Temer|publisher=G1|language=pt|date=2 August 2017|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> Later, he was in favor of the Constitutional Amendment n.\u00ba 95 of 2016, that established a new tax regime.<ref name=\"Votes\"/> On April 2017, voted in favor of the Labour Reform.<ref name=\"Votes\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/blogs/parlatorio/reforma-trabalhista-como-votaram-os-deputados|title=Reforma trabalhista: como votaram os deputados|publisher=Carta Capital|language=pt|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> On August 2017, voted for the progress of the complaint against president [[Michel Temer]].<ref name=\"Votes\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/politica/como-votou-cada-deputado-sobre-a-denuncia-contra-temer|title=Como votou cada deputado sobre a den\u00fancia contra Temer|publisher=Carta Capital|date=3 August 2017|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of Health, 2018\u2013present===\nIn 20 November 2018, Mandetta was confirmed by president-elect [[Jair Bolsonaro]] to assume the Ministry of Health.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/politica/noticia/2018/11/mandetta-e-confirmado-como-ministro-da-saude-cjopzkpg20f7o01pimja3nm36.html|title=Mandetta \u00e9 confirmado como ministro da Sa\u00fade|publisher=Ga\u00fachaZH|language=pt|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> About the accusations of irregularities when he was Secretary of Health of Campo Grande, Mandetta affirmed a week before the confirmation that he had talked to Bolsonaro about the details of the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saude.gov.br/o-ministro|title=O Ministro|last=Minist\u00e9rio da Sa\u00fade|website=www.saude.gov.br|language=pt-br|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> According to him, the president-elect said that only the complaint wouldn't be a reason to block his nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.campograndenews.com.br/politica/cotado-para-ministerio-mandetta-discutiu-caso-gisa-com-bolsonaro|title=Cotado para minist\u00e9rio, Mandetta discutiu \"caso Gisa\" com Bolsonaro|publisher=Campo Grande News|language=pt|first=Humberto|last=Marques|date=13 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> Mandetta is currently under investigation for alleged procurement fraud, influence peddling and undeclared campaign donations.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-46282841 Governo Bolsonaro: Quem \u00e9 Luiz Henrique Mandetta, que ser\u00e1 ministro da Sa\u00fade, BBC]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMandetta is Roman Catholic.<ref>https://aonca.com.br/siteprints/catolico-mandetta-representa-ms-em-cerimonia-de-canonizacao-de-santa-dulce/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gilberto Occhi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Health (Brazil)|Minister of Health]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Bolsonaro cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandetta, Luiz Henrique}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Campo Grande]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Democratic Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Democrats (Brazil) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies (Brazil) from Mato Grosso do Sul]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luiz_Henrique_Mandetta"}
{"title_page": "List of National Taiwan University people", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of National Taiwan University people''' includes alumni and prominent faculty and staff.\n\n==University chancellors==\n*[[Chang-lin Tien|Tien, Chang-lin]] (\u7530\u9577\u9716): the 8th Chancellor of the University of California, Berkeley\n*[[Henry T. Yang]] (\u694a\u7956\u4f51): the 5th Chancellor of the University of California, Santa Barbara.\n\n==Academia==\n*[[Benjamin Hsiao]] (BS, [[chemical engineering]] 1980): chief research officer and vice-president for research at [[Stony Brook University]], Fellow of the [[American Physical Society]], Fellow of the [[American Chemical Society]], Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Benjamin S. Hsiao Named Vice President for Research at Stony Brook University|url=http://commcgi.cc.stonybrook.edu/am2/publish/General_University_News_2/Benjamin_S_Hsiao_Named_Vice_President_for_Research_at_Stony_Brook_University.shtml|accessdate=12 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712101250/http://commcgi.cc.stonybrook.edu/am2/publish/General_University_News_2/Benjamin_S_Hsiao_Named_Vice_President_for_Research_at_Stony_Brook_University.shtml|archivedate=12 July 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Larry Hsien Ping Lang]] (\u90ce\u54b8\u5e73): chair professor of finance at The [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]]\n*[[Ruey-Shiung Lin]] (\u6797\u745e\u96c4): Professor Emeritus of [[Public health]], National Taiwan University\n*[[Jiun-Huei Proty Wu]]: physics professor and Deputy Vice President for International Affairs, National Taiwan University\n\n==Engineering==\n*[[Wen Chi Chen]] (\u9673\u6587\u7426): president and CEO of [[VIA Technologies]]\n*[[Min Kao|Min H. Kao]] (\u9ad8\u6c11\u74b0): co-founder of [[Garmin]] Corporation, the GPS manufacturer\n*[[Barry Lam]]: (\u6797\u767e\u91cc): founder and chair of [[Quanta Computer]], the leading laptop producer worldwide\n*[[John Shen]]: executive of Globalization Services, [[IBM]] China Development Laboratory\n*[[Rick Tsai]] (\u8521\u529b\u884c): president and CEO of [[Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company]]\n\n==Physical sciences, mathematics, and engineering==\n*[[Ching-Li Chai]] (\u7fdf\u656c\u7acb): Professor of Mathematics, [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n*[[Sun-Yung Alice Chang]] (\u5f20\u5723\u5bb9): Professor of Mathematics at Princeton University\n*[[Chen-Yu Chi]] (\u9f4a\u9707\u5b87): Junior Fellow, [[Harvard University]]\n*[[Wu-Chung Hsiang]] (\u9805\u6b66\u5fe0): Professor of Mathematics, [[Princeton University]]\n*[[Wu-Yi Hsiang]] (\u9805\u6b66\u7fa9): Professor of Mathematics, [[Hong Kong University of Science and Technology]]; Professor Emeritus of Mathematics, [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n*[[Benjamin Hsiao]] (BS, [[Chemical Engineering]] 1980) : Chief Research Officer and Vice-President for Research at [[Stony Brook University]], Fellow of the [[American Physical Society]], Fellow of the [[American Chemical Society]], Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Benjamin S. Hsiao Named Vice President for Research at Stony Brook University|url=http://commcgi.cc.stonybrook.edu/am2/publish/General_University_News_2/Benjamin_S_Hsiao_Named_Vice_President_for_Research_at_Stony_Brook_University.shtml|accessdate=12 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712101250/http://commcgi.cc.stonybrook.edu/am2/publish/General_University_News_2/Benjamin_S_Hsiao_Named_Vice_President_for_Research_at_Stony_Brook_University.shtml|archivedate=12 July 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Chun-Hway Hsueh]]: ISI ''high-cited researcher'' in materials science; Distinguished R&D Staff, Metals & Ceramics Division, [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]]\n*[[Jin Au Kong]] (\u5b54\u91d1\u750c): Professor of Electrical Engineering, Massachusetts Institute of Technology\n*[[Lee Si-Chen]] (\u674e\u55e3\u6d94): [[semiconductor]] researcher; IEEE Fellow, 2002; Professor of Electrical Engineering, National Taiwan University; President of National Taiwan University (2005 \u2013 )\n*[[Fan Chung]] (\u91d1\u82b3\u84c9): Professor of Mathematics at the University of California, San Diego\n*[[Yuan-Tseh Lee]] (\u674e\u9060\u54f2): Nobel Prize in chemistry, 1986; Professor Emeritus of Physical Chemistry, National Taiwan University\n*[[Winnie Li]] (\u674e\u6587\u537f): Professor of Mathematics at Pennsylvania State University, [[Chern Prize (ICCM)]] recipient\n*[[Chang-Shou Lin]] (\u6797\u9577\u58fd): Director, Taida Institute of Mathematical Sciences (TIMS), Fellow of Academia Sinica\n*[[Ching-Liang Lin]] ([[Traditional Chinese characters|Chinese]]: \u6797\u6e05\u51c9; 1931\u20132019): Professor of Physics, [[National Taiwan University]]\n*[[Tai-Ping Liu]] (\u5289\u592a\u5e73): Director, Institute of Mathematics, Academia Sinica\n*[[Ho-Kwang Mao]] (\u6bdb\u6cb3\u5149): [[Balzan Prize]], 2005; [[Gregori Aminoff Prize]], 2005; [[Roebling Medal]], 2005; Staff, Geophysical Laboratory, [[Carnegie Institution of Washington]]\n*[[Chiang-Chung Mei]] (\u6885\u5f37\u4e2d): Professor of Civil and Environmental Engineering, [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n*[[Teresa H. Meng]](\u5b5f\u61f7\u7e08): Reid Weaver Dennis Professor of Electrical Engineering, Stanford University; Founder of [[Atheros Communications]], Inc.\n*[[Shen-su Sun]] (\u5b6b\u8ce2\u9265): geochemist\n*[[Simon Min Sze]] (\u65bd\u654f): pioneer in [[MOSFET]]; IEEE [[J J Ebers Award]], 1991\n*[[Yu-Chong Tai]] (\u6234\u807f\u660c): pioneer in [[microelectromechanical system]] (MEMS); Professor of Electrical Engineering, [[California Institute of Technology]]\n*[[Chenming Calvin Hu]] (\u80e1\u6b63\u660e):pioneer in [[FinFET]]; Distinguished Professor Emeritus in the electronic engineering and computer science department of the [[University of California, Berkeley]].\n*[[Kuan-Chong Ting]] : Professor and Head, Department of Agricultural and Biological Engineering, [[University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]]\n*[[Tsay Ting-kuei]] (\u8521\u4e01\u8cb4), Professor of Civil Engineering, National Taiwan University since 1990<ref name=\"SingTao20140412\">{{cite news|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/2014-04-12/taiwan1397281850d5001753.html|title=\u8521\u4e01\u8cb4\u7acb\u9662\u65c1\u7d2e\u71df1988\u5929|trans-title=Tsay Ting-kuei camps outside Legislative Yuan building for 1988 days|work=[[Sing Tao Daily]] Canada Edition|date=12 April 2014|accessdate=14 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416183517/http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/2014-04-12/taiwan1397281850d5001753.html|archive-date=16 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Chin-Lung Wang]] (\u738b\u91d1\u9f8d): National Endowed Chair Professor and Professor of Mathematics, [[National Taiwan University]]\n*[[Weng I. Wang]] (\u738b\u6587\u4e00): Professor of Electrical Engineering, [[Columbia University]]\n*[[Chi-Huey Wong]] (\u7fc1\u555f\u60e0): Professor of Chemistry, the [[Scripps Research Institute]]; President of [[Academia Sinica]] (in Taiwan)\n*[[C.F. Jeff Wu]] (\u5433\u5efa\u798f): Coca-Cola Chair in Engineering Statistics, [[Georgia Institute of Technology]]; Member, [[National Academy of Engineering]], USA\n*[[Andrew Yao]] (\u59da\u671f\u667a): [[Turing Award]] 2000; Professor, Princeton University; Professor, [[Tsinghua University]], Beijing (2004 \u2013 )\n*[[Horng-Tzer Yau]] (\u59da\u9d3b\u6fa4): [[MacArthur Fellowship]], 2000; Professor of Mathematics, Harvard University\n*[[Nai-Chang Yeh]] (\u8449\u4e43\u88f3): Professor of Physics, California Institute of Technology\n\n==Life sciences==\n*[[Chuan-Chiung Chang]] (\u5f35\u50b3\u70f1): co-discoverer of [[bungarotoxin]]; Professor Emeritus of Pharmacology, National Taiwan University\n*[[Ding-Shinn Chen]], M.D. (\u9673\u5b9a\u4fe1): authority on [[hepatitis B]] and [[hepatocellular carcinoma]]; Dean, NTU College of Medicine; Foreign Member, [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]], USA\n*[[Lan-Bo Chen]] (\u9673\u826f\u535a): Professor of Pathology, [[Harvard Medical School]]\n*[[Pei-Jer Chen]], M.D. (\u9673\u57f9\u54f2): authority on [[hepatitis D]] virus; [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]] International Research Scholar; Professor of Medicine, NTU\n*[[Wei-Jao Chen]], M.D. (\u9673\u7dad\u662d): President, NTU, 1993\u20132005; pioneer in surgical separation of ischiopagus tripus [[conjoined twins]]\n*[[Yuan-Tsong Chen]], M.D. (\u9673\u57a3\u5d07): inventor of [[Myozyme]], the first [[European Medicines Agency|EMEA]]- and [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]]-approved treatment for [[Pompe disease]] (approved in 2006); Director, Institute of Biomedical Sciences, [[Academia Sinica]]; former Chief and professor, the Pediatrics Division of Medical Genetics, [[Duke University Medical Center]]\n*[[Yao-Tseng Chen]], M.D.: Professor of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine, [[Weill Cornell Medical College]]\n*[[Yu-Ray Chen]], M.D. (\u9673\u6631\u745e): President, International Society of [[Craniofacial]] Surgery, 1999\u20132000\n*[[Shu Chien]], M.D. (\u9322\u7166): University Professor, [[University of California]]; President, the [[American Physiological Society]], 1990\u20131; President Elect, the [[Biomedical Engineering Society]], USA, 2005-6\n*[[Tuan-Hua David Ho]] (\u8cc0\u7aef\u83ef): ISI ([[Institute for Scientific Information]]) ''highly cited researcher'' in plant and animal science; [[UNESCO]] Professorship, 2004; Director and Distinguished Research Fellow, Institute of Botany, Academia Sinica, 2003\u20132008, Currently a Professor in the Biology Department Washington University in St. Louis.\n*[[Fushih Pan]], PhD: Plastic Surgeon, Developer of the [[MIRA Procedure]]\n*[[Ru-Chih Chow Huang]] (\u9ec3\u5468\u6c5d\u5409): American Women in Science, 1985; Professor of Biology, Johns Hopkins University\n*[[Tao-shih Hsieh]] (\u8b1d\u9053\u6642): Professor of Biochemistry, [[Duke University Medical Center]]\n*[[Su-Ming Hsu]], M.D. (\u8a31\u4e16\u660e): ISI ''highly cited researcher'' in clinical medicine (cited more than 10,000 times between 1981 and 1992); Professor of Pathology, NTU\n*[[Lily Y. Jan]] (\u8449\u516c\u677c): Howard Hughes Medical Institute investigator, Professor of Physiology and Biophysics, [[University of California, San Francisco]]\n*[[Yuh Nung Jan]] (\u8a79\u88d5\u8fb2): Howard Hughes Medical Institute investigator, Professor of Molecular Physiology, University of California, San Francisco\n*[[Selina Chen-Kiang]]: Professor of Microbiology and Immunology, Professor of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine, Weill Cornell Medical College\n* [[George Kuo]], Co-discoverer of [[Hepatitis C]]\n*[[Michael M. C. Lai]], M.D. (\u8cf4\u660e\u8a54): President, [[National Cheng Kung University]], 2007\u20132011; Vice President, Academia Sinica, 2003\u20132007; Distinguished Professor of Molecular Microbiology and Immunology, [[University of Southern California]]; Howard Hughes Medical Institute Investigator, 1990\u20132003\n*[[Chen-Yuan Lee]], M.D. (\u674e\u93ae\u6e90): co-discoverer of bungarotoxin; [[Redi Award]], 1976; Former President, [[International Society on Toxinology]]\n*[[Tun-Hou Lee]] (\u674e\u60c7\u539a): Professor of Virology, [[Harvard School of Public Health]]\n*[[Ching-Hon Pui]], M.D.: Chair, Department of Oncology, [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]; ISI ''highly cited researcher'' in clinical medicine\n*[[Vivian E. Shih]], M.D.: Professor of Neurology, Harvard Medical School\n*[[Ming T. Tsuang]], M.D. (\u838a\u660e\u54f2): University Professor, University of California; Director, Institute of Behavioral Genomics, [[University of California, San Diego]]; Director, Harvard Institute of Psychiatric Epidemiology and Genetics\n*[[Ching-Chung Wang]] (\u738b\u6b63\u4e2d): Professor of Chemistry and Pharmaceutical Chemistry, University of California, San Francisco\n*[[James C. Wang]] (\u738b\u502c): discoverer of [[topoisomerase]]; Chair (1983\u20131985) and Professor (1977\u20132005), Department of Molecular and Cellular Biology, Harvard University\n*[[Judy Chou]] (\u5468\u6167\u6cc9): PH.D. Yale University; Senior Vice President & Head of Biotech, Bayer Pharmaceuticals.\n*[[Tzyy Choou Wu]], M.D.: Professor of Pathology, Professor of Oncology, and Professor of Obstetrics and Gynecology, [[Johns Hopkins Medical Institutions]]; Professor of Molecular Microbiology and Immunology, [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n*[[Jang Yen Wu]] (\u5433\u653f\u5f65): ISI ''highly cited researcher'' in neuroscience; Member, [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]; Senior Schmidt Fellow, Department of Biomedical Science, [[Florida Atlantic University]]\n*[[Fun-Sun Frank Yao]], M.D.: Professor of Clinical Anesthesiology, Weill Cornell Medical College\n\n==Politics==\n*[[Chang Chau-hsiung]], M.D. (\u5f35\u662d\u96c4): vice-chairman, [[People First Party (Republic of China)|People First Party]], 2000\u2013\n*[[Chang Po-ya]] (\u5f35\u535a\u96c5), M.P.H.: Minister of Health, R.O.C., 1979\u20131986\n*General [[Chen Chao-min]], M.B.A. (\u9673\u8087\u654f): Commander-in-Chief, [[Republic of China Air Force|R.O.C. Air Force]], 1998\u20132002; Deputy Defense Minister, R.O.C., 2002\u2013\n*[[Chen Ding-nan]] (\u9673\u5b9a\u5357): Minister of Justice, R.O.C., 2000\u20132005\n*[[Chen Shui-bian]] (\u9673\u6c34\u6241): Mayor of Taipei, 1994\u20131998; President of R.O.C., 2000\u20132008\n*[[Huang Kuo-chang]] (\u9ec3\u570b\u660c): Chairperson of the [[New Power Party]], Taiwan, 2015\u2013\n*[[Sisy Chen|Chen, Sisy]] (\u9673\u6587\u831c): famous talk show host in Taiwan\n*[[Frank Hsieh]] (\u8b1d\u9577\u5ef7): Mayor of [[Kaohsiung]], 1998\u20132005; Premier of R.O.C., 2005\u20132006\n*[[Joe Hung]] (\u6d2a\u5065\u662d): journalist ([[Central News Agency (Taiwan)|Central News Agency]]), translator and diplomat, Representative of Taiwan to Italy, 1993\u20132000<ref name=eyetai>{{cite news|title=Late journalist-diplomat Joe Hung remembered as man of erudition and veracity |url=https://eyeontw.com/archives/4797 |work=[[Eye on Taiwan Media]] |date=6 March 2018 |accessdate=14 March 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314020900/https://eyeontw.com/archives/4797 |archivedate=14 March 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> \n*[[Kao Chia-yu]] (\u9ad8\u5609\u745c): Councillor of the 11th to 13th [[Taipei City Council]]; 14th President of [[National Taiwan University Student Association|NTU Student Association]]\n*[[Lee Teng-hui]] (\u674e\u767b\u8f1d): President of R.O.C., 1988\u20132000\n*[[Lien Chan]] (\u9023\u6230): Vice President of R.O.C., 1996\u20132000\n*[[Lin Yang-kang]] (\u6797\u6d0b\u6e2f): President, [[Judicial Yuan]], R.O.C., 1987\u20131994\n*[[Lin Yi-hsiung]] (\u6797\u7fa9\u96c4): chairman, [[Democratic Progressive Party]], 1998\u20132000\n*[[Annette Lu|Lu, Annette]] (\u5442\u79c0\u84ee): Vice President of R.O.C., 2000\u20132008\n*[[Li Ao]] (\u674e\u6556): A writer, social commentator, historian, independent scholar and politician in the Republic of China (Taiwan).\n*[[Ma Ying-jeou]] (\u99ac\u82f1\u4e5d): President of R.O.C., 2008\u20132016\n*[[Peng Ming-min]] (\u5f6d\u660e\u654f): former Chair and professor, Department of Political Science, NTU; political activist for [[Taiwan independence]]\n*[[Su Tseng-chang]] (\u8607\u8c9e\u660c): Premier of R.O.C., 2006\u20132007\n*[[Shen Fu-hsiung]], M.D. (\u6c88\u5bcc\u96c4): Member, [[Legislative Yuan]], R.O.C., 1992\u20132004; former Associate Professor, [[University of Washington, Seattle]]; former Director, [[Hemodialysis]] Unit, [[Seattle Veterans Administration Hospital]]\n*[[Wu Den-yih]] (\u5433\u6566\u7fa9): Mayor of Kaohsiung, 1990\u20131998; Member, Legislative Yuan, 2002\u2013 ; Secretary-General of the KMT Central Committee, 2007\u2013; Premier of R.O.C., 2009\u2013\n*[[Chen Changwen]]: president of [[Red Cross Society of the Republic of China]] and the secretary of [[Straits Exchange Foundation]].\n\n==Humanitie