\u5e36)\n|\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044438/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241753&v=44] a belt worn by officials<sub>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044624/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pimage.html?s=&i=241753001&en=241753&p_i=&a_i=&e=1 image]</sub>.\n|-\n|[[Gwadae]]\n|\n|ornament [https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044639/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=240977&v=44]\n|-\n|[[Gwanja]] ([[Hangul]]: \uad00\uc790; \u8cab\u5b50)\n|\n|small holes attached to [[manggeon]] (hairband)<!-- \ub9dd\uac74\uc5d0 \ub2ec\uc544 \ub2f9\uc904\uc744 \uac78\uc5b4\ub118\uae30\ub294 \uad6c\uc2e4\uc744 \ud558\ub294 \uc791\uc740 \uace0\ub9ac. --> [http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241767&v=44]<sup>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044755/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pimage.html?s=&i=241767002&en=241767&p_i=&a_i=&e=1 image]</sup>\n|-\n|[[Gwansik]]\n|[[File:\ubb34\ub839\uc655 \uae08\uc81c\uad00\uc2dd.jpg|70px]]\n|an ornament attached to crowns or hats [https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044832/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=244109&v=44]\n|-\n|[[Hyangdae]] ([[Hangul]]: \ud5a5\ub300)\n|\n|Also called a nunmul goreum ([[Hangul]]: \ub208\ubb3c\uace0\ub984). A ribbon worn from the chima of a woman's dress, sometimes embroidered for upper class and sometimes with a tassel used for a handkerchief, especially in mourning.\n|-\n|[[Jumeoni]]\n|[[File:Korea-Bokjumeoni-01.jpg|70px]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610050633/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=249365&v=44]\n|-\n|[[Norigae]]\n|[[File:Korean accessory-Norigae-01.jpg|70px]]\n|pendants [http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp][https://web.archive.org/web/20080423103519/http://english.chosun.com/english/contents/magazine/2001/Shopping200108_1.html][https://web.archive.org/web/20090214161701/http://kccc.ro/Korean_Custome.html]\n|-\n|[[Tteoljam]]\n|[[File:Korean hairpin-Tteoljam-01.jpg|70px]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610045149/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241798&v=44]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20091114025453/http://hair.culturecontent.com/index.asp\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Korean clothing}}\n[[Category:Korean clothing| ]]\n[[Category:Korea-related lists|Clothing]]\n[[Category:Clothing-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Culture of Korea}}\n{{Expand list|date=February 2011}}\nHanbok is a traditional clothing of Korea. \nThis is a list of [[Korea]]n clothing including the national costume, [[hanbok]] as well as [[headgear]], [[footwear]], and accessories.\n\n==[[Hanbok]]==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|'''[[Baji (clothing)|\ubc14\uc9c0 (Baji)]]'''\n|[[File:Korea-Seoul 0589-06 traditional dress.JPG|70px]]\n|baggy pants (see more pictures at [[commons:Category:Baji]])\n|-\n|'''[[Chima (clothing)|\uce58\ub9c8 (Chima)]]'''\n|[[File:Korea-Busan-Beomeosa-04.jpg|70px]]\n|''Chima'' is a type of skirt worn together with ''[[jeogori]]'', short jacket.\n|-\n|'''[[Dangui]]'''\n|[[File:Korean costume-Hanbok-Dangui-Seuranchima-01.jpg|70px]]\n|''Dangui'' is a female upper garment worn for ceremonial occasions during the [[Joseon Dynasty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241781&v=455 |script-title=ko:\ub2f9\uc758 (\u5510\u8863) |publisher=[[Nate (web portal)|Nate]] / [[EncyKorea]] |language=Korean |accessdate=2008-10-28 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610042424/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241781&v=455 |archive-date=2011-06-10 |df= }}</ref> ''Dangui'' was also called ''dang-[[jeogori]]'' ([[Hangul]]: \ub2f9\uc800\uace0\ub9ac), ''dang-jeoksam'' ([[Hangul]]: \ub2f9\uc801\uc0bc), or ''dang-hansam'' ([[Hangul]]: \ub2f9\ud55c\uc0bc).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=B&i=123348&v=45 |script-title=ko:\ub2f9\uc758 (\u5510\u8863) |publisher=[[Nate (web portal)|Nate]] / [[Britannica]] |language=Korean |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610042442/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=B&i=123348&v=45 |archive-date=2011-06-10 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Dopo (clothing)|Dopo]]'''\n|[[File:Interior 1, Unhyeongung - Seoul, Korea.JPG|70px]]\n|''Dopo'' is a variety of [[Po (clothing)|po]] (an overcoat) mostly worn by male [[Confucian]] scholars called [[seonbi]] since the mid Joseon period.\n|-\n|'''[[Durumagi]]'''\n|[[File:APEC2005 Hanbok.jpg|70px]]\n|''Durumagi'' is a lined overcoat worn by men or women with no slit. It is most commonly held closed with a single ''goreum'' \n|-\n|'''[[Garot]]'''\n| [[File:Korea-Jeju-Museum-02.jpg|70px]]\n|Garot is a type of working and everyday dress dyed with juice of unripe [[persimmon]]s. It has been worn by [[Jeju Island]] locals.\n|-\n|'''[[Gwanbok]]'''\n| [[File:Joseon-Portrait of Cha Jegong-Black danryeongpo.jpg|70px]]\n|Gwanbok is a Korean general term referring to all business attires of government officers given by government, with [[Rank badge]] on them to distinguish hierarchies.\n|-\n|'''[[Dragon robe#Korea|Gonryongpo]]'''\n|[[File:Korea-Yeongjo-King of Joseon-c1.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|'''[[Hakchangui]]'''\n|[[File:Korean hanbok-Hakchangui-Waryonggwan.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|'''[[Hwarot]]'''\n|[[File:Korean.costume-Hanbok-wedding.bride-01.jpg|70px]]\n|Hwarot is a type of traditional Korean clothing worn during the Goryeo and Joseon Dynasty by royal women for ceremonial occasions or by commoners for weddings.<ref>\"\ud65c\uc637\" (in Korean). [[Empas]] / [[Britannica]]. Retrieved 2008-09-20.</ref> It originated from the Kingdom of Khotan, Central Asia.<ref>\uae40\uc18c\ud604. \uc6b0\uc804 ( khotan ) \uc758 \ubcf5\uc2dd\uc5d0 \uad00\ud55c \uc5f0\uad6c, \ud55c\uad6d\ubcf5\uc2dd\ud559\ud68c, v. 34, 169-183. 1997.</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Jeogori]]'''\n|[[File:Hanbok-female clothing-01.jpg|70px]]\n|''Jeogori'' is a basic upper garment which has been worn by both men and women. It covers arms and upper part of the wearer's body.\n|-\n|'''[[Jeonbok]]'''\n|[[File:Korean clothing-Hanbok-Jeonbok-01.jpg|70px]]\n|Jeonbok is a type of sleeveless long vest mostly worn by military personnel. It does not have overlapped column on the front side, and was worn over ''[[dongdari]]''.\n|-\n|'''[[Jokki]]'''\n|[[File:Korea-Seoul 0589-06 traditional dress.JPG|70px]]\n|vest\n|-\n|'''[[Kkachi durumagi]]'''\n|[[File:Korean clothing-Hanbok-Obangjang durumagi-01.jpg|70px]]\n|Kkachi durumagi is a children's colorful overcoat worn on [[Korean New Year]]. It was worn over a ''[[jeogori]]'' or ''[[jokki]]'' while the wearer could put a ''[[jeonbok]]'' over it. Kkachi durumagi was also worn along with headgear such as [[bokgeon]], [[hogeon]] or [[gulle]].\n|-\n|'''[[Magoja]]'''\n|[[File:Korean costume-Hanbok-Magoja and baji-01.jpg|70px]]\n|The magoja is a type of long jacket worn with hanbok, the traditional clothing of Korea, and is usually worn on top of the jeogori (short jacket). \n|-\n|'''[[Po (clothing)|Po]]'''\n|[[File:Interior 1, Unhyeongung - Seoul, Korea.JPG|70px]]\n|The po is a generic term referring to an outer robe or overcoat in hanbok.\n|-\n|'''[[Sagyusam]]'''\n|[[File:Korean clothing-Hanbok-Sagyusam-Bokgeon.jpg|70px]]\n|''Sagyusam'' is a type of ''[[po (clothing)|po]]'' (outer robe) worn by young boys until they had a [[coming-of-age]] ceremony called ''[[gwallye]]''. The name was derived from the shape; the lower end of the garment is divided into four parts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfm.go.kr/data/full.cgi?v_db=1&v_doc_no=00000477&v_kw_str=%BB%E7%B1%D4%BB%EF |script-title=ko:\uc0ac\uaddc\uc0bc(\u56db\u63c6\u886b) |publisher=[[National Folk Museum of Korea]] |language=Korean }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Saekdongot]]'''\n|[[File:Korean clothing-Hanbok-Saekdong jeogori-01.jpg|70px]]\n|''Saekdongot'' is any hanbok [[patchwork]]ed with colorful stripes. It began to be made since the [[Goryeo period]] (918 \u2013 1392). The name literally means \"many colored clothing\". It was usually worn by children of the age at one to seven year old. The ''saekdong'' can be applied throughout ''[[jeogori]]'' (short jacket with sash), ''majoja'' (buttoned jacket), ''[[durumagi]]'' (overcoat) or among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://100.empas.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=300001&v=44 |script-title=ko:\uc0c9\ub3d9\uc637 |publisher=[[Empas]] / [[EncyKorea]] |accessdate=2008-09-29 |language=Korean}}</ref><ref name=\"Doosan\">{{cite web |url=http://map.encyber.com/search_w/ctdetail.php?&masterno=88005&contentno=88005 |script-title=ko:\uc0c9\ub3d9\uc800\uace0\ub9ac |publisher=[[Doosan Encyclopedia]] |accessdate=2008-09-29 |language=Korean |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116164017/http://map.encyber.com/search_w/ctdetail.php |archive-date=2006-11-16 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Wonsam]]'''\n|[[File:Korean.costume-Wonsam-for.Queen.Joseon-01.jpg|70px]]\n|''Wonsam'' is a female ceremonial [[Overcoat|topcoat]] during the [[Joseon Dynasty]]. The queen, princess consort, and consort to the first son of the crown prince wore it as a ''soryebok'', a robe for small ceremonies, while wives of high officers and ''sanggung'' (court matrons)  wore it as ''daeryebok'', a robe for major ceremonies. The color and decorations of the garment around the chest, shoulders and back represent the wearer's rank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lifeinkorea.com/culture/clothes/clothes.cfm?xURL=official |title=Official/Court clothing |publisher=Life in Korea}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://100.empas.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=249325&v=42 |script-title=ko:\uc6d0\uc0bc (\u5713\u886b) |publisher=[[Empas]] / [[EncyKorea]] |language=Korean}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Headgear==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|[[Ayam (cap)|Ayam]]\n|[[File:Korean hat-Ayam-01.jpg|70px]]\n|An ayam is a traditional winter [[cap]] mostly worn by women during the Joseon period. It is also called ''aegeom'' meaning \"covering a forehead\". The ayam consists of a crown and trailing big ribbons. The upper part of the crown is finely [[quilt]]ed, and its outer fabric consists of black or purple [[silk]]. While black or dark brown fur is used for the rest of the crown. The fabric for the inner is red cotton flannel. A tassel attached to the upper center of both front and back. Some ayam worn by ''[[kisaeng]]'' (female entertainer) were luxuriously adorned with jewels. The ayam worn for spring and autumn has the same shape as the one for winter, but it is made of a lighter silk.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://russian.tour2korea.com/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp |title=Hanboks(Traditional Clothings) |work=Headgear and Accessories Worn Together with Hanbok |publisher=[[Korea Tourism Organization]] |accessdate=2008-09-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002225735/http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp |archive-date=2013-10-02 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=249310&v=45 |script-title=ko:\uc544\uc58c |publisher=[[Nate (web portal)|Nate]] / [[EncyKorea]] |accessdate=2008-09-16 |language=Korean |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610050645/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=249310&v=45 |archive-date=2011-06-10 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Banggeon]]\n|[[File:Jeon Seon-Taking a reast after reading books-d1.jpg|70px]]\n|Headgear \n|-\n|[[Beonggeoji]]\n|[[File:Korean hat-Jeonnip-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Bokgeon]]\n|[[File:Korea-Portrait of Song Siyeol-Joseon.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Chaek (hat)|Chaek]]\n|[[File:Korean hat-02.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Daesu]]\n|[[File:Korean royal costume for queen-Jeogui and daesu-02.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Gache]]\n|[[File:Miindo-Yun.family.of.Haenam-d1.jpg|70px]]\n|wig\n|-\n|[[Gat (hat)|\uac13 (Gat)]]\n|[[File:Korea-gat-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Gulle]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Gullae-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Hogeon]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Hogeon-01A.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Hwagwan]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Hwagwan-01.jpg|70px]]\n|Hwagwan is a type of Korean coronet worn by women traditionally for ceremonial occasions such as wedding.\n|-\n|[[Ikseongwang]]\n|[[File:Korea-Yeongjo-King of Joseon-c1.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Jangot]]\n|[[File:Korean clothing-Jangot-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Jeongjagwan]]\n|[[File:Korea-Min Sangho-1898-Hubert Vos.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Jeonmo]]\n|[[File:Hanbok-Kisaeng-Hyewon-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Jobawi]]\n|[[File:Korean winter cap-Jobawi-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Jokduri]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Jokduri-01A.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Joujeolpung]]\n|[[File:Korean hat-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Manggeon]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Manggeon and tanggeon-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Nambawi]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Nambawi-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Pungcha]]\n|[[File:Pungcha.jpg|70px]]\n|\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Tanggeon]]\n|[[File:Korea-Yi Chegwan-Portrait of a Confucian scholar.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Tongcheongwan]]\n|[[File:Korean.crown-Tongcheongwan-01v.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Satgat|\uc0bf\uac13 (Satgat)]]\n|[[File:Hyewon-Nojung.sangbong.jpg|70px]]\n|-\n|[[Sseugae chima]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Sseugae chima-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Waryonggwan]]\n|[[File:Korean headgear-Waryonggwan-01.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Yanggwan]]\n|[[File:Korea-Geumgwan Jobok-01.jpg|70px]]\n|Yanggwan was a kind of crown worn by officials when they wore a ''[[jobok]]'' (\u671d\u670d) and ''jebok'' (\u796d\u670d, ceremonial clothing) during the Joseon Dynasty.[https://archive.today/20111005052055/http://hair.culturecontent.com/dress/kwan_man_09.asp]\n|}\n\n==Footwear==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|[[Beoseon]]\n|[[File:Korean sock-Beoseon-01A.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|[[Gomusin]]\n|[[File:Korean shoes-01.jpg|70px]]\n|literally \"rubber shoes\". In present it is mostly worn by elder people and Buddhist monks and nuns [https://web.archive.org/web/20110610043214/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=236485&v=42]\n|-\n|\ud654 ([[Hwa]])\n|[[File:Korean traditional men's winter shoes.jpg|70px]]\n|generic term referring to all kinds of boots\n|-\n|\ud61c [[Hye (shoes)|(Hye]])\n|[[File:Korean traditional shoes-01.jpg|70px]]\n|Varieties: [[Buntuhye]] ([[Hangul]]: \ubd84\ud22c\ud61c), [[taesahye]] ([[Hangul]]: \ud0dc\uc0ac\ud61c), [[danghye]] ([[Hangul]]: \ub2f9\ud61c), [[unhye]] ([[Hangul]]: \uc6b4\ud61c)[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610043509/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=258304&v=43]\n|-\n|\uc9d1\uc2e0 ([[Jipsin]])\n|[[File:\uc9da\uc2e0.jpg|70px]]\n|<!-- description -->\n|-\n|\ubbf8\ud22c\ub9ac [[Mituri|(Mituri]])\n|[[File:\ubbf8\ud22c\ub9ac.jpg|70px]]\n|shoes made of hemp fabric [http://nfm.museum.go.kr/nfm/getDetailArtifact.do?JSON=%7B%22MCSJGBNC%22%3A%22PS01002001001%22%2C%22MCSEQNO1%22%3A%22015982%22%2C%22MCSEQNO2%22%3A%22000%22%2C%22SEARCH_MODES%22%3A%22KEYWORDS%22%2C%22SEARCH_STR%22%3A%22%EB%AF%B8%ED%88%AC%EB%A6%AC%22%7D#]\n|-\n|\ubaa9\ud654 ([[Mokhwa]])\n|\n|a variety of [[hwa]], worn by officials along with [[gwanbok]] (official clothing) during the mid and late Joseon Dynasty.[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610043639/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?i=239589]\n|-\n|\ub098\ub9c9\uc2e0 [[Namaksin|(Namaksin]])\n|[[File:Koreanclogs.JPG|70px]]\n|a type of wooden [[Clog (shoe)|clog]][https://web.archive.org/web/20110610043747/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241776&v=42]\n|}\n\n==Accessories==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|[[Baetssi]]\n|[[File:Korean hair accessory-Baetssi daenggi-01.jpg|70px]]\n|hair ornament for young girls [https://web.archive.org/web/20110610050304/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=242333&v=44]\n|-\n|[[Balhyang]]\n|\n|pendant including incense <!-- \ud5a5\uc744 \ud64d\u00b7\ubc31\u00b7\ub179\u00b7\ud669 \ub4f1 \uc0ac\uc0c9\uc73c\ub85c \ud558\uc5ec \uc2e4\uc5d0 \uaff0\uc5b4 \uc5fc\uc8fc\ubaa8\uc591\uc73c\ub85c \ub9cc\ub4e0 \uac83 -->[http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=242324&v=44]<sup>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610050350/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pimage.html?s=&i=242324001&en=242324&p_i=&a_i=&e=1 image]</sup>\n|-\n|[[Binyeo]] ([[Hangul]]: \ube44\ub140)\n|[[File:Korean hair pin-Binyeo-02.jpg|70px]]\n|a large decorative stick like a hairpin [http://annals.yonsei.ac.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=205][https://web.archive.org/web/20080423103519/http://english.chosun.com/english/contents/magazine/2001/Shopping200108_1.html][http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp][http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2900616][https://books.google.com/books?id=HcsMRc6pbQoC&pg=PA202&lpg=PA202&dq=Binyeo+hair&source=bl&ots=XeCEmynTok&sig=Il0MOPHz4RhnHVMfMbbLpkt3_Y0&hl=en&ei=B56qScTGFNeitgfH85jkDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=9&ct=result#PPA202,M1][https://web.archive.org/web/20090423212820/http://eng.actakoreana.org/clickkorea/text/14-Wedding/14-03spr-traditional.doc][https://web.archive.org/web/20090214161701/http://kccc.ro/Korean_Custome.html]\n|-\n|[[Buchae]]\n|\n|Korean fan [https://web.archive.org/web/20080423103519/http://english.chosun.com/english/contents/magazine/2001/Shopping200108_1.html]\n|-\n|[[Cheopji]] ([[Hangul]]: \ucca9\uc9c0)\n|[[File:Korean hair pin-Cheopji-01.jpg|70px]]\n|a hair pin [http://100.empas.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=258292&v=44][http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp]\n|-\n|[[Chimnang]] ([[Hangul]]: \uce68\ub0ad)\n|\n|pockets for needles<sup>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610050405/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pimage.html?s=&i=263355002&en=263355&p_i=&a_i=&e=1 image]</sup>\n|-\n|[[Daenggi]]\n|[[File:Korean hanbok and daenggi-01.jpg|70px]]\n|[http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp]\n|-\n|[[Donggot]]\n|\n|pin for tying sangtu (men's topnot)<sup>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610050436/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pimage.html?s=&i=241791001&en=241791&p_i=&a_i=&e=1 image]</sup>\n|-\n|[[Dwikkoji]] ([[Hangul]]: \ub4a4\uaf2c\uc9c0)\n|[[File:Korean hairpin-Dwikkoji-01.jpg|70px]]\n|[http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241795&v=44][http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp]{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n|-\n|[[Eunjangdo]]\n|\n|a women's ornamental silver dagger [https://web.archive.org/web/20090214161701/http://kccc.ro/Korean_Custome.html][https://web.archive.org/web/20080423103519/http://english.chosun.com/english/contents/magazine/2001/Shopping200108_1.html]\n|-\n|[[Gakdae]] ([[Hangul]]: \uac01\ub300 \u89d2\u5e36)\n|\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044438/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241753&v=44] a belt worn by officials<sub>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044624/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pimage.html?s=&i=241753001&en=241753&p_i=&a_i=&e=1 image]</sub>.\n|-\n|[[Gwadae]]\n|\n|ornament [https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044639/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=240977&v=44]\n|-\n|[[Gwanja]] ([[Hangul]]: \uad00\uc790; \u8cab\u5b50)\n|\n|small holes attached to [[manggeon]] (hairband)<!-- \ub9dd\uac74\uc5d0 \ub2ec\uc544 \ub2f9\uc904\uc744 \uac78\uc5b4\ub118\uae30\ub294 \uad6c\uc2e4\uc744 \ud558\ub294 \uc791\uc740 \uace0\ub9ac. --> [http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241767&v=44]<sup>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044755/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pimage.html?s=&i=241767002&en=241767&p_i=&a_i=&e=1 image]</sup>\n|-\n|[[Gwansik]]\n|[[File:\ubb34\ub839\uc655 \uae08\uc81c\uad00\uc2dd.jpg|70px]]\n|an ornament attached to crowns or hats [https://web.archive.org/web/20110610044832/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=244109&v=44]\n|-\n|[[Hyangdae]] ([[Hangul]]: \ud5a5\ub300)\n|\n|Also called a nunmul goreum ([[Hangul]]: \ub208\ubb3c\uace0\ub984). A ribbon worn from the chima of a woman's dress, sometimes embroidered for upper class and sometimes with a tassel used for a handkerchief, especially in mourning.\n|-\n|[[Jumeoni]]\n|[[File:Korea-Bokjumeoni-01.jpg|70px]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610050633/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=249365&v=44]\n|-\n|[[Norigae]]\n|[[File:Korean accessory-Norigae-01.jpg|70px]]\n|pendants [http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_1_2.jsp][https://web.archive.org/web/20080423103519/http://english.chosun.com/english/contents/magazine/2001/Shopping200108_1.html][https://web.archive.org/web/20090214161701/http://kccc.ro/Korean_Custome.html]\n|-\n|[[Tteoljam]]\n|[[File:Korean hairpin-Tteoljam-01.jpg|70px]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610045149/http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=241798&v=44]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20091114025453/http://hair.culturecontent.com/index.asp\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Korean clothing}}\n[[Category:Korean clothing| ]]\n[[Category:Korea-related lists|Clothing]]\n[[Category:Clothing-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "LorcanCho", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added descriptions to each headwear entry", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Korean_clothing"}
{"title_page": "The Mandalorian", "text_new": "{{about|the television series|the fictional group of people|Mandalorian|the title character|The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|2019 American ''Star Wars'' live-action television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Mandalorian\n| image                    = The Mandalorian logo.jpg\n| genre                    = [[Space Western]]\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Star Wars]]''|[[George Lucas]]}}\n| creator                  = [[Jon Favreau]]\n| writer                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jon Favreau\n* [[Dave Filoni]]\n* [[Rick Famuyiwa]]\n* [[Christopher Yost]]\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Dave Filoni\n* Rick Famuyiwa\n* [[Deborah Chow]]\n* [[Bryce Dallas Howard]]\n* [[Taika Waititi]]\n}}\n| starring                 = [[Pedro Pascal]]\n| composer                 = [[Ludwig G\u00f6ransson]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!--Only increment as a new season premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| num_episodes             = 8<!--Only increment as a new episode premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Jon Favreau\n* Dave Filoni\n* [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]]\n* [[Colin Wilson (film producer)|Colin Wilson]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greig Fraser]]\n* Barry Idoine\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jeff Seibenick\n* Andrew S. Eisen\n* [[Dana E. Glauberman]]\n}}\n| runtime                  = 31\u201346 minutes\n| location                 = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lucasfilm]]\n* [[Fairview Entertainment]]\n* [[Golem Creations]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Disney Media Distribution]]\n| network                  = [[Disney+]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|11|12}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| website                  = https://disneyplusoriginals.disney.com/show/the-mandalorian\n}}\n'''''The Mandalorian''''', also known as '''''Star Wars: The Mandalorian''''', is an American [[space Western]] [[web television]] series created by [[Jon Favreau]] and released on [[Disney+]]. It is the first [[live action]] series in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' franchise. Set five years after the events of ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'' and 25 years prior to the events of [[Star Wars: The Force Awakens|''The Force Awakens'']], it follows the [[The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)|title character]], the [[Mandalorian]] [[bounty hunter]] Din Djarin, and his exploits beyond the reaches of the [[New Republic (Star Wars)|New Republic]].\n\nFavreau also serves as [[head writer]] and [[showrunner]], as well as [[Television producer#Executive producer|executive producer]], alongside [[Dave Filoni]], [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]], and [[Colin Wilson (film producer)|Colin Wilson]]. ''The Mandalorian'' premiered with the launch of Disney+ on November 12, 2019, with its eight-episode first season. The series has received positive reviews.\n\nA second season has been ordered, which is set to premiere in October 2020.\n\n==Synopsis==\n{{quote|After the stories of [[Jango Fett|Jango]] and [[Boba Fett]], another warrior emerges in the ''Star Wars'' universe. ''The Mandalorian'' is set after the [[Star Wars: Return of the Jedi|fall of the Empire]] and before the [[Star Wars: The Force Awakens|emergence of the First Order]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Charlie|title=Mandalorian is making sense of the time between Return of Jedi and Force Awakens|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/18/21026895/mandalorian-episode-7-recap-timeline-return-of-jedi-force-awakens|website=Polygon|date=December 18, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219150605/https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/18/21026895/mandalorian-episode-7-recap-timeline-return-of-jedi-force-awakens|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Brett|title=Does \u2018Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker\u2019 Connect to \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019?|url=https://decider.com/2019/12/20/does-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-connect-to-the-mandalorian/|website=Decider|date=December 20, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221141124/https://decider.com/2019/12/20/does-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-connect-to-the-mandalorian/|archive-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Katz|first1=Brandon|title=\u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Creator Opens Up About Baby Yoda and \u2018Star Wars\u2019 Crossovers|url=https://observer.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-baby-yoda-star-wars-crossovers/|website=Observer|date=December 5, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228172821/https://observer.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-baby-yoda-star-wars-crossovers/|archive-date=December 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pometsey|first1=Olive|title=Everything you need to know about The Mandalorian|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/culture/article/the-mandalorian|website=GQ Magazine|date=December 9, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122113411/https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/culture/article/the-mandalorian|archive-date=November 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The series depicts a lone bounty hunter in the outer reaches of the galaxy far from the authority of the [[New Republic (Star Wars)|New Republic]].<ref name=\"TitlePremise\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/star-wars-jon-favreau-series-the-mandalorian-boba-fett-1202475775/ |title=Jon Favreau Unveils Details For His ''Star Wars'' Live-Action Streaming Series ''The Mandalorian'' |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=October 3, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=October 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222080706/https://deadline.com/2018/10/star-wars-jon-favreau-series-the-mandalorian-boba-fett-1202475775/ |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>|[[Jon Favreau]]}}\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{{main|List of The Mandalorian characters}}\n=== Starring ===\n* [[Pedro Pascal]] as [[The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)|Din Djarin / The Mandalorian]], a lone gunfighter and bounty hunter who is sometimes referred to as \"Mando\" (a generic term used to refer to all [[Mandalorian]]s, a clan of skilled warriors). He is a \"foundling\" who was rescued at a young age by Mandalorians during [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|the Clone Wars]]. Pascal has described his character as [[Clint Eastwood]]\u2013esque with advanced combat skills and of \"questionable moral character\".<ref name=IG11 /> \n* \"[[The Child (Star Wars)|The Child]]\" (performed by various [[puppeteer]]s), a member of [[Yoda's species|the same unnamed species]] as the powerful [[Jedi master]] [[Yoda]] with similar [[The Force|Force abilities]]. The Child is a toddler at age 50. A bounty is offered for his return by \"[[The Client (Star Wars)|The Client]]\". He is found and protected by the Mandalorian while being targeted by other bounty hunters.\n\n=== Co-starring ===\nThe following actors received co-starring billing in the main end credits of the episodes they appeared in:\n* [[Carl Weathers]] as [[Greef Karga]], an ex-[[magistrate]] and leader of a bounty hunter guild who hires the Mandalorian to track a valuable asset.<ref name=space />\n* [[Werner Herzog]] as \"[[The Client (Star Wars)|The Client]],\" an unnamed man with Stormtrooper bodyguards who arranges for the Mandalorian to track a valuable asset.<ref name=DeadlineCast />\n* [[Omid Abtahi]]<ref name=DeadlineCast /> as [[Dr. Pershing]], a scientist working for \"the Client\".\n* [[Nick Nolte]] as the voice of [[Kuiil]], an [[Ugnaught]] moisture farmer who bought his freedom after being enslaved by the Empire.<ref name=DeadlineCast /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-new-character-posters/ |title=''The Mandalorian'' releases 5 new character photos |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=October 28, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=October 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030210746/https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-new-character-posters/ |archive-date=October 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Misty Rosas provided the [[motion capture]] performance of Kuiil.<ref>{{cite podcast |last1=Rosas |first1=Misty |last2=Ballance |first2=Brian |url=https://soundcloud.com/theinterestingpodcast/ep-108-misty-rosas |publisher=The Interesting Podcast |title=Ep. 108 Misty Rosas |date=January 21, 2020 |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kain |first=Erik |title=Star Wars 'The Mandalorian' Episode 7 Recap And Review: 'The Reckoning' Is The Best Episode Yet |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/12/18/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-7-recap-and-review-the-best-episode-yet/#abd12ef70788 |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222175408/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/12/18/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-7-recap-and-review-the-best-episode-yet/#abd12ef70788 |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Taika Waititi]] as the voice of [[IG-11]],<ref name=IG11 /> a bounty-hunting [[Droid (Star Wars)|droid]] who processes conversations in a precise and literal manner.<ref name=ew /> After attempting to kill \"the Child\" as its bounty, and being stopped by Djarin, IG-11 is re-programmed by Kuiil to protect the toddler.<!--ADD WHEN A SOURCE CAN BE FOUND Rio Hackford provides the motion-capture for IG-11.-->\n* [[Gina Carano]] as [[Cara Dune]], a former rebel shock trooper-turned-mercenary from the now destroyed planet of [[Alderaan]] who fought in the [[Galactic Civil War]] for the [[Rebel Alliance]]/[[New Republic (Star Wars)|New Republic]].<ref name=\"space\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.space.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-what-we-know.html |title=''The Mandalorian'': Here's What We Know So Far About the ''Star Wars'' Live Action Show |last=Snowden |first=Scott |date=May 2, 2019 |website=Space.com |access-date=May 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502162656/https://www.space.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-what-we-know.html |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Amy Sedaris]] as [[Peli Motto]], a cantankerous docking bay attendant and ship mechanic on [[Tatooine]].\n* [[Jake Cannavale]] as [[Toro Calican]], a fledgling bounty hunter looking to join the bounty hunters\u2019 guild by capturing Fennec Shand. He hires the Mandalorian to help.\n* [[Ming-Na Wen]] as [[Fennec Shand]], an assassin who crosses paths with the Mandalorian.<ref name=\"Fennec\">{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/ming-na-wen-the-mandalorian-star-wars-fennec-shand |title=First Look: Ming-Na Wen's Star Wars Assassin From The Mandalorian |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |author-link=Anthony Breznican |date=November 4, 2019 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |magazine= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123011358/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/ming-na-wen-the-mandalorian-star-wars-fennec-shand |archive-date=November 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Wen />\n* [[Mark Boone Junior]] as [[Ranzar Malk|Ranzar \"Ran\" Malk]], an aging mercenary and leader of a motley crew looking to free a prisoner on a New Republic ship. Malk is a former associate of the Mandalorian from before he joined the guild.\n* [[Bill Burr]] as [[Mayfeld]], a former Imperial sharpshooter and the point man on Malk's crew.\n* [[Natalia Tena]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Xi'an|Xi'an]], a [[Twi'lek]] member of Malk's crew and knife master, who claims to be Djarin's former love interest.\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Burg|Burg]], a large Devaronian member of Malk's crew who serves as the muscle of the team.\n* [[Richard Ayoade]] as the voice of [[Q9-0]], also known as \"Zero\", a droid member of Malk's crew.<!--ADD WHEN A SOURCE CAN BE FOUND Chris Bartlett provides the motion-capture for Q9-0.-->\n* [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Qin|Qin]], a Twi'lek and Xi'an's brother. He has a combative past with the Mandalorian.\n* [[Giancarlo Esposito]] as [[Moff Gideon]], a former officer of the Imperial Security Bureau, the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]]'s [[secret police]], whose life changed after the Rebel Alliance/New Republic destroyed the second [[Death Star]].<ref name=\"ew\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/05/inside-the-mandalorian-star-wars/ |title=''The Mandalorian'' unmasked: 'We did things no ''Star Wars'' fan has ever seen' |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=September 5, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905185539/https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/05/inside-the-mandalorian-star-wars/ |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Emily Swallow]] as [[The Armorer (Star Wars)|The Armorer]],<ref name=DeadlineCast /><ref name=\"BabyYoda\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/the-mandalorians-emily-swallow-on-the-armorers-secrets-and-the-baby-yoda-puppet |title=The Mandalorian's Emily Swallow on the Armorer's secrets and the Baby Yoda puppet |last=Silliman |first=Brian |date=November 27, 2019 |website=[[Syfy Wire]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224092134/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/the-mandalorians-emily-swallow-on-the-armorers-secrets-and-the-baby-yoda-puppet |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> a Mandalorian woman who forges armor and equipment from Beskar steel, and enforces tradition among the surviving Mandalorians.\n\n=== Guests ===\n<!-- ONLY NAMED CHARACTERS HERE. USE THE EPISODES' ARTICLES TO LIST THE FULL GUEST CAST, INCLUDING UNNAMED CHARACTERS. -->\n====Season 1====\n<!-- 104 -->\n* [[Julia Jones]] as [[Omera]],<ref name=Julia /> a widowed farmer on [[Sorgan]] who provides lodging for the Mandalorian during his stay on the planet.<ref name=\"credits104\">{{Cite episode |title=Chapter 4: Sanctuary |series=The Mandalorian |network=[[Disney+]] |date=November 29, 2019 |season=1 |number=4}}</ref>\n* Isla Farris as [[Winta (Star Wars)|Winta]], Omera's daughter who bonds with the Child during his stay on the planet.<ref name=\"credits104\" />\n* Asif Ali as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Caben and Stoke|Caben]], a farmer on Sorgan who, with his friend Stoke, asks the Mandalorian to protect his village against the attacks of Klatooinian raiders.<ref name=\"credits104\" />\n* [[Eugene Cordero]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Caben and Stoke|Stoke]], a farmer on Sorgan.<ref name=\"credits104\" />\n<!-- 105 -->\n* Rio Hackford as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Riot Mar|Riot Mar]], a bounty hunter who engages the Mandalorian in a dogfight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-latest-mandalorian-had-maybe-a-little-too-much-fan-1840243870 |title=The Latest Mandalorian Had Maybe a Little Too Much Fan Service for Its Own Good |last=Lussier |first=Germain |date=December 6, 2019 |website=[[io9]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220220429/https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-latest-mandalorian-had-maybe-a-little-too-much-fan-1840243870 |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<!-- 106 -->\n* [[Matt Lanter]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Davan|Davan]], a New Republic soldier.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schedeen |first1=Jesse |title=The Mandalorian Cast: Every Character and Cameo From Season 1 So Far |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/14/the-mandalorian-cast-cameos-celebrity-who-was-in-episode |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214215728/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/14/the-mandalorian-cast-cameos-celebrity-who-was-in-episode |archive-date=December 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lanter had previously voiced [[Darth Vader|Anakin Skywalker]] in ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' and ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]''.\n* [[Dave Filoni]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Trapper Wolf|Trapper Wolf]], a New Republic X-wing pilot.\n* [[Rick Famuyiwa]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Jib Dodger|Jib Dodger]], a New Republic X-wing pilot.\n* [[Deborah Chow]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Sash Ketter|Sash Ketter]], a New Republic X-wing pilot.\n\n[[Horatio Sanz]] played a [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Mythrol|Mythrol]] bounty,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a29786836/horatio-sanz-brian-posehn-the-mandalorian/ |title=Comedians Horatio Sanz and Brian Posehn Made Sneaky Cameos in the First Episode of The Mandalorian |last=Romano |first=Evan |date=November 13, 2019 |website=[[Men's Health]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128064743/https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a29786836/horatio-sanz-brian-posehn-the-mandalorian/ |archive-date=November 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Brian Posehn]] played a speeder pilot in \"[[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/60855-the-mandalorian-star-wars-brian-posehn-cameo |title=Yes, that is Brian Posehn from 'Sarah Silverman' in 'The Mandalorian' |last=Franciscov |first=Eric |date=November 12, 2019 |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |access-date=December 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222225540/https://www.inverse.com/article/60855-the-mandalorian-star-wars-brian-posehn-cameo |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Series creator [[Jon Favreau]] voiced [[Paz Vizla]], an infantry Mandalorian featured in \"[[Chapter 3: The Sin]]\", physically played by stunt double Tait Fletcher.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/11/22/star-wars-the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-cameo/ |title=Star Wars: Did The Mandalorian Feature a Jon Favreau Cameo? |last=Cavanaugh |first=Patrick |date=November 23, 2019 |website=ComicBook.com |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127172705/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/11/22/star-wars-the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-cameo/ |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Adam Pally]] and [[Jason Sudeikis]] played two bike scout troopers in \"[[Chapter 8: Redemption]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/the-mandalorian-spoilers-darksaber-jason-sudeikis-and-adam-pally/ |title=The Mandalorian spoilers: Darksaber, Jason Sudeikis, and Adam Pally |last=DeVault |first=Ryan |date=December 27, 2019 |website=[[Monsters and Critics]] |access-date=December 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227124329/https://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/the-mandalorian-spoilers-darksaber-jason-sudeikis-and-adam-pally/ |archive-date=December 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, members of the [[501st Legion]] fan organization were used as [[Stormtrooper (Star Wars)|stormtrooper]] extras.<ref name=space /><ref>{{Cite_web|url=https://geektyrant.com/news/heartwarming-story-about-how-501st-legion-came-to-appear-in-the-mandalorian|title=Heartwarming Story About How 501st Legion Came to Appear in The Mandalorian|publisher=geektyrant|last=Fisher|first=Jessica|date=April 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Baver |first1=Kristin |title=SWCC 2019: 9 Things We Learned From The Mandalorian Panel |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |website=StarWars.com |accessdate=December 29, 2019 |date=April 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415024016/https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |archive-date=April 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Season 2====\n* [[Michael Biehn]] as a bounty hunter<ref name=\"BiehnCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mandalorian-casts-terminator-star-michael-biehn-1286284|title='The Mandalorian' Casts 'Terminator' Star Michael Biehn|last=Couch|first=Aaron|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Rosario Dawson]] as [[Ahsoka Tano]], a former [[Jedi|Jedi Padawan]] of [[Anakin Skywalker]] turned spymaster for the [[Rebel Alliance]].<ref name=\"DawsonMandalorian\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/rosario-dawson-ahsoka-tano-the-mandalorian-season-2-1203540472/|title=Rosario Dawson to Play Ahsoka Tano in \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2|last=Thorne|first=Will|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n=== Season 1 (2019) ===\n{{Episode table |background=#C4A574 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = [[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Dave Filoni]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Jon Favreau]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|12}}\n |ShortSummary    = Five years after the fall of the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]]<ref name=\"mccl\">{{Cite magazine |url=https://time.com/5717734/mandalorian-star-wars-timeline/ |title=How ''The Mandalorian'' Fits Into the Larger ''Star Wars'' Timeline |last=McCluskey |first=Megan |date=November 12, 2019 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124055630/https://time.com/5717734/mandalorian-star-wars-timeline/ |archive-date=November 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> a [[Mandalorian]] [[bounty hunter]] hands his latest bounty to [[Greef Karga]]. Then he accepts an under-the-table commission on the outpost world of [[List of Star Wars planets and moons#Nevarro|Nevarro]] from an enigmatic [[The Client (Star Wars)|client]] with apparent Imperial connections, directing him to track down and capture an unnamed fifty-year-old target. While the Client is indifferent to the target's well-being, his colleague [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Dr. Pershing|Dr. Pershing]] insists the target be brought back alive. The Mandalorian is given a down payment of a single bar of [[Beskar steel]], sacred to his people. He takes it to a covert Mandalorian enclave where an [[The Armorer (Star Wars)|armorer]] uses it to make him a [[pauldron]]. Arriving at the planet of the target's last reported location, the Mandalorian is aided by a vapor farmer named [[Kuiil]]. Tired of the chaos that bounty hunters bring to the area, Kuiil leads him to the target's location and departs. Entering the remote and heavily defended encampment, the Mandalorian reluctantly teams up with bounty hunting droid [[IG-11]] to clear the camp and find the quarry: a [[The Child (Star Wars)|child]] of [[Yoda's species]]. When IG-11 attempts to kill the infant per its bounty orders, the Mandalorian shoots and destroys the droid, taking the Child alive.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = [[Chapter 2: The Child]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Rick Famuyiwa]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|15}}\n |ShortSummary    = While returning to his ship with the Child, the Mandalorian fights and kills a group of rival bounty hunters who ambush him. Nearing his ship, he finds it being stripped by [[Jawa (Star Wars)|Jawas]] for parts, and violently confronts them. When he tries to attack their [[sandcrawler]], the Jawas stun him and drop him from its roof. The following day, Kuiil helps him locate the Jawas and negotiate for the return of his ship's components. The Mandalorian agrees to retrieve the egg of a rhinoceros-like Mudhorn in exchange for the stolen parts. He enters the Mudhorn's cave only to be hurled out by the angry beast inside, which attacks him repeatedly, damaging his armor. As the Mudhorn rushes in for the kill, the Child uses [[the Force]] to levitate the beast, allowing the surprised Mandalorian to stab and kill it. He collects the egg and takes it to the Jawas, who crack it open and eat its yellow insides. With the trade complete, the Mandalorian and Kuiil work together to repair the ship, allowing the Mandalorian to leave the planet with the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = [[Chapter 3: The Sin]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Deborah Chow]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|22}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian delivers the Child to the Client on Nevarro and collects the bounty of 20 bars of Beskar steel. Uncharacteristically, the Mandalorian asks about the Client's plans for the Child, but is told that it's none of his concern. He leaves before conflict arises. Returning to the Mandalorian enclave, the Mandalorian has his damaged armor replaced and weapons upgraded by the Armorer, who forges a full [[cuirass]] from most of the Beskar steel, while the remainder goes to support Mandalorian foundling children. The Mandalorian accepts a new job from Greef Karga and prepares his ship to depart. Feeling guilty for abandoning the Child to the Empire, he turns back to attack the Client's base, killing most of the stormtroopers guarding it. He rescues the Child from Dr. Pershing's laboratory where it was being experimented on, but chooses not to kill the doctor. On the way back to his ship, the Mandalorian is ambushed by other bounty hunters and Greef Karga, who demand that he hand over the Child. He refuses, and a firefight breaks out. Outnumbered and cornered, the Mandalorian is able to escape only when other Mandalorians arrive from the enclave, attacking the bounty hunters and allowing him to reach his ship with the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = [[Chapter 4: Sanctuary]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Bryce Dallas Howard]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|29}}\n |ShortSummary    = Arriving on the sparsely populated forest planet [[List of Star Wars planets and moons#Sorgan|Sorgan]], the Mandalorian encounters ex-Rebel shock trooper-turned-mercenary [[Cara Dune]]. Following a short brawl, Dune explains that she is hiding after taking \"early retirement\", and asks the Mandalorian to leave. While he prepares his ship, two desperate fishermen approach, offering to hire him to drive off a band of [[List of Star Wars species|Klatoonian]] raiders. He accepts the job in exchange for lodging, using their credits to enlist Dune's help. At the village, they are housed by [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Omera|Omera]], a widowed mother. The Mandalorian confides in her that no one has seen him without his helmet since childhood, when his tribe took him in as an orphan. Despite discovering that the raiders have an old Imperial [[AT-ST]], the villagers refuse to leave, so the Mandalorian and Dune train them to defend themselves. They provoke the raiders at night, with Dune luring the AT-ST into a trap for the Mandalorian to blow up and forcing the remaining raiders to flee. With peace restored, the Mandalorian plans to leave the Child in the village, but a Guild bounty hunter tracks it down and is killed by Dune. Realizing that neither the village nor the Child would be safe, the Mandalorian departs with the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = [[Chapter 5: The Gunslinger]]\n |DirectedBy      = Dave Filoni\n |WrittenBy       = Dave Filoni\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|6}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian defeats a pursuing bounty hunter in a [[dogfight]]. He lands his damaged ship at a nearby repair dock, run by mechanic [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Peli Motto|Peli Motto]] in [[Mos Eisley]] on [[Tatooine]]. He seeks work in a cantina to pay for the repairs, meeting aspiring bounty hunter [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Toro Calican|Toro Calican]], who is tracking elite mercenary and assassin [[Fennec Shand]]. Calican needs to catch Shand to join the Guild, and the Mandalorian agrees to help when Calican offers to let him keep the money. They capture Shand in the desert, but she destroys one of their speeder bikes, so the Mandalorian goes to get a [[List of Star Wars species|dewback]] they passed for transportation. While Calican watches Shand, she tells him that the Mandalorian betrayed the guild, making the bounty on him and the Child worth more than hers. Shand offers to help Calican capture the Mandalorian if he sets her free, but he shoots her instead and rides the remaining speeder bike to the repair dock, taking Motto and the Child hostage. The Mandalorian arrives, uses a [[flare]] to disorient Calican, and kills him. He takes Calican's money to pay Motto for the repairs, thanking her before leaving Tatooine. Out in the desert, a mysterious figure approaches Shand's body.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = [[Chapter 6: The Prisoner]]\n |DirectedBy      = Rick Famuyiwa\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=[[Christopher Yost]] |t=Christopher Yost and Rick Famuyiwa}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|13}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian contacts his former partner [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Ranzar Malk|\"Ran\" Malk]] for work. Ran welcomes him to his space station and informs the Mandalorian that he needs his ship for a five-man job. He is joined by ex-Imperial sharpshooter [[Mayfeld]], [[Devaronian]] strongman [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Burg|Burg]], droid pilot [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Q9-0|Q9-0]], and [[Twi'lek]] knife-expert [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Xi'an|Xi'an]] for a mission to rescue Xi'an's brother [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Qin|Qin]], a prisoner of the New Republic. After infiltrating the prison ship, they fight through security droids and make it to the control room where the ship's security chief triggers a security beacon before being killed by Xi'an. The crew rescues Qin but double-crosses the Mandalorian. He escapes and defeats each crew member, then captures Qin. Q9-0 finds the Child after deciphering the archived transmission from Greef Karga, but is shot by the Mandalorian before he can harm him. The Mandalorian delivers Qin to Ran and departs with his payment. Ran immediately moves to launch a fighter to kill the Mandalorian, but discovers the New Republic beacon had been placed on Qin, leading a trio of [[X-wing fighter|X-wings]] to Ran's station where they attack. In the final scene, Mayfeld, Burg, and Xi'an are revealed to be locked in a cell on the prison transport, having been spared by the Mandalorian.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = [[Chapter 7: The Reckoning]]\n |DirectedBy      = Deborah Chow\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|18}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian receives a message from Greef Karga, whose town on Nevarro has been overrun by ex-Imperial troops led by the Client. Karga proposes that the Mandalorian use the Child as bait in order to kill the Client and free the town. In return, Karga will square things with the Guild, which would allow the Mandalorian and the Child to live in peace. Sensing a trap, the Mandalorian recruits Cara Dune and Kuiil to assist him, and Kuiil brings a rebuilt and reprogrammed IG-11 to protect the Child. They meet Karga and his associates, but are attacked by [[Mynock]]s. Karga is injured, but the Child uses the Force to heal his wound. In return, Karga kills his associates and confesses his original plan to shoot the Mandalorian and take the Child to the Client. Karga pretends that Dune has captured the Mandalorian, while Kuiil returns the Child to the ship. During the meeting, [[Moff Gideon]]'s troops open fire on the building and kill the Client and his bodyguards, trapping the Mandalorian, Karga, and Dune inside. Gideon arrives, demanding the Child. In the desert, two scout troopers intercept the Mandalorian's communications and track Kuiil, killing him and taking the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = [[Chapter 8: Redemption]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Taika Waititi]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = IG-11 rescues the Child from the scout troopers. Gideon warns Karga, Dune, and the Mandalorian that they face certain death unless they agree to assist him. IG-11 arrives and breaks the standoff but Gideon injures the Mandalorian. The Child uses the Force to deflect an attacking stormtrooper's flamethrower back on him. The Mandalorian sends the others through a sewer grate with the Child to find help from the Mandalorian enclave, while IG-11 removes his helmet to tend to a head injury. Joining the others, the Mandalorian finds the covert group of Mandalorians dead or escaped, except for the Armorer. She tasks him to care for the foundling Child like his own, discover its origins, and return it to its kind. The Armorer fashions the Mandalorian his own signet and gives him a jetpack. The group is ferried down an underground lava river, but when they are ambushed by stormtroopers, IG-11 self-destructs to eliminate the enemy. Gideon attacks in a [[TIE fighter]] and the Mandalorian uses the jetpack to bring the craft down, but the Moff survives and cuts himself out of the ship with the [[Darksaber (fictional weapon)|Darksaber]].<!-- The inclusion of the Darksaber in this plot summary, and the accompanying efn citation, were the result of a a consensus and compromise reached after an extensive talk page discussion. Please do not remove or modify it without seeking a new consensus. -->{{efn|Actor Giancarlo Esposito, as well as Lucasfilm's official ''Star Wars'' website, have identified the weapon as the Darksaber,<ref>{{cite news |last=Lash |first=Jolie |title=The Mandalorian Season 2: Giancarlo Esposito Offers Clue on Why Moff Gideon Wants Baby Yoda |work=[[IGN]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorian-season-2-moff-gideon-baby-yoda-darksaber |accessdate=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121054150/https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorian-season-2-moff-gideon-baby-yoda-darksaber |archive-date=January 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Knox0211\">{{cite news |last=Knox |first=Kelly |title=What is the Darksaber? |work=[[Star Wars|StarWars.com]] |publisher=[[Lucasfilm]] |date=February 11, 2020 |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/what-is-the-darksaber |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221195525/https://www.starwars.com/news/what-is-the-darksaber |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> a Mandalorian lightsaber that has appeared previously in [[List of Star Wars television series#Animated series|''Star Wars'' animated series]].<ref name=\"Knox0211\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5756064/mandalorian-finale-darksaber/|title=The Darksaber Made a Crucial Appearance in ''The Mandalorian''{{'s}} Season Finale. Here's Its Significance in ''Star Wars'' Lore|last=Dockterman|first=Eliana|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=December 28, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105085326/https://time.com/5756064/mandalorian-finale-darksaber/|archivedate=January 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/the-mandalorian-finale-recap-black-lightsaber|title=''The Mandalorian'' Season Finale: What is the Darksaber?|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|author-link=Anthony Breznican|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=December 27, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200111175049/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/the-mandalorian-finale-recap-black-lightsaber|archivedate=January 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}} The Mandalorian leaves with the Child, while Karga and Dune stay behind.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n}}\n\n==== Notes ====\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n=== Season 2=== <!-- Per WP:TVUPCOMING, do NOT add a year until an episode has been released. Thank you! -->\nFamuyiwa,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://discussingfilm.net/2019/08/21/rick-famuyiwa-set-to-direct-episodes-of-the-mandalorian-season-2-exclusive |title=Rick Famuyiwa Set To Direct Episodes Of \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2 (EXCLUSIVE) |date=August 21, 2019 |website=Discussing Film |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321062633/https://discussingfilm.net/2019/08/21/rick-famuyiwa-set-to-direct-episodes-of-the-mandalorian-season-2-exclusive |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Favreau, Filoni, and [[Carl Weathers]] will direct episodes in the season.<ref name=\"S2FilmingWrap\" /> The season will premiere in October 2020.<ref name=\"S2Premiere\" />\n\n== Production ==\n=== Background ===\nA live-action ''Star Wars'' TV series entered production in early 2009, with over 50 scripts written by 2012, but they were deemed too expensive to produce due to their complex content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://denofgeek.com/movies/rick-mccallum/21562/rick-mccallum-interview-dennis-potter-star-wars-tv-series-george-lucas-red-tails |title=Rick McCallum interview: Dennis Potter, Star Wars TV series, George Lucas & Red Tails |last=Peaty |first=James |date=June 3, 2012 |website=[[Den of Geek]] |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819171150/http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/rick-mccallum/21562/rick-mccallum-interview-dennis-potter-star-wars-tv-series-george-lucas-red-tails |archive-date=August 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Its title was to have been ''[[Star Wars: Underworld]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2012/01/09/is-this-the-star-wars-live-action-shows-title |title=Is This the ''Star Wars'' Live-Action Show's Title? |last=Collura |first=Scott |date=January 9, 2012 |website=IGN |access-date=March 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228085206/http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/01/09/is-this-the-star-wars-live-action-shows-title |archive-date=February 28, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2013, following the October 30, 2012 sale of [[Lucasfilm]] to [[The Walt Disney Company]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC television network]] president [[Paul Lee (television executive)|Paul Lee]] spoke to the current status of the series commenting that \"We'd love to do something with Lucasfilm, we're not sure what yet. We haven't even sat down with them. We're going to look at [the live-action series], we're going to look at all of them, and see what's right. We weren't able to discuss this with them until [the acquisition] closed and it just closed. It's definitely going to be part of the conversation.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/2013/01/10/star-wars-live-action-tv-series-3/ |title=ABC to look at 'Star Wars' live-action TV series |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=January 10, 2013 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714170844/http://www.ew.com/article/2013/01/10/star-wars-live-action-tv-series-3/ |archive-date=July 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2014, more details regarding the series were revealed, including that [[Boba Fett]] would have appeared.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/06/cancelled-star-wars-underworld-tv-series-would-have-featured-young-versions-of-han-chewie-lando-84952/ |title=Cancelled 'Star Wars: Underworld' TV Series Would Have Featured Young Versions Of Han, Chewie & Lando |last=Lyttelton |first=Oliver |date=June 11, 2014 |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004144928/https://www.indiewire.com/2014/06/cancelled-star-wars-underworld-tv-series-would-have-featured-young-versions-of-han-chewie-lando-84952/ |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Jon Favreau 2016.jpeg|thumb|upright|Jon Favreau initially pitched the idea for ''The Mandalorian''.]]\nIn 2019, Jon Favreau revealed to ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' that he had first pitched the idea for what became ''The Mandalorian'' to Kennedy during the summer of 2017, while directing the photorealistic remake of ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]'' for [[Walt Disney Pictures]].<ref name=\"Keegan\">{{cite news |last1=Keegan |first1=Rebecca |title=In Baby Yoda, Hollywood Sees Its Past, Present and Meme-able Future |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/baby-yoda-represents-past-present-future-hollywood-1263588 |accessdate=December 29, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=December 19, 2019 |location=Los Angeles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230193122/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/baby-yoda-represents-past-present-future-hollywood-1263588 |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Kennedy put Favreau in touch with Filoni, and when the two men met, Filoni began to draw doodles on napkins of what would become The Child.<ref name=\"Keegan\" />  After each day of work on ''The Lion King's'' virtual reality set in [[Playa Vista, Los Angeles|Playa Vista]], Favreau would then stay late and work a few more hours developing his secret television project for Lucasfilm.<ref name=\"Keegan\" />\n\nOn November 9, 2017, Walt Disney Company chairman and CEO [[Bob Iger]], while on a quarterly earnings call with investors, announced that Disney and Lucasfilm were developing a new live-action ''Star Wars'' television series for Disney's [[Disney+|then-unnamed upcoming streaming service]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-live-action-series-launch-disney-streaming-service-1056755 |title='Star Wars' Live-Action TV Series to Launch on Disney Streaming Service |last=Stanhope |first=Kate |last2=Jarvey |first2=Natalie |date=November 9, 2017 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005072112/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-live-action-series-launch-disney-streaming-service-1056755 |archive-date=October 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/biz/news/star-wars-tv-series-disney-streaming-service-1202611408/ |title=New 'Star Wars' Trilogy in Works With Rian Johnson, TV Series Also Coming to Disney Streaming Service |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=November 9, 2017 |website=Variety |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6ush9b0jh?url=http://variety.com/2017/biz/news/star-wars-tv-series-disney-streaming-service-1202611408/ |archive-date=November 10, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 6, 2018, it was reported that Iger had revealed during another financial report conference call with investors that multiple ''Star Wars'' live-action series were actually in development by Disney saying, \"We are developing not just one, but a few ''Star Wars'' series specifically for the Disney direct-to-consumer app. We've mentioned that and we are close to being able to reveal at least one of the entities that is developing that for us. Because the deal isn't completely closed, we can't be specific about that. I think you'll find the level of talent ... on the television front will be rather significant as well.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-tv-series-disney-developing-a-few-streaming-service-1082523 |title='Star Wars' TV Series: Disney Developing \"a Few\" for Its Streaming Service |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |last2=Couch |first2=Aaron |date=February 6, 2018 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004202538/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-tv-series-disney-developing-a-few-streaming-service-1082523 |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2018, Lucasfilm announced that Favreau was the writer and executive producer of the forthcoming series.<ref name=\"FavreauWrite\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/08/iron-man-filmmaker-jon-favreau-will-create-a-star-wars-tv-series/ |title='Iron Man' filmmaker Jon Favreau will create a live-action 'Star Wars' series |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=March 8, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005112016/https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/08/iron-man-filmmaker-jon-favreau-will-create-a-star-wars-tv-series/ |archive-date=October 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2018, Favreau stated that half of the scripts for the first season had been completed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/jon-favreau-star-wars-tv-series-details-exclusive-nerdist-news/ |title=Exclusive Details on Jon Favreau's STAR WARS TV Series {{!}} Nerdist |last=Marnell |first=Blair |date=May 11, 2018 |website=[[Nerdist]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512022354/https://nerdist.com/jon-favreau-star-wars-tv-series-details-exclusive-nerdist-news/ |archive-date=May 12, 2018 |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comingsoon.net/tv/news/945169-jon-favreau-confirms-setting-script-status-of-star-wars-series |title=Jon Favreau Confirms Setting, Script Status of Star Wars Series |last=Evry |first=Max |date=May 11, 2018 |website=[[ComingSoon.net]] |access-date=August 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718050935/http://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/945169-jon-favreau-confirms-setting-script-status-of-star-wars-series |archive-date=July 18, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 3, Favreau announced that the series had been titled ''The Mandalorian'' and revealed the show's central premise.<ref name=\"TitlePremise\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-jon-favreau-tv-the-mandalorian-1202968077/ |title='Star Wars': Jon Favreau Reveals TV Series Details |last=Holloway |first=Daniel |date=October 3, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=October 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004021613/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-jon-favreau-tv-the-mandalorian-1202968077/ |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following day, it was revealed that additional executive producers would include [[Dave Filoni]], [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]], and [[Colin Wilson (film producer)|Colin Wilson]] with Karen Gilchrist acting as a co-executive producer. Filoni was also expected to direct the series' first episode with additional directors including [[Taika Waititi]], [[Bryce Dallas Howard]], [[Rick Famuyiwa]], and [[Deborah Chow]].<ref name=\"Directors\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-the-mandalorian-directors-first-look-1202969766/ |title=Bryce Dallas Howard, Taika Waititi, and More to Direct 'Star Wars' Live-Action TV Series |last=Stedman |first=Alex |date=October 4, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=October 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005030117/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-the-mandalorian-directors-first-look-1202969766/ |archive-date=October 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 19, StarWars.com announced that [[Ludwig G\u00f6ransson]] would compose the musical score for the series.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/19/black-panther-composer-ludwig-goransson-star-wars-mandalorian/ |title='Black Panther' composer Ludwig G\u00f6ransson will write music for 'The Mandalorian' |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=December 19, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=December 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220015829/https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/19/black-panther-composer-ludwig-goransson-star-wars-mandalorian/ |archive-date=December 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ludwig Goransson to Compose Score for the Mandalorian |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/ludwig-goransson-to-compose-score-for-the-mandalorian |publisher=Star Wars |accessdate=3 March 2020 |date=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 12, 2019, during a press conference for ''The Lion King'' remake, Favreau revealed that he had written scripts for the second season and that pre-production was underway.<ref name=\"Season2\">{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-mandalorian-season-2-filming-jon-favreau |title=Exclusive: Jon Favreau Says He's Already Writing and Pre-Shooting 'The Mandalorian' Season 2 |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=July 12, 2019 |website=[[Collider]] |access-date=July 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712193523/http://collider.com/the-mandalorian-season-2-filming-jon-favreau/ |archive-date=July 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Favreau plans to direct an episode of the second season, and stated that he was too busy with the production of ''The Lion King'' to direct any of the series' first season.<ref name=\"plans\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/09/jon-favreau-mandalorian-season-2/ |title=Jon Favreau plans to direct a 'Mandalorian' season 2 episode himself |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=September 9, 2019 |website=EW.com |access-date=September 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913224159/https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/09/jon-favreau-mandalorian-season-2/ |archive-date=September 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an interview with [[Pedro Pascal]], The Mandalorian's name was revealed to be \"Din Djarin\".<ref name=\"Mandalorian Name\">{{Cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-real-name-confirmed-dyn-jarren/ |title=The Mandalorian's Real Name Revealed |last=Zinski |first=Dan |date=November 13, 2019 |website=[[Screen Rant]] |access-date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113194128/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-real-name-confirmed-dyn-jarren/ |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nBy November 2018, Pascal, [[Gina Carano]], and [[Nick Nolte]] had been cast in starring roles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/star-wars-pedro-pascal-mandalorian-series-1203023818/ |title=''Star Wars'': Pedro Pascal to Lead ''The Mandalorian'' Series |last=Kroll |first=Justin |last2=Otterson |first2=Joe |date=November 13, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=November 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114000343/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/star-wars-pedro-pascal-mandalorian-series-1203023818/ |archive-date=November 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-pedro-pascal-talks-disney-streaming-series-1202501235/ |title=''The Mandalorian'' Targets Pedro Pascal For Title Role In Disney+ Series |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |date=November 13, 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=November 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113232557/https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-pedro-pascal-talks-disney-streaming-series-1202501235/ |archive-date=November 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gina-carano-joins-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1160809 |title=''Star Wars'': Gina Carano Joins 'The Mandalorian' |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=November 14, 2018 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=November 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115112924/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gina-carano-joins-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1160809 |archive-date=November 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/nick-nolte-joins-pedro-pascal-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1164696 |title='Star Wars': Nick Nolte Joins Pedro Pascal in 'The Mandalorian' (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=November 30, 2018 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201003051/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/nick-nolte-joins-pedro-pascal-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1164696 |archive-date=December 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> After meeting with Favreau, Pascal initially thought he would be playing Boba Fett.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/09/15/star-wars-the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-thought-boba-fett/ |title=Star Wars: Pedro Pascal Thought He Was Playing Boba Fett in The Mandalorian |last=Schmidt |first=JK |date=September 14, 2019 |website=comicbook.com |access-date=September 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916063850/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/09/15/star-wars-the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-thought-boba-fett/ |archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 12, 2018, LucasFilm announced that [[Giancarlo Esposito]], [[Carl Weathers]], [[Emily Swallow]], [[Omid Abtahi]], and [[Werner Herzog]] had joined the main cast.<ref name=\"DeadlineCast\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/star-wars-the-mandaloriancast-disney-favreau-jedi-pascal-pedro-1202518897/ |title=''Star Wars: The Mandalorian'' Casting: Giancarlo Esposito, Carl Weathers and Werner Herzog Join Disney+ Series |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |date=December 12, 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213021650/https://deadline.com/2018/12/star-wars-the-mandaloriancast-disney-favreau-jedi-pascal-pedro-1202518897/ |archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 21, 2019, [[Taika Waititi]] was revealed to be recording a voice for the series, speculated to be bounty hunter droid [[IG-88]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/22/star-wars-it-looks-like-taika-waititi-is-ig-88-in-the-mandalorian |title=''Star Wars'': It Looks Like Taika Waititi Is IG-88 in ''The Mandalorian'' |last=Stevens |first=Colin |date=March 21, 2019 |website=IGN |access-date=March 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322030405/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/22/star-wars-it-looks-like-taika-waititi-is-ig-88-in-the-mandalorian |archive-date=March 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> but which turned out to be a new character named IG-11.<ref name=\"IG11\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/the-mandalorian-star-wars-celebration/ |title=The Mandalorian is described as Clint Eastwood in Star Wars |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=April 14, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414231148/https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/the-mandalorian-star-wars-celebration/ |archive-date=April 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Footage shown at [[Star Wars Celebration#Celebration Chicago|''Star Wars'' Celebration]] in April 2019 revealed that [[Bill Burr]] and [[Mark Boone Junior]] were in the series, with Burr portraying an outlaw.<ref name=\"BurrBoone\">{{Cite news |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/secret-footage-the-mandalorian/ |title=Here's what happened in the secret footage of ''The Mandalorian'' |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=April 14, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=April 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416053035/https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/secret-footage-the-mandalorian/ |archive-date=April 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[D23 Expo]] in August, it was revealed [[Ming-Na Wen]] would appear in the series.<ref name=\"Wen\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-ming-na-wen-joins-the-cast-of-the-disney-star-wars-series |title=The Mandalorian: Ming-Na Wen Joins the Cast of the Disney+ Star Wars Series |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |date=August 23, 2019 |website=[[IGN]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220180730/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-ming-na-wen-joins-the-cast-of-the-disney-star-wars-series |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Julia Jones]]'s casting was announced in September.<ref name=\"Julia\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-mandalorian-twilight-saga-actress-joins-cast-of-disney-live-action-star-wars-series-1202713442/ |title='The Mandalorian': Julia Jones Joins Cast of Disney+ Live-Action 'Star Wars' Series |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |last2=Boucher |first2=Geoff |date=September 6, 2019 |access-date=September 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906032029/https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-mandalorian-twilight-saga-actress-joins-cast-of-disney-live-action-star-wars-series-1202713442/ |archive-date=September 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, [[Rosario Dawson]] was reported to be appearing as [[Ahsoka Tano]] in the second season, which would be the character's first live-action on-screen appearance. Having previously appeared in the ''Star Wars'' animated media ''The Clone Wars'' ([[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|film]] and [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|television series]]) and ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]'', Ahsoka's voice was briefly heard in the live-action film ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]''; she was voiced by [[Ashley Eckstein]] in these appearances.<ref name=\"DawsonMandalorian\">{{cite web |last=Sciretta |first=Peter |title=Star Wars Exclusive: \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2 Casts Rosario Dawson as Ahsoka Tano |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/rosario-dawson-ahsoka-mandalorian/|website=[[/Film]] |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320174731/https://www.slashfilm.com/rosario-dawson-ahsoka-mandalorian/|archivedate=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Shortly after, [[Michael Biehn]] joined the cast as a bounty hunter.<ref name=\"BiehnCast\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\nPrincipal photography for the first season began during the first week of October 2018 in [[Southern California]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-star-wars-tv-series/ |title=''The Mandalorian'': Directors, First Photo, Details & More Revealed for Jon Favreau's ''Star Wars'' TV Series |last=Sciretta |first=Peter |date=October 4, 2018 |website=[[/Film]] |access-date=October 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004115434/https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-star-wars-tv-series/ |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 19, [[George Lucas]] visited the set of the series as a birthday surprise for Favreau;<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-mandalorian-set-photo-george-lucas/ |title=George Lucas Visits ''The Mandalorian'' Set in New Behind-the-Scenes Photo |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=October 19, 2018 |website=Collider |access-date=October 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020015520/http://collider.com/the-mandalorian-set-photo-george-lucas/ |archive-date=October 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> it was later revealed that Lucas had some level of involvement in creating the show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-mandalorian-filming-details-giancarlo-esposito/ |title='The Mandalorian' Actor Giancarlo Esposito Describes the New Technology Used on the 'Star Wars' Show |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=April 18, 2019 |website=Collider |access-date=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422214859/http://collider.com/the-mandalorian-filming-details-giancarlo-esposito/ |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 25, it was reported that police were investigating the grand theft of several unspecified items from ''The Mandalorian''{{'s}} set at the Manhattan Beach Studios campus in [[Manhattan Beach, California]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grand-theft-investigated-at-studio-hosting-high-profile-projects-1154992 |title=Grand Theft Investigated at Studio Hosting ''Star Wars'' TV Show 'The Mandalorian' |last=Parker |first=Ryan |date=October 25, 2018 |access-date=October 26, 2018 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026010951/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grand-theft-investigated-at-studio-hosting-high-profile-projects-1154992 |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-set-theft-investigation/ |title=''Star Wars'': Police Investigating Theft On ''Mandalorian'' Set |last=Agar |first=Chris |date=October 25, 2018 |access-date=October 26, 2018 |website=[[Screen Rant]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026055443/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-set-theft-investigation/ |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming for the first season wrapped on February 27, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-mandalorian-disney-wraps-filming-on-jon-favreaus-star-wars-tv-show/ |title=''The Mandalorian'': Disney+ Wraps Filming on Jon Favreau's 'Star Wars' TV Show |last=Baysinger |first=Tim |date=February 27, 2019 |access-date=February 27, 2019 |last2=Mass |first2=Jennifer |website=The Wrap}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Favreau, the first season was filmed on a large soundstage with a 360-degree [[video wall]] at Manhattan Beach Studios, supplemented by limited [[location shooting]] around Southern California.<ref name=\"Giardina\">{{cite news |last1=Giardina |first1=Carolyn |title=Why Jon Favreau Chose Baby Yoda: \"We Don't Know a Lot of Details About His Species\" |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=December 5, 2019 |location=Los Angeles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206084030/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The show sent camera crews to shoot distant locations like Iceland and Chile, the resulting digital assets were integrated into virtual sets built with the [[Unreal Engine|Unreal]] game engine from [[Epic Games]], and those sets were displayed on the video wall.<ref name=\"Giardina\" /> In Favreau's words: \"So, there is real photography being incorporated, but the actors aren't brought on location. The location is brought to the actors.\"<ref name=\"Giardina\" />\n\n[[Dave Filoni]], who is mostly renowned for his work on other ''Star Wars'' projects, and [[Bryce Dallas Howard]] were given individual freedom on directing their episodes, which was surprising to Howard's father [[Ron Howard]], who directed ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''.<ref>{{Citation |title=Bryce Dallas Howard's 'So Awesome' Experience Directing on \"The Mandalorian\" from IMDb at Toronto International Film Festival (2017-) |url=http://www.imdb.com/list/ls090647824/videoplayer/vi2661596953 |access-date=December 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911101432/https://www.imdb.com/list/ls090647824/videoplayer/vi2661596953 |archive-date=September 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> When Pascal would become unavailable for filming, the Mandalorian would occasionally be portrayed physically by stunt actors Brendan Wayne and [[Lateef Crowder dos Santos|Lateef Crowder]] with Wayne having worked closely with Pascal to develop the character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-double-stunt-performer.html|title=So, Who's Really Under the Mandalorian's Helmet?|last=Miller|first=Liz Shannon|date=December 9, 2019|website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|access-date=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209223508/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-double-stunt-performer.html|archive-date=December 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFilming for the second season started in mid-October 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2482786/the-mandalorian-season-2-has-already-begun-filming|title=The Mandalorian Season 2 Has Already Begun Filming|last=Hurley|first=Laura|work=Cinema Blend|date=October 21, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> and concluded on March 8, 2020.<ref name=\"S2FilmingWrap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-season-2-directors-include-dave-filoni/|title=\u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2 Bringing Back Dave Filoni to Direct Again|last=Anderton|first=Ethan|publisher=[[/Film]]|date=March 8, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Visual effects ===\nVisual effects studio [[Industrial Light & Magic]], a subsidiary of Lucasfilm, opened a new division in November 2018 targeted for streaming and episodic television called ILM TV. Based in London with support from the company's locations in San Francisco, Vancouver, and Singapore, it is expected that the new division will work extensively on live-action ''Star Wars'' television series, starting with ''The Mandalorian''.<ref name=\"ILMTV\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/artisans/news/george-lucas-star-wars-ilm-launches-tv-unit-1203022007/ |title=ILM Launches TV Unit to Serve Episodic and Streaming Content |last=Caranicas |first=Peter |date=November 7, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=November 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116072921/https://variety.com/2018/artisans/news/george-lucas-star-wars-ilm-launches-tv-unit-1203022007/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Unreal Engine 4]], a [[game engine]] developed by [[Epic Games]], is used to create the digital backgrounds. It makes the rendering of the visual effects faster than would normally be possible for a live-action series, and Favreau said the technology can be applied to a variety of challenges. So rather than using sketches on a whiteboard to map out scenes, the storyboarding was done on the game engine.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2019-07-26/disneys-lion-king-remake-is-a-hit-its-virtual-reality-technology-could-change-how-movies-are-made |title='The Lion King's' VR helped make a hit. It could also change movie making |date=July 26, 2019 |website=Los Angeles Times |access-date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729221049/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2019-07-26/disneys-lion-king-remake-is-a-hit-its-virtual-reality-technology-could-change-how-movies-are-made |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/jon-favreau-confirms-season-two-mandalorian-already-pre-production-2806291 |title=Jon Favreau Confirms Season Two Of 'The Mandalorian' Is Already In Pre-Production |last=Billings |first=Kevin |date=July 12, 2019 |website=International Business Times |access-date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729144244/https://www.ibtimes.com/jon-favreau-confirms-season-two-mandalorian-already-pre-production-2806291 |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/20/21145671/mandalorian-sets-stagecraft-epic-games-ilm-fortnite-baby-yoda-digital | title = How The Mandalorian teamed up with Fortnite creator Epic Games to create its digital sets | first=  Chaim | last =Gartenberg | date = February 20, 2020 | accessdate = February 20, 2020 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nThe music for ''The Mandalorian'' is composed by [[Ludwig G\u00f6ransson]]. Each chapter has its own soundtrack album, released the same day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-1-original-score/1486687329 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 1 (Original Score) |date=November 12, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204020906/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-1-original-score/1486687329 |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-2-original-score/1487534284 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 2 (Original Score) |date=November 15, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204080227/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-2-original-score/1487534284 |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-3-original-score/1488169340 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 3 (Original Score) |date=November 22, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127214544/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-3-original-score/1488169340 |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-4-original-score/1489004142 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 4 (Original Score) |date=November 29, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204020838/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-4-original-score/1489004142 |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-5-original-score/1489518198 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 5 (Original Score) |date=December 6, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206132926/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-5-original-score/1489518198 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-6-original-score/1490621791 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 6 (Original Score) |date=December 13, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213120731/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-6-original-score/1490621791 |archive-date=December 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-7-original-score/1491415764 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 7 (Original Score) |date=December 18, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219113655/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-7-original-score/1491415764 |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-8-original-score/1492195968 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 8 (Original Score) |date=December 27, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227233406/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-8-original-score/1492195968 |archive-date=December 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> For the score, G\u00f6ransson played many of the key instruments himself, and then added a 70-piece orchestra. He wrote four hours of music for the eight episodes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burlingame |first1=Jon |title=Composer Takes Music for the \u2018Star Wars\u2019 Series \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 to a New Universe |url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/star-wars-mandalorian-music-1203402950/ |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |publisher=Variety |date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217184801/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/star-wars-mandalorian-music-1203402950/ |archive-date=December 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n===Parenting and fatherhood===\nOne of the primary themes of ''The Mandalorian'' is [[parenting]] and [[Father|fatherhood]], particularly through the father-son relationship dynamic between the Mandalorian and the Child.<ref name=\"Britt1129\">{{cite news |last=Britt |first=Ryan |title=Baby Yoda, Daddy Mando, and How Star Wars Gave Parents a New Fantasy |work=[[Fatherly]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.fatherly.com/play/baby-yoda-star-wars-the-mandalorian-adults/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Singer1213\">{{cite news |last=Singer |first=Matt |title='The Mandalorian' Is A Good Show About How Hard It Is to Be a Single Parent |work=[[Townsquare Media#Web publications and services|ScreenCrush]] |date=December 13, 2019 |url=https://screencrush.com/the-mandalorian-episode-6-recap-single-dad/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Chase1216\">{{cite news |last=Chase |first=Eileen |title=Why The Mandalorian is, in fact, a show about a single dad |work=[[Today (American TV program)|Today]] |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://community.today.com/parentingteam/post/why-the-mandalorian-is-in-fact-a-show-about-a-single-dad |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Ryan Britt of ''[[Fatherly]]'' wrote that this is unusual in ''Star Wars'' stories, and that past examples of parenting in the franchise have tended to be poor ones, from the murderous [[Darth Vader]] (father of [[Luke Skywalker]]) to the neglectful [[List of Star Wars characters#Galen Erso|Galen Erso]], father of [[Jyn Erso]] in ''[[Rogue One]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> Britt wrote: \"For years the Star Wars franchise avoided depicting a parent-child dynamic. With Mando and Baby Yoda, that's finally changing.\"<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> The dynamic between Kuiil and IG-11 also reflect the childrearing theme in ''The Mandalorian''. The two have a relationship similar to that of a father and son, as demonstrated in the scene in which Kuiil teaches IG-11 how to operate and function after the droid is reprogrammed.<ref name=\"Phipps1218\">{{cite news |last=Phipps |first=Keith |title=''The Mandalorian'' Recap: Bait and Switch (and Switch) |work=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-recap-chapter-7-the-reckoning.html |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219022023/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-recap-chapter-7-the-reckoning.html |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' writer Kathryn VanArendonk argued that parenting has been the subject of past ''Star Wars'' stories, but almost always during later stages of parenthood, rather than an infant in early stages such as the Child. As examples, she cited [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] serving as a mentor to the adolescent Anakin Skywalker, [[Princess Leia]] lamenting over her grown son [[Kylo Ren]], or the absence of [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]]'s parents.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\">{{cite news |last=VanArendonk |first=Kathryn |title=''The Mandalorian'' Doesn\u2019t Care About Diapers |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=January 3, 2020 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/the-mandalorian-parenting-fatherhood-archetype.html |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Britt argued strong parental examples in ''Star Wars'' are important because the franchise is so often associated with the childhoods of its fans.<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> ''The Mandalorian'' particularly highlights the challenges of being a [[single parent]],<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /><ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> and a [[working parent]], as the Mandalorian struggles to continue his day job as a bounty hunter and mercenary while serving as the sole caretaker of the Child.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /><ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> Richard Newby of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' described the show as \"the adventures of a single dad looking for a job\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Newby |first=Richard |title=How 'The Mandalorian' Is Setting Up the Long Game |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 14, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/why-mandalorian-episode-5-didnt-include-mysterious-figure-1262747 |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Several reviewers have compared the dynamic between the Child and the Mandalorian to ''[[Lone Wolf and Cub]]'', a [[manga]] about a [[samurai]] warrior and his young son.<ref>{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Hannah |title=Somali and the Forest Spirit Will Fill The Mandalorian Hole in Your Life |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=January 4, 2020 |url=https://www.cbr.com/somali-and-the-forest-spirit-the-mandalorian-comparison/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pierce-Bohen |title=5 Westerns & 5 Samurai Movies To Watch If You Love The Mandalorian |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 23, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-westerns-samurai-movies-similar/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |title=How The Mandalorian's Plot Twist Evokes a Classic Manga Series |work=[[IGN]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/12/the-mandalorian-plot-twist-lone-wolf-and-cub |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Housman |first=Andrew |title=The Mandalorian: How the Series Takes Star Wars Back to Its Samurai Roots |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 20, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-lone-wolf-and-cub-influence/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Mandalorian's parental role in the series makes him a softer and more relatable character;<ref>{{cite news |last=Frank |first=Allegra |title=Baby Yoda: the Mandalorian's adorable alien co-star, explained |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/11/23/20972511/baby-yoda-meme-the-mandalorian-gif-star-wars |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> he changes in a positive way because of raising the Child, becoming less selfish and self-absorbed.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> He risked his life and drastically changed his career as a bounty hunter to accept his responsibility as the Child's caretaker and guardian,<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /><ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> marking a significant parental sacrifice.<ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> When the Mandalorian seeks work to earn money, he is now doing so to provide not only for himself, but for the Child as well.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> We see several examples of the Mandalorian parenting the Child throughout the series, such as when he stops the Child from pressing random buttons in the cockpit of the Mandalorian's spaceship, ultimately by holding him in his lap.<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> In another example, the Mandalorian establishes a [[car seat]] for the Child in the cockpit of his ship, so he can be seated safely and comfortably during their travels.<ref name=\"Atkin1230\">{{cite news |last=Atkin |first=Jessie |title=5 Reasons The Witcher Geralt Will Be a Better Dad Than the Mandalorian (& 5 Reasons He Won't) |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 30, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/5-reasons-the-witcher-geralt-will-be-a-better-dad-than-the-mandalorian-5-reasons-he-wont/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe relationship between the Mandalorian and the Child is an example of unexpected fatherhood.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /><ref name=\"Pereira1129\">{{cite news |last=Pereira |first=Sergio |title=The Mandalorian Is Basically Big Daddy in Space |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-big-daddy-in-space/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> The Mandalorian feels a connection and parental bond with the Child because of his own childhood, when he was orphaned upon the death of his parents and was adopted by the Mandalorian culture as a \"foundling\".<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> Nevertheless, fatherhood was not a role the Mandalorian was initially seeking, and he makes repeated initial attempts to avoid this responsibility.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> He first does so in \"Chapter 3: The Sin\", when he first leave the Child with the Client.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> He does so again in \"Chapter 4\" Sanctuary\", when he plans to leave the Child with Omera, a protective mother on the planet Sorgan, who is willing to take the Child into her own family.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> The Mandalorian does not fully commit to the role of fatherhood until the first-season finale, \"Chapter 8: Redemption\", when the Child himself is also adopted into the Mandalorian culture as a \"foundling\" and the Mandalorian is formally declared to be his father figure.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" />\n\nSeveral writers suggested the fact that the Mandalorian's face is concealed has a [[tabula rasa]] effect and his anonymity allows viewers to see and imagine themselves as parents.<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /><ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> Britt said this \"allow(s) us to dream about what arsenal we might deploy to protect our children\".<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> However, Singer said the show's setting in space make the challenges of child-rearing seem more exciting and exotic than they might otherwise be.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> Anthony Breznican of ''Vanity Fair'' has noted that none of the day-to-day difficulties of parenthood are portrayed in the series: \"There is no shrill squawking from Baby Yoda, no tantrum, no spit-up, no uncontrollable shrieking that burrows into a parent's psyche like a dentist's drill shredding a soft, pink nerve.\"<ref name=\"Breznican1126\">{{cite news |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |title=Baby Yoda Has Conquered the World |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 26, 2019 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127163301/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Likewise, ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' writer Kathryn VanArendonk said the show ignores or does not address many parenting details that make fatherhood difficult, such as what the Child eats, when he goes him to sleep, and whether he wears diapers. She wrote: \"''The Mandalorian'' is uninterested in diapers, and so Mando gets to be a very particular image of fatherhood: the guy who doesn't have to sweat the small stuff.\"<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> VanAnderonk described this as a [[wish fulfillment]] fantasy for parents or prospective parents: \"a vision of parenting stripped so thoroughly of all detail and specificity that all that's left are archetypes: the parent, the child\".<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" />\n\nThe Child encounters a handful of other protector figures throughout the first season, including Omera, IG-11, and Peli Motto.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> Some observers have criticized the series for the fact that the Mandalorian repeatedly leaves the Child alone or in the hands of relative strangers,<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> as well as for making decisions that place the Child in danger. One example is in \"Chapter 6: The Prisoner\", when he allows a team of dangerous mercenaries to use his ship while the Child is on board, nearly resulting in the Child's death.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /><ref name=\"White1218\">{{cite news |last=White |first=Brett |title=Is Baby Yoda Bad to the Bone? This Week's 'The Mandalorian' Has Us Wondering |work=[[New York Post|Decider]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://decider.com/2019/12/18/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-evil/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> An interaction the Mandalorian has with Peli Motto in \"Chapter 5: The Gunslinger\" is one of the most overt discussions about the challenges of caring for the Child. When the Mandalorian accidentally wakes the child, who had been sleeping in Peli's arms, she chides him: \"Do you have any idea how long it took me to get it to sleep?\"<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> She also condemns the Mandalorian for leaving the child alone on the ship, saying: \"you have an awful lot to learn about raising a young one\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Keane |first=Sean |title=The Mandalorian episode 5 recap: Baby Yoda travels to an iconic planet |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 7, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-5-the-gunslinger-recap-baby-yoda-travels-to-an-iconic-planet/ |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Townsquare Media#Web publications and services|ScreenCrush]]'' writer Matt Singer argued the Mandalorian's parenting errors makes the show that much more appealing because making mistakes is a large part of being a parent.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> Eileen Chase of ''[[Today (American TV program)|Today]]'' echoed this: \"He is not an ideal parent, just like the rest of us who have to balance parenting and work.\"<ref name=\"Chase1216\" />\n\n===Good and evil; nature versus nurture===\nThe nature of good and evil and the question of [[nature versus nurture]] is raised repeatedly throughout ''The Mandalorian'', perhaps most overtly through by Kuiil's reprogramming of IG-11 from a bounty hunter to a nurse droid and protector. <ref name=\"Phipps1227\">{{cite news |last=Phipps |first=Keith |title=''The Mandalorian'' Season Finale Recap: Tragedy of the Manufacturer's Protocol |work=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-season-1-finale-recap-episode-8-redemption.html |accessdate=January 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230211122/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-season-1-finale-recap-episode-8-redemption.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Milner1222\">{{cite news |last=Milner |first=Sarah Bea |title=The Mandalorian: Baby Yoda Learns About Good & Bad In A Powerful Way |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 22, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-makes-statement-nature-versus-nurture/ |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223125659/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-makes-statement-nature-versus-nurture/ |archive-date=December 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Even after IG-11 is reprogrammed, the Mandalorian does not believe he has truly changed, because he believes droids have an essential nature and that IG-11's nature remains murderous and untrustworthy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Libbey |first=Dirk |title=The Mandalorian: 6 Biggest Questions After Episode 8 |work=CinemaBlend |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2487459/the-mandalorian-6-biggest-questions-after-episode-8 |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227204600/https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2487459/the-mandalorian-6-biggest-questions-after-episode-8 |archive-date=December 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> But in reprogramming IG-11, Kuiil nurtures him and helps him to change; Kuiil feels that in the process of learning how to function again, IG-11 gained a new personality.<ref>{{cite news |last=Babu |first=Armaan |title='The Mandalorian': IG-11 and Kuiil's inspiring and heartwarming story deserves its own spinoff |work=Media Entertainment Arts WorldWide |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://meaww.com/the-mandalorian-ig-11-kuiil-deserves-its-own-spinoff-star-wars-disney-396037 |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Kuiil insists to the Mandalorian: \"Droids are not good or bad \u2014 they are neutral reflections of those who program them.\"<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /> Keith Phipps of ''[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]]'' wrote of IG-11 and the nature versus nurture theme: \"He's not bad. He's just programmed that way, and with care and change he can do a lot of good in the world.\"<ref name=\"Phipps1227\" />\n\nThe Kuiil and IG-11 scenes also demonstrate that the way in which the \"child\" character is raised makes a significant difference in whether the child becomes an asset or a threat to those around him. The droid was a dangerous assassin before Kuiil reprogrammed him, but thanks to the Ugnaught's parenting, he becomes a protector and helper instead.<ref name=\"Phipps1218\" /> Some writers have likewise suggested the Child is not inherently good or evil,<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Foy1221\" /> but that instead, like all children, he is impressionable and does not fully understand the events occurring around him. He is learning about the world around him and needs guidance as he develops his abilities.<ref name=\"White1218\" /><ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Burwick1219\">{{cite news |last=Burwick |first=Kevin |title=Baby Yoda Might Be Evil in The Mandalorian, Is He Wielding the Dark Side of the Force? |work=TVweb |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://tvweb.com/baby-yoda-evil-the-mandalorian-dark-side-force/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> It will largely fall to the Mandalorian to provide this guidance,<ref name=\"White1218\" /> as when the Mandalorian stops him from strangling Cara Dune.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" />\n\nHowever, multiple writers have questioned whether the violent acts the Child has repeatedly witnessed throughout ''The Mandalorian'' are having a negative impact on his development, and that he is learning to become violent himself as a result.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> Phipps wrote of this: \"That look of wonder in the Child's eyes as IG-11 kills and kills again is hilarious, but also a little chilling.\"<ref name=\"Phipps1227\" /> One particular scene in \"Chapter 7: The Reckoning\" led many reviewers and fans to question whether the Child may be demonstrating [[evil]] tendencies. During a scene on the Mandalorian's spaceship, the Child observes as the Mandalorian and Cara Dune engage in a friendly [[arm wrestling]] match. During the contest, the Child uses the Force to choke Cara, nearly strangling her before the Mandalorian intervened.<ref name=\"Foy1221\">{{cite news |last=Foy |first=Peter |title=The Mandalorian: Could Baby Yoda Actually Be... [Spoiler]? |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=December 21, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-actually-evil/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Burwick1219\" /><ref name=\"Gallagher1226\">{{cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Caitlin |title=Is Baby Yoda Evil On 'The Mandalorian'? The Force Choke Means He Could Join The Dark Side |work=[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]] |date=December 26, 2019 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/is-baby-yoda-evil-on-the-mandalorian-the-force-choke-means-he-could-join-the-dark-side-19629941 |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> Throughout the ''Star Wars'' franchise, that ability has been most commonly associated with the Dark Side of the Force, particularly Darth Vader.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /><ref name=\"Hibberd1218\" /><ref name=\"Miller1218\" />\n\nSarah Bea Milner of ''Screen Rant'' wrote: \"The moment is genuinely shocking \u2014 and more than a little disturbing.\"<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /> Some reviewers noted, however, that the Child likely mistakenly believed the Mandalorian was in danger and intervened to help.<ref name=\"Miller1218\">{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Matt |title=We Regret to Inform You Baby Yoda Might Be Evil |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a30272695/evil-baby-yoda-force-choke-the-mandalorian-episode-7/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Hedash1219\">{{cite news |last=Hedash |first=Kara |title=Wait... Is Baby Yoda Tempted By The Dark Side? |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-force-choke-dark-side/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, in the same episode, the Child uses Force healing to save Greef Karga, a power typically associated with the Light Side.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Foy1221\" /><ref name=\"Hedash1219\" /> Nevertheless, some writers have suggested viewers had been underestimating the Child's capacity for evil because he is so adorable.<ref name=\"Miller1218\" /><ref name=\"Hibberd1218\">{{cite news |last=Hibberd |first=James |title=What if Baby Yoda is secretly evil? |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/18/evil-baby-yoda/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Abdulbaki0106\">{{cite news |last=Abdulbaki |first=Mae |title='Mandalorian' Season 2 theory links Baby Yoda to a Dark side icon |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=January 6, 2020 |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/62121-mandalorian-season-2-theory-baby-yoda-prophecy-anakin-skywalker |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> Fans speculated the Child could be presenting a false personality or using the Force to manipulate people into caring about him to help ensure his survival.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> However, Caitlin Gallagher of ''[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]]'' suggested rather than building toward making the Child evil, the show could be suggesting the Mandalorian needs to find a way to raise the Child in a less violent environment.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" />\n\n== Marketing ==\nOn October 4, 2018, the first promotional image from the series was released, featuring a Mandalorian with a rifle.<ref name=\"Directors\" /> About a week later, Favreau released a photo through his official Instagram account featuring a rifle with a two-pronged barrel, an apparent callback to Boba Fett's weapon in ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mashable.com/article/star-wars-mandalorian-holiday-special-boba-fett-blaster/#21yD0UDQ1Oq6 |title=Jon Favreau's upcoming 'Star Wars' TV series nods to the infamous 'Holiday Special' |last=Rosenberg |first=Adam |date=October 13, 2018 |website=[[Mashable]] |access-date=October 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014155925/https://mashable.com/article/star-wars-mandalorian-holiday-special-boba-fett-blaster/#21yD0UDQ1Oq6 |archive-date=October 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-rifle-from-the-mandalorian-is-a-blast-from-star-war-1829729845 |title=The Rifle From The Mandalorian Is a Blast From Star Wars' Silliest Past |last=Muncy |first=Julie |date=October 13, 2018 |website=[[io9]] |access-date=October 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014113418/https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-rifle-from-the-mandalorian-is-a-blast-from-star-war-1829729845 |archive-date=October 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Jon Favreau]], [[Dave Filoni]], and the main cast hosted a panel for ''The Mandalorian'' at ''Star Wars'' Celebration Chicago on April 14, 2019, where the first footage premiered to fans in attendance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |title=SWCC 2019: 9 THINGS WE LEARNED FROM THE MANDALORIAN PANEL |website=[[Star Wars]] |access-date=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415024016/https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |archive-date=April 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first official poster and trailer were released at the [[D23 Expo]] on August 23, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-first-poster-revealed-for-star-wars-disney-show |title=The Mandalorian: First Poster Revealed for Star Wars Disney+ Show |last=Wade |first=Jessie |date=August 23, 2019 |website=[[IGN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824101415/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-first-poster-revealed-for-star-wars-disney-show |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://time.com/5657961/the-mandalorian-trailer-second-by-second-breakdown/ |title=The Mandalorian Trailer: Everything We Learned at D23 |last=Dockterman |first=Eliana |date=August 24, 2019 |website=[[TIME]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824044324/https://time.com/5657961/the-mandalorian-trailer-second-by-second-breakdown/ |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> A second and final trailer was released on October 28, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-star-wars-trailer-2/amp/ |title=The Mandalorian releases action-packed second trailer |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=October 28, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |url-status=live |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112015133/https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-star-wars-trailer-2/amp/ }}</ref> On November 11, a sneak peek was released during ''[[Monday Night Football]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/amp-articles/the-mandalorian-arrives-tomorrow-but-a-special-sne/1100-6471348/ |title=The Mandalorian Arrives Tomorrow, But A Special Sneak Peek Releases Tonight |last=Elfring |first=Mat |date=November 11, 2019 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=live |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112014640/https://www.gamespot.com/amp-articles/the-mandalorian-arrives-tomorrow-but-a-special-sne/1100-6471348/ }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Mandalorian'' premiered on the [[streaming service]] [[Disney+]] on November 12, 2019 in the United States.<ref name=\"Disney+ReleaseDate\">{{Cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-mandalorian-will-be-available-on-disney-from-day-o-1833985687/amp |title=The Mandalorian Will Premiere on Disney+ November 12 |last=Whitbrook |first=James |date=April 11, 2019 |website=io9.gizmodo.com |access-date=April 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412063838/https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-mandalorian-will-be-available-on-disney-from-day-o-1833985687/amp |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is available in [[4K resolution|4K]] [[High dynamic range video|HDR]], though analysis found its luminance to be well below typical HDR standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2019/11/disneys-the-mandalorian-joins-a-long-list-of-fake-hdr-content-analysis-finds/|title=Disney+\u2019s The Mandalorian joins a long list of fake HDR content, analysis finds|last=Axon|first=Samuel|date=2019-11-26|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221151717/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2019/11/disneys-the-mandalorian-joins-a-long-list-of-fake-hdr-content-analysis-finds/|archive-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"4K\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewaltdisneycompany.com/disney-spotlights-comprehensive-direct-to-consumer-strategy-at-2019-investor-day/ |title=Disney Spotlights Comprehensive Direct-to-Consumer Strategy at 2019 Investor Day |date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=[[The Walt Disney Company]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413005151/https://www.thewaltdisneycompany.com/disney-spotlights-comprehensive-direct-to-consumer-strategy-at-2019-investor-day/ |archive-date=April 13, 2019 |access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref> Disney+ releases ''The Mandalorian'' episodes on a weekly basis, with the first two episodes released only a few days apart on November 12 and 15, 2019 respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/google-amp/news/the-mandalorian-release-schedule-on-disney-plus-has-leaked/ |title=The Mandalorian release schedule on Disney Plus has leaked |last=Reichert |first=Corinne |date=November 4, 2019 |website=[[CNET]] |url-status=live |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112015822/https://www.cnet.com/google-amp/news/the-mandalorian-release-schedule-on-disney-plus-has-leaked/ }}</ref> The seventh episode was released on December 18, 2019 instead of December 20, in order to attach a sneak preview of ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'', which came out on the latter date.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsarama.com/48116-the-mandalorian-changes-dates-for-special-tie-in-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker.html |title=The Mandalorian Changes Dates For Special Tie-In to Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker |last=Arrant |first=Chris |date=December 3, 2019 |website=[[Newsarama]] |url-status=live |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205143203/https://www.newsarama.com/48116-the-mandalorian-changes-dates-for-special-tie-in-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker.html |archive-date=December 5, 2019 }}</ref> When Disney+ became available in several European countries in late March 2020, episodes of ''The Mandalorian'' were available weekly, opposed to having all season one episodes available at the start,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-mandalorian-will-still-roll-out-weekly-when-disney-1841765999|title=The Mandalorian Will Still Roll Out Weekly When Disney+ Comes to Europe, Which Seems Dumb|last=Whitbrook|first=James|work=[[io9]]|date=February 18, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref> the first two episodes were available at launch on March 24, 2020, followed by the third on March 27, after which each episode were released weekly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a31783698/disney-plus-uk-launch-mandalorian-episodes-release/|title=Disney+ confirms how many episodes of The Mandalorian will be available on UK launch day|last=Davies|first=Megan|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The second season is set to premiere in October 2020.<ref name=\"S2Premiere\">{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/02/04/the-mandalorian-season-2-premiere-date-october/|title=''The Mandalorian'' Set for Early Return, Disney+ Marvel Slate Starts in August|first=Matt|last=Mitovitch|work=TVLine|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204223821/https://tvline.com/2020/02/04/the-mandalorian-season-2-premiere-date-october/|archive-date=February 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical response===\n{{Television Rotten Tomatoes scores\n| align = right\n| color = #C4A574\n| title = The Mandalorian\n| label = Season 1 \n| year  = 2019\n| ref   = <ref name=\"RTS1\" /> \n| 90 | 92 | 93 | 91 | 73 | 81 | 100 | 100\n}}\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 95% approval rating for the first season with an average rating of 8.23/10, based on 15 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Action-packed and expertly crafted\u2014if at times a bit too withholding\u2014''The Mandalorian'' is a welcome addition to the ''Star Wars'' universe that benefits greatly from the cuteness of its cargo.\"<ref name=\"RTS1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_mandalorian/s01|title=The Mandalorian: Season 1|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=December 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127180258/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_mandalorian/s01/|archive-date=November 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 69 out of 100, based on 27 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-mandalorian/season-1 |title=The Mandalorian \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211133837/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-mandalorian/season-1 |archive-date=December 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nZaki Hasan of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' said the show \"in essence allows the franchise to take a [[Mulligan (games)|mulligan]] with Boba Fett. Take the look, take that ineffable 'cool,' and transfer it over to an entirely new character who offers an untouched canvas, while giving the audience something that feels familiar.\" He added, \"Three episodes in, that's really all ''The Mandalorian'' is: a feeling. A good feeling, mind you, but rather than any specific storytelling quality, it's that feeling you're talking about. The visual effects, the sound effects, the overall look of the thing is all bang-on. This is a polished production that shows off every cent of its feature film budget on every frame of its run time.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/california-streamin-everyone-loves-the-mandalorian-for-now |title=Everyone loves 'The Mandalorian.' For now |last=Hasan |first=Zaki |date=November 15, 2019 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |access-date=November 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123175734/https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/california-streamin-everyone-loves-the-mandalorian-for-now |archive-date=November 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]'', Micah Peters said, \"''The Mandalorian'' may already be difficult to care about as something more than an installment that exists solely to set up the next installment. But there are still many enjoyable things about it, and also it's a Disney show with spaceships and giant sea slugs, so it doesn't need to be ''[[Citizen Kane]]''. It might, however, be the next great TV Western.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theringer.com/tv/2019/11/14/20965328/mandalorian-justified-westerns-star-wars-disney-plus-han-solo |title='The Mandalorian' Could Be the Best TV Western Since 'Justified' |last=Peters |first=Micah |date=November 14, 2019 |website=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |access-date=November 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125194302/https://www.theringer.com/tv/2019/11/14/20965328/mandalorian-justified-westerns-star-wars-disney-plus-han-solo |archive-date=November 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Audience viewership ===\n<!--AUDIENCE RECEPTION AND RATINGS: Do not include them! Wikipedia does not support user-generated content in its articles, and thus audience ratings cannot be included. Please refer to the talk page before proceeding to edit this section, and view the multiple discussions raised on the topic. No consensus has been formed to allow this article to differ from Wikipedia's guidelines and policies by including such content. Additions of audience ratings will be reverted.-->\nWithin four days of its release, ''The Mandalorian'' had stronger U.S. demand compared to four of 2019's biggest streaming originals: [[Netflix]]'s ''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]'', ''[[When They See Us]]'', ''[[The Dark Crystal: Age of Resistance]]'', and [[Amazon Prime Video]]'s ''[[Good Omens (TV series)|Good Omens]]''. [[TV Time]], a popular app allowing users to track shows and movies they are watching (or want to watch), stated that double the number of people compared to last week are interested in ''The Mandalorian'', and noted that it had the largest gain of any TV show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/the-mandalorian-demand-premiere-stranger-things-titans-1203409008/ |title='The Mandalorian' Demand Surges in Debut Week But Trails 'Stranger Things,' DC's 'Titans' |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=November 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121095559/https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/the-mandalorian-demand-premiere-stranger-things-titans-1203409008/ |archive-date=November 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMuch of the [[social media]] reaction has been to the show's [[breakout character]], a 50-year old \"infant\" of [[Yoda]]'s species, who was kept secret until the series' pilot episode aired.<ref>{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Travis |title=It was 'The Lion King' star Donald Glover's idea to keep Baby Yoda a secret |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/it-was-donald-glovers-idea-to-keep-baby-yoda-secret-2019-12 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=January 5, 2020 |date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230033331/https://www.businessinsider.com/it-was-donald-glovers-idea-to-keep-baby-yoda-secret-2019-12 |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian initially takes \"[[The Child (Star Wars)|The Child]]\" (the official name for the character) for a bounty, but ends up becoming its ''[[de facto]]'' guardian in order to protect it. It has been shown to have the powers of [[the Force]], and has been affably nicknamed \"Baby Yoda\".<ref name=BabyYoda /> The unexpected popularity of \"Baby Yoda\" led to an explosion of unofficial merchandise for the [[Christmas and holiday season]], which quickly sold out.<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/27/why-baby-yoda-merchandise-from-the-mandalorian-is-delayed.html |title='Baby Yoda' caught the merch industry off guard, and now they're trying to catch up |last=Whitten |first=Sarah |date=November 27, 2019 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213123053/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/27/why-baby-yoda-merchandise-from-the-mandalorian-is-delayed.html |archive-date=December 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/what-is-baby-yoda-in-the-mandalorian-our-wildest-theories-so-far/ |title=Who is 'Baby Yoda' in The Mandalorian? Here are some of our wildest theories so far |date=December 4, 2019 |website=[[CNET]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129091138/https://www.cnet.com/news/what-is-baby-yoda-in-the-mandalorian-our-wildest-theories-so-far/ |archive-date=November 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Awards table|5}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"10\" | <center>2020</center>\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[18th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n| Outstanding Visual Effects in a Photoreal Episode\n| [[Richard Bluff]], Abbigail Keller, Jason Porter, Hayden Jones, Roy Cancinon <small>(for \"[[Chapter 2: The Child]]\")</small>\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"6\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/ves-awards-nominations-2020-list-the-lion-king-the-mandalorian-game-of-thrones-1202823016/|title=VES Awards Nominations: \u2018The Lion King\u2019, \u2018Alita: Battle Angel\u2019, \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 & \u2018GoT\u2019 Top List|work=Deadline|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=January 7, 2020|accessdate=January 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109042040/https://deadline.com/2020/01/ves-awards-nominations-2020-list-the-lion-king-the-mandalorian-game-of-thrones-1202823016/|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|-\n| Outstanding Virtual Cinematography in a CG Project\n| [[Richard Bluff]], Jason Porter, Landis Fields IV, Baz Idione <small>(for \"[[Chapter 6: The Prisoner]]\"; The Roost)</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Animated Character in an Episode or Real-Time Project\n| Terry Bannon, Rudy Massar, Hugo Leygnac <small>(for \"The Child\"; Mudhorn)</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Model in a Photoreal or Animated Project\n| Doug Chiang, Jay Machado, John Goodson, Landis Fields IV <small>(for \"[[Chapter 3: The Sin]]\"; The Razorcrest)</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Created Environment in an Episode, Commercial, or Real-Time Project\n| Alex Murtaza, Yanick Gaudreau, Marco Tremblay, Maryse Bouchard (for Nevarro Town)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Effects Simulations in an Episode, Commercial, or Real-Time Project\n| Xavier Martin Ramirez, Ian Baxter, Fabio Slino, Andrea Rosa <small>(for \"Chapter 2: The Child\"; Mudhorn)</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|Art Directors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Art Directors Guild Award for Excellence in Production Design for a One-Hour Period or Fantasy Single-Camera Series|One-Hour Period or Fantasy Single-Camera Series]]\n| Andrew L. Jones <small>(for \"[[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\")</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/art-directors-guild-winners-2020-complete-list-1273722/item/period-film-art-directors-guild-award-winners-2020-1273734 |title='Parasite,' 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Win Art Directors Guild Awards |website=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Carolyn |last=Giardina |date=February 1, 2019 |accessdate=February 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202063346/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/art-directors-guild-winners-2020-complete-list-1273722/item/period-film-art-directors-guild-award-winners-2020-1273734 |archive-date=February 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[International Cinematographers Guild|Publicists Guild Awards]]\n| Maxwell Weinberg Publicist Showmanship Television Award\n| [[Disney+]]\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/icg-publicists-awards-2020-winners-list-1274564|title=ICG Publicists Awards: 'Joker,' 'The Mandalorian' Among Winners|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Carita|last=Rizzo|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Nebula Award]]\n| [[Ray Bradbury Award|Ray Bradbury Award for Outstanding Dramatic Presentation]]\n| [[Jon Favreau]] <small>(for \"The Child\")</small>\n| {{pending}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2019 Nebula Awards Finalists |url=https://www.tor.com/2020/02/20/announcing-the-2019-nebula-awards-finalists/ |website=Tor.com |accessdate=22 February 2020 |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Hugo Award]]\n| [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation#Short Form|Best Dramatic Presentation - Short Form]]\n| [[Jon Favreau]], [[Taika Waititi]] <small>(for \"Redemption\")</small>\n| {{pending}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2020-hugo-awards/|title=2020 Hugo Awards|publisher=The Hugo Awards|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Future==\nIn November 2019, [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|Walt Disney Studios]] chief creative officer [[Alan F. Horn|Alan Horn]] stated that if the series is successful, a film featuring the character could be developed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/disney-chief-scorsese-marvel-mandalorian-1203403513/ |title=Disney Studios Chief Alan Horn on Scorsese v. Marvel, Challenges in a Changing Business |last=Thorne |first=Will |date=November 13, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=November 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191114001553/https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/disney-chief-scorsese-marvel-mandalorian-1203403513/ |archive-date=November 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 5, 2019, when asked if characters from the series will appear in future ''Star Wars'' productions, Favreau said that \"There's definitely the opportunity to explore these characters beyond what has been presented on the show\", and that \"There's a very fluid line between what's in the movie theaters and what's on the screen at home\".<ref name=\"FavreauDirector\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |title=Why Jon Favreau Chose Baby Yoda: \"We Don't Know a Lot of Details About His Species\" |last=Giardina |first=Carolyn |date=December 5, 2019 |access-date=December 8, 2019 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206084030/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2020, Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]] said that spin-offs of ''The Mandalorian'' are being considered, stating that there is \"the possibility of infusing [the series] with more characters and taking those characters in their own direction in terms of series\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-bob-iger-teases-mandalorian-falcon-winter-soldier-wandavision-dates-1276326 |title=Disney's Bob Iger Considering 'Mandalorian' Spinoff Shows |last=Couch |first=Aaron |date=February 4, 2020 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |access-date=February 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204230308/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-bob-iger-teases-mandalorian-falcon-winter-soldier-wandavision-dates-1276326 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Documentary series==\nIn April 2020, Disney announced an eight-episode documentary series titled ''Disney Gallery: The Mandalorian'', to premiere on Disney+ on May 4, 2020, [[Star Wars Day|''Star Wars'' Day]]. Hosted by Favreau, the series features interviews, never-before-seen footage, and roundtable conversations to explore behind the scenes of ''The Mandalorian''. Subsequent episodes of ''Disney Gallery: The Mandalorian'' will air weekly on Fridays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/disney-gallery-the-mandalorian-announce|title=Go Behind the Scenes in the New Disney+ Series ''Disney Gallery: The Mandalorian''|website=StarWars.com|date=April 15, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Disney+ series}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{Wookieepedia|The Mandalorian|''The Mandalorian''}}\n* [https://www.starwars.com/series/the-mandalorian  The Mandalorian on ''StarWars.com'']\n{{The Mandalorian}}\n{{Star Wars}}\n{{Lucasfilm}}\n{{Disney+}}\n{{Jon Favreau}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandalorian, The}}\n[[Category:The Mandalorian| ]]\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Action television series]]\n[[Category:American television programs featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Disney+ original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Interquel television series]]\n[[Category:Space adventure television series]]\n[[Category:Space opera television series]]\n[[Category:Space Western television series]]\n[[Category:Star Wars television series]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Jon Favreau]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the television series|the fictional group of people|Mandalorian|the title character|The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|2019 American ''Star Wars'' live-action television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Mandalorian\n| image                    = The Mandalorian logo.jpg\n| genre                    = [[Space Western]]\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Star Wars]]''|[[George Lucas]]}}\n| creator                  = [[Jon Favreau]]\n| writer                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jon Favreau\n* [[Dave Filoni]]\n* [[Rick Famuyiwa]]\n* [[Christopher Yost]]\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Dave Filoni\n* Rick Famuyiwa\n* [[Deborah Chow]]\n* [[Bryce Dallas Howard]]\n* [[Taika Waititi]]\n}}\n| starring                 = [[Pedro Pascal]]\n| composer                 = [[Ludwig G\u00f6ransson]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!--Only increment as a new season premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| num_episodes             = 8<!--Only increment as a new episode premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Jon Favreau\n* Dave Filoni\n* [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]]\n* [[Colin Wilson (film producer)|Colin Wilson]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greig Fraser]]\n* Barry Idoine\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jeff Seibenick\n* Andrew S. Eisen\n* [[Dana E. Glauberman]]\n}}\n| runtime                  = 31\u201346 minutes\n| location                 = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lucasfilm]]\n* [[Fairview Entertainment]]\n* [[Golem Creations]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Disney Media Distribution]]\n| network                  = [[Disney+]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|11|12}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| website                  = https://disneyplusoriginals.disney.com/show/the-mandalorian\n}}\n'''''The Mandalorian''''', also known as '''''Star Wars: The Mandalorian''''', is an American [[space Western]] [[web television]] series created by [[Jon Favreau]] and released on [[Disney+]]. It is the first [[live action]] series in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' franchise. Set five years after the events of ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'' and 25 years prior to the events of [[Star Wars: The Force Awakens|''The Force Awakens'']], it follows the [[The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)|title character]], the [[Mandalorian]] [[bounty hunter]] Din Djarin, and his exploits beyond the reaches of the [[New Republic (Star Wars)|New Republic]].\n\nFavreau also serves as [[head writer]] and [[showrunner]], as well as [[Television producer#Executive producer|executive producer]], alongside [[Dave Filoni]], [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]], and [[Colin Wilson (film producer)|Colin Wilson]]. ''The Mandalorian'' premiered with the launch of Disney+ on November 12, 2019, with its eight-episode first season. The series has received positive reviews.\n\nA second season has been ordered, which is set to premiere in October 2020.\n\n==Synopsis==\n{{quote|After the stories of [[Jango Fett|Jango]] and [[Boba Fett]], another warrior emerges in the ''Star Wars'' universe. ''The Mandalorian'' is set after the [[Star Wars: Return of the Jedi|fall of the Empire]] and before the [[Star Wars: The Force Awakens|emergence of the First Order]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Charlie|title=Mandalorian is making sense of the time between Return of Jedi and Force Awakens|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/18/21026895/mandalorian-episode-7-recap-timeline-return-of-jedi-force-awakens|website=Polygon|date=December 18, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219150605/https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/18/21026895/mandalorian-episode-7-recap-timeline-return-of-jedi-force-awakens|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Brett|title=Does \u2018Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker\u2019 Connect to \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019?|url=https://decider.com/2019/12/20/does-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-connect-to-the-mandalorian/|website=Decider|date=December 20, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221141124/https://decider.com/2019/12/20/does-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-connect-to-the-mandalorian/|archive-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Katz|first1=Brandon|title=\u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Creator Opens Up About Baby Yoda and \u2018Star Wars\u2019 Crossovers|url=https://observer.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-baby-yoda-star-wars-crossovers/|website=Observer|date=December 5, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228172821/https://observer.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-baby-yoda-star-wars-crossovers/|archive-date=December 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pometsey|first1=Olive|title=Everything you need to know about The Mandalorian|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/culture/article/the-mandalorian|website=GQ Magazine|date=December 9, 2019|access-date=December 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122113411/https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/culture/article/the-mandalorian|archive-date=November 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The series depicts a lone bounty hunter in the outer reaches of the galaxy far from the authority of the [[New Republic (Star Wars)|New Republic]].<ref name=\"TitlePremise\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/star-wars-jon-favreau-series-the-mandalorian-boba-fett-1202475775/ |title=Jon Favreau Unveils Details For His ''Star Wars'' Live-Action Streaming Series ''The Mandalorian'' |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=October 3, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=October 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222080706/https://deadline.com/2018/10/star-wars-jon-favreau-series-the-mandalorian-boba-fett-1202475775/ |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>|[[Jon Favreau]]}}\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{{main|List of The Mandalorian characters}}\n=== Starring ===\n* [[Pedro Pascal]] as [[The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)|Din Djarin / The Mandalorian]], a lone gunfighter and bounty hunter who is sometimes referred to as \"Mando\" (a generic term used to refer to all [[Mandalorian]]s, a clan of skilled warriors). He is a \"foundling\" who was rescued at a young age by Mandalorians during [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|the Clone Wars]]. Pascal has described his character as [[Clint Eastwood]]\u2013esque with advanced combat skills and of \"questionable moral character\".<ref name=IG11 /> \n* \"[[The Child (Star Wars)|The Child]]\" (performed by various [[puppeteer]]s), a member of [[Yoda's species|the same unnamed species]] as the powerful [[Jedi master]] [[Yoda]] with similar [[The Force|Force abilities]]. The Child is a toddler at age 50. A bounty is offered for his return by \"[[The Client (Star Wars)|The Client]]\". He is found and protected by the Mandalorian while being targeted by other bounty hunters.\n\n=== Co-starring ===\nThe following actors received co-starring billing in the main end credits of the episodes they appeared in:\n* [[Carl Weathers]] as [[Greef Karga]], an ex-[[magistrate]] and leader of a bounty hunter guild who hires the Mandalorian to track a valuable asset.<ref name=space />\n* [[Werner Herzog]] as \"[[The Client (Star Wars)|The Client]],\" an unnamed man with Stormtrooper bodyguards who arranges for the Mandalorian to track a valuable asset.<ref name=DeadlineCast />\n* [[Omid Abtahi]]<ref name=DeadlineCast /> as [[Dr. Pershing]], a scientist working for \"the Client\".\n* [[Nick Nolte]] as the voice of [[Kuiil]], an [[Ugnaught]] moisture farmer who bought his freedom after being enslaved by the Empire.<ref name=DeadlineCast /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-new-character-posters/ |title=''The Mandalorian'' releases 5 new character photos |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=October 28, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=October 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030210746/https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-new-character-posters/ |archive-date=October 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Misty Rosas provided the [[motion capture]] performance of Kuiil.<ref>{{cite podcast |last1=Rosas |first1=Misty |last2=Ballance |first2=Brian |url=https://soundcloud.com/theinterestingpodcast/ep-108-misty-rosas |publisher=The Interesting Podcast |title=Ep. 108 Misty Rosas |date=January 21, 2020 |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kain |first=Erik |title=Star Wars 'The Mandalorian' Episode 7 Recap And Review: 'The Reckoning' Is The Best Episode Yet |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/12/18/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-7-recap-and-review-the-best-episode-yet/#abd12ef70788 |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222175408/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/12/18/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-7-recap-and-review-the-best-episode-yet/#abd12ef70788 |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Taika Waititi]] as the voice of [[IG-11]],<ref name=IG11 /> a bounty-hunting [[Droid (Star Wars)|droid]] who processes conversations in a precise and literal manner.<ref name=ew /> After attempting to kill \"the Child\" as its bounty, and being stopped by Djarin, IG-11 is re-programmed by Kuiil to protect the toddler.<!--ADD WHEN A SOURCE CAN BE FOUND Rio Hackford provides the motion-capture for IG-11.-->\n* [[Gina Carano]] as [[Cara Dune]], a former rebel shock trooper-turned-mercenary from the now destroyed planet of [[Alderaan]] who fought in the [[Galactic Civil War]] for the [[Rebel Alliance]]/[[New Republic (Star Wars)|New Republic]].<ref name=\"space\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.space.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-what-we-know.html |title=''The Mandalorian'': Here's What We Know So Far About the ''Star Wars'' Live Action Show |last=Snowden |first=Scott |date=May 2, 2019 |website=Space.com |access-date=May 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502162656/https://www.space.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-what-we-know.html |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Amy Sedaris]] as [[Peli Motto]], a cantankerous docking bay attendant and ship mechanic on [[Tatooine]].\n* [[Jake Cannavale]] as [[Toro Calican]], a fledgling bounty hunter looking to join the bounty hunters\u2019 guild by capturing Fennec Shand. He hires the Mandalorian to help.\n* [[Ming-Na Wen]] as [[Fennec Shand]], an assassin who crosses paths with the Mandalorian.<ref name=\"Fennec\">{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/ming-na-wen-the-mandalorian-star-wars-fennec-shand |title=First Look: Ming-Na Wen's Star Wars Assassin From The Mandalorian |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |author-link=Anthony Breznican |date=November 4, 2019 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |magazine= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123011358/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/ming-na-wen-the-mandalorian-star-wars-fennec-shand |archive-date=November 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Wen />\n* [[Mark Boone Junior]] as [[Ranzar Malk|Ranzar \"Ran\" Malk]], an aging mercenary and leader of a motley crew looking to free a prisoner on a New Republic ship. Malk is a former associate of the Mandalorian from before he joined the guild.\n* [[Bill Burr]] as [[Mayfeld]], a former Imperial sharpshooter and the point man on Malk's crew.\n* [[Natalia Tena]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Xi'an|Xi'an]], a [[Twi'lek]] member of Malk's crew and knife master, who claims to be Djarin's former love interest.\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Burg|Burg]], a large Devaronian member of Malk's crew who serves as the muscle of the team.\n* [[Richard Ayoade]] as the voice of [[Q9-0]], also known as \"Zero\", a droid member of Malk's crew.<!--ADD WHEN A SOURCE CAN BE FOUND Chris Bartlett provides the motion-capture for Q9-0.-->\n* [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Qin|Qin]], a Twi'lek and Xi'an's brother. He has a combative past with the Mandalorian.\n* [[Giancarlo Esposito]] as [[Moff Gideon]], a former officer of the Imperial Security Bureau, the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]]'s [[secret police]], whose life changed after the Rebel Alliance/New Republic destroyed the second [[Death Star]].<ref name=\"ew\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/05/inside-the-mandalorian-star-wars/ |title=''The Mandalorian'' unmasked: 'We did things no ''Star Wars'' fan has ever seen' |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=September 5, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905185539/https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/05/inside-the-mandalorian-star-wars/ |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Emily Swallow]] as [[The Armorer (Star Wars)|The Armorer]],<ref name=DeadlineCast /><ref name=\"BabyYoda\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/the-mandalorians-emily-swallow-on-the-armorers-secrets-and-the-baby-yoda-puppet |title=The Mandalorian's Emily Swallow on the Armorer's secrets and the Baby Yoda puppet |last=Silliman |first=Brian |date=November 27, 2019 |website=[[Syfy Wire]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224092134/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/the-mandalorians-emily-swallow-on-the-armorers-secrets-and-the-baby-yoda-puppet |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> a Mandalorian woman who forges armor and equipment from Beskar steel, and enforces tradition among the surviving Mandalorians.\n\n=== Guests ===\n<!-- ONLY NAMED CHARACTERS HERE. USE THE EPISODES' ARTICLES TO LIST THE FULL GUEST CAST, INCLUDING UNNAMED CHARACTERS. -->\n====Season 1====\n<!-- 104 -->\n* [[Julia Jones]] as [[Omera]],<ref name=Julia /> a widowed farmer on [[Sorgan]] who provides lodging for the Mandalorian during his stay on the planet.<ref name=\"credits104\">{{Cite episode |title=Chapter 4: Sanctuary |series=The Mandalorian |network=[[Disney+]] |date=November 29, 2019 |season=1 |number=4}}</ref>\n* Isla Farris as [[Winta (Star Wars)|Winta]], Omera's daughter who bonds with the Child during his stay on the planet.<ref name=\"credits104\" />\n* Asif Ali as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Caben and Stoke|Caben]], a farmer on Sorgan who, with his friend Stoke, asks the Mandalorian to protect his village against the attacks of Klatooinian raiders.<ref name=\"credits104\" />\n* [[Eugene Cordero]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Caben and Stoke|Stoke]], a farmer on Sorgan.<ref name=\"credits104\" />\n<!-- 105 -->\n* Rio Hackford as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Riot Mar|Riot Mar]], a bounty hunter who engages the Mandalorian in a dogfight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-latest-mandalorian-had-maybe-a-little-too-much-fan-1840243870 |title=The Latest Mandalorian Had Maybe a Little Too Much Fan Service for Its Own Good |last=Lussier |first=Germain |date=December 6, 2019 |website=[[io9]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220220429/https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-latest-mandalorian-had-maybe-a-little-too-much-fan-1840243870 |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<!-- 106 -->\n* [[Matt Lanter]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Davan|Davan]], a New Republic soldier.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schedeen |first1=Jesse |title=The Mandalorian Cast: Every Character and Cameo From Season 1 So Far |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/14/the-mandalorian-cast-cameos-celebrity-who-was-in-episode |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214215728/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/14/the-mandalorian-cast-cameos-celebrity-who-was-in-episode |archive-date=December 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lanter had previously voiced [[Darth Vader|Anakin Skywalker]] in ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' and ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]''.\n* [[Dave Filoni]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Trapper Wolf|Trapper Wolf]], a New Republic X-wing pilot.\n* [[Rick Famuyiwa]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Jib Dodger|Jib Dodger]], a New Republic X-wing pilot.\n* [[Deborah Chow]] as [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Sash Ketter|Sash Ketter]], a New Republic X-wing pilot.\n\n[[Horatio Sanz]] played a [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Mythrol|Mythrol]] bounty,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a29786836/horatio-sanz-brian-posehn-the-mandalorian/ |title=Comedians Horatio Sanz and Brian Posehn Made Sneaky Cameos in the First Episode of The Mandalorian |last=Romano |first=Evan |date=November 13, 2019 |website=[[Men's Health]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128064743/https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a29786836/horatio-sanz-brian-posehn-the-mandalorian/ |archive-date=November 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Brian Posehn]] played a speeder pilot in \"[[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/60855-the-mandalorian-star-wars-brian-posehn-cameo |title=Yes, that is Brian Posehn from 'Sarah Silverman' in 'The Mandalorian' |last=Franciscov |first=Eric |date=November 12, 2019 |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |access-date=December 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222225540/https://www.inverse.com/article/60855-the-mandalorian-star-wars-brian-posehn-cameo |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Series creator [[Jon Favreau]] voiced [[Paz Vizla]], an infantry Mandalorian featured in \"[[Chapter 3: The Sin]]\", physically played by stunt double Tait Fletcher.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/11/22/star-wars-the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-cameo/ |title=Star Wars: Did The Mandalorian Feature a Jon Favreau Cameo? |last=Cavanaugh |first=Patrick |date=November 23, 2019 |website=ComicBook.com |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127172705/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/11/22/star-wars-the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-cameo/ |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Adam Pally]] and [[Jason Sudeikis]] played two bike scout troopers in \"[[Chapter 8: Redemption]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/the-mandalorian-spoilers-darksaber-jason-sudeikis-and-adam-pally/ |title=The Mandalorian spoilers: Darksaber, Jason Sudeikis, and Adam Pally |last=DeVault |first=Ryan |date=December 27, 2019 |website=[[Monsters and Critics]] |access-date=December 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227124329/https://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/the-mandalorian-spoilers-darksaber-jason-sudeikis-and-adam-pally/ |archive-date=December 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, members of the [[501st Legion]] fan organization were used as [[Stormtrooper (Star Wars)|stormtrooper]] extras.<ref name=space /><ref>{{Cite_web|url=https://geektyrant.com/news/heartwarming-story-about-how-501st-legion-came-to-appear-in-the-mandalorian|title=Heartwarming Story About How 501st Legion Came to Appear in The Mandalorian|publisher=geektyrant|last=Fisher|first=Jessica|date=April 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Baver |first1=Kristin |title=SWCC 2019: 9 Things We Learned From The Mandalorian Panel |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |website=StarWars.com |accessdate=December 29, 2019 |date=April 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415024016/https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |archive-date=April 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Season 2====\n* [[Michael Biehn]] as a bounty hunter<ref name=\"BiehnCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mandalorian-casts-terminator-star-michael-biehn-1286284|title='The Mandalorian' Casts 'Terminator' Star Michael Biehn|last=Couch|first=Aaron|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Rosario Dawson]] as [[Ahsoka Tano]], a former [[Jedi|Jedi Padawan]] of [[Anakin Skywalker]] turned spymaster for the [[Rebel Alliance]].<ref name=\"DawsonMandalorian\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/rosario-dawson-ahsoka-tano-the-mandalorian-season-2-1203540472/|title=Rosario Dawson to Play Ahsoka Tano in \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2|last=Thorne|first=Will|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n===Season 1 (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background=#C4A574 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = [[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Dave Filoni]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Jon Favreau]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|12}}\n |ShortSummary    = Five years after the fall of the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]]<ref name=\"mccl\">{{Cite magazine |url=https://time.com/5717734/mandalorian-star-wars-timeline/ |title=How ''The Mandalorian'' Fits Into the Larger ''Star Wars'' Timeline |last=McCluskey |first=Megan |date=November 12, 2019 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124055630/https://time.com/5717734/mandalorian-star-wars-timeline/ |archive-date=November 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> a [[Mandalorian]] [[bounty hunter]] hands his latest bounty to [[Greef Karga]]. Then he accepts an under-the-table commission on the outpost world of [[List of Star Wars planets and moons#Nevarro|Nevarro]] from an enigmatic [[The Client (Star Wars)|client]] with apparent Imperial connections, directing him to track down and capture an unnamed fifty-year-old target. While the Client is indifferent to the target's well-being, his colleague [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Dr. Pershing|Dr. Pershing]] insists the target be brought back alive. The Mandalorian is given a down payment of a single bar of [[Beskar steel]], sacred to his people. He takes it to a covert Mandalorian enclave where an [[The Armorer (Star Wars)|armorer]] uses it to make him a [[pauldron]]. Arriving at the planet of the target's last reported location, the Mandalorian is aided by a vapor farmer named [[Kuiil]]. Tired of the chaos that bounty hunters bring to the area, Kuiil leads him to the target's location and departs. Entering the remote and heavily defended encampment, the Mandalorian reluctantly teams up with bounty hunting droid [[IG-11]] to clear the camp and find the quarry: a [[The Child (Star Wars)|child]] of [[Yoda's species]]. When IG-11 attempts to kill the infant per its bounty orders, the Mandalorian shoots and destroys the droid, taking the Child alive.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = [[Chapter 2: The Child]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Rick Famuyiwa]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|15}}\n |ShortSummary    = While returning to his ship with the Child, the Mandalorian fights and kills a group of rival bounty hunters who ambush him. Nearing his ship, he finds it being stripped by [[Jawa (Star Wars)|Jawas]] for parts, and violently confronts them. When he tries to attack their [[sandcrawler]], the Jawas stun him and drop him from its roof. The following day, Kuiil helps him locate the Jawas and negotiate for the return of his ship's components. The Mandalorian agrees to retrieve the egg of a rhinoceros-like Mudhorn in exchange for the stolen parts. He enters the Mudhorn's cave only to be hurled out by the angry beast inside, which attacks him repeatedly, damaging his armor. As the Mudhorn rushes in for the kill, the Child uses [[the Force]] to levitate the beast, allowing the surprised Mandalorian to stab and kill it. He collects the egg and takes it to the Jawas, who crack it open and eat its yellow insides. With the trade complete, the Mandalorian and Kuiil work together to repair the ship, allowing the Mandalorian to leave the planet with the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = [[Chapter 3: The Sin]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Deborah Chow]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|22}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian delivers the Child to the Client on Nevarro and collects the bounty of 20 bars of Beskar steel. Uncharacteristically, the Mandalorian asks about the Client's plans for the Child, but is told that it's none of his concern. He leaves before conflict arises. Returning to the Mandalorian enclave, the Mandalorian has his damaged armor replaced and weapons upgraded by the Armorer, who forges a full [[cuirass]] from most of the Beskar steel, while the remainder goes to support Mandalorian foundling children. The Mandalorian accepts a new job from Greef Karga and prepares his ship to depart. Feeling guilty for abandoning the Child to the Empire, he turns back to attack the Client's base, killing most of the stormtroopers guarding it. He rescues the Child from Dr. Pershing's laboratory where it was being experimented on, but chooses not to kill the doctor. On the way back to his ship, the Mandalorian is ambushed by other bounty hunters and Greef Karga, who demand that he hand over the Child. He refuses, and a firefight breaks out. Outnumbered and cornered, the Mandalorian is able to escape only when other Mandalorians arrive from the enclave, attacking the bounty hunters and allowing him to reach his ship with the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = [[Chapter 4: Sanctuary]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Bryce Dallas Howard]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|29}}\n |ShortSummary    = Arriving on the sparsely populated forest planet [[List of Star Wars planets and moons#Sorgan|Sorgan]], the Mandalorian encounters ex-Rebel shock trooper-turned-mercenary [[Cara Dune]]. Following a short brawl, Dune explains that she is hiding after taking \"early retirement\", and asks the Mandalorian to leave. While he prepares his ship, two desperate fishermen approach, offering to hire him to drive off a band of [[List of Star Wars species|Klatoonian]] raiders. He accepts the job in exchange for lodging, using their credits to enlist Dune's help. At the village, they are housed by [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Omera|Omera]], a widowed mother. The Mandalorian confides in her that no one has seen him without his helmet since childhood, when his tribe took him in as an orphan. Despite discovering that the raiders have an old Imperial [[AT-ST]], the villagers refuse to leave, so the Mandalorian and Dune train them to defend themselves. They provoke the raiders at night, with Dune luring the AT-ST into a trap for the Mandalorian to blow up and forcing the remaining raiders to flee. With peace restored, the Mandalorian plans to leave the Child in the village, but a Guild bounty hunter tracks it down and is killed by Dune. Realizing that neither the village nor the Child would be safe, the Mandalorian departs with the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = [[Chapter 5: The Gunslinger]]\n |DirectedBy      = Dave Filoni\n |WrittenBy       = Dave Filoni\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|6}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian defeats a pursuing bounty hunter in a [[dogfight]]. He lands his damaged ship at a nearby repair dock, run by mechanic [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Peli Motto|Peli Motto]] in [[Mos Eisley]] on [[Tatooine]]. He seeks work in a cantina to pay for the repairs, meeting aspiring bounty hunter [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Toro Calican|Toro Calican]], who is tracking elite mercenary and assassin [[Fennec Shand]]. Calican needs to catch Shand to join the Guild, and the Mandalorian agrees to help when Calican offers to let him keep the money. They capture Shand in the desert, but she destroys one of their speeder bikes, so the Mandalorian goes to get a [[List of Star Wars species|dewback]] they passed for transportation. While Calican watches Shand, she tells him that the Mandalorian betrayed the guild, making the bounty on him and the Child worth more than hers. Shand offers to help Calican capture the Mandalorian if he sets her free, but he shoots her instead and rides the remaining speeder bike to the repair dock, taking Motto and the Child hostage. The Mandalorian arrives, uses a [[flare]] to disorient Calican, and kills him. He takes Calican's money to pay Motto for the repairs, thanking her before leaving Tatooine. Out in the desert, a mysterious figure approaches Shand's body.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = [[Chapter 6: The Prisoner]]\n |DirectedBy      = Rick Famuyiwa\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=[[Christopher Yost]] |t=Christopher Yost and Rick Famuyiwa}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|13}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian contacts his former partner [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Ranzar Malk|\"Ran\" Malk]] for work. Ran welcomes him to his space station and informs the Mandalorian that he needs his ship for a five-man job. He is joined by ex-Imperial sharpshooter [[Mayfeld]], [[Devaronian]] strongman [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Burg|Burg]], droid pilot [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Q9-0|Q9-0]], and [[Twi'lek]] knife-expert [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Xi'an|Xi'an]] for a mission to rescue Xi'an's brother [[List of The Mandalorian characters#Qin|Qin]], a prisoner of the New Republic. After infiltrating the prison ship, they fight through security droids and make it to the control room where the ship's security chief triggers a security beacon before being killed by Xi'an. The crew rescues Qin but double-crosses the Mandalorian. He escapes and defeats each crew member, then captures Qin. Q9-0 finds the Child after deciphering the archived transmission from Greef Karga, but is shot by the Mandalorian before he can harm him. The Mandalorian delivers Qin to Ran and departs with his payment. Ran immediately moves to launch a fighter to kill the Mandalorian, but discovers the New Republic beacon had been placed on Qin, leading a trio of [[X-wing fighter|X-wings]] to Ran's station where they attack. In the final scene, Mayfeld, Burg, and Xi'an are revealed to be locked in a cell on the prison transport, having been spared by the Mandalorian.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = [[Chapter 7: The Reckoning]]\n |DirectedBy      = Deborah Chow\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|18}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Mandalorian receives a message from Greef Karga, whose town on Nevarro has been overrun by ex-Imperial troops led by the Client. Karga proposes that the Mandalorian use the Child as bait in order to kill the Client and free the town. In return, Karga will square things with the Guild, which would allow the Mandalorian and the Child to live in peace. Sensing a trap, the Mandalorian recruits Cara Dune and Kuiil to assist him, and Kuiil brings a rebuilt and reprogrammed IG-11 to protect the Child. They meet Karga and his associates, but are attacked by [[Mynock]]s. Karga is injured, but the Child uses the Force to heal his wound. In return, Karga kills his associates and confesses his original plan to shoot the Mandalorian and take the Child to the Client. Karga pretends that Dune has captured the Mandalorian, while Kuiil returns the Child to the ship. During the meeting, [[Moff Gideon]]'s troops open fire on the building and kill the Client and his bodyguards, trapping the Mandalorian, Karga, and Dune inside. Gideon arrives, demanding the Child. In the desert, two scout troopers intercept the Mandalorian's communications and track Kuiil, killing him and taking the Child.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = [[Chapter 8: Redemption]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Taika Waititi]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jon Favreau\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = IG-11 rescues the Child from the scout troopers. Gideon warns Karga, Dune, and the Mandalorian that they face certain death unless they agree to assist him. IG-11 arrives and breaks the standoff but Gideon injures the Mandalorian. The Child uses the Force to deflect an attacking stormtrooper's flamethrower back on him. The Mandalorian sends the others through a sewer grate with the Child to find help from the Mandalorian enclave, while IG-11 removes his helmet to tend to a head injury. Joining the others, the Mandalorian finds the covert group of Mandalorians dead or escaped, except for the Armorer. She tasks him to care for the foundling Child like his own, discover its origins, and return it to its kind. The Armorer fashions the Mandalorian his own signet and gives him a jetpack. The group is ferried down an underground lava river, but when they are ambushed by stormtroopers, IG-11 self-destructs to eliminate the enemy. Gideon attacks in a [[TIE fighter]] and the Mandalorian uses the jetpack to bring the craft down, but the Moff survives and cuts himself out of the ship with the [[Darksaber (fictional weapon)|Darksaber]].<!-- The inclusion of the Darksaber in this plot summary, and the accompanying efn citation, were the result of a a consensus and compromise reached after an extensive talk page discussion. Please do not remove or modify it without seeking a new consensus. -->{{efn|Actor Giancarlo Esposito, as well as Lucasfilm's official ''Star Wars'' website, have identified the weapon as the Darksaber,<ref>{{cite news |last=Lash |first=Jolie |title=The Mandalorian Season 2: Giancarlo Esposito Offers Clue on Why Moff Gideon Wants Baby Yoda |work=[[IGN]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorian-season-2-moff-gideon-baby-yoda-darksaber |accessdate=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121054150/https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorian-season-2-moff-gideon-baby-yoda-darksaber |archive-date=January 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Knox0211\">{{cite news |last=Knox |first=Kelly |title=What is the Darksaber? |work=[[Star Wars|StarWars.com]] |publisher=[[Lucasfilm]] |date=February 11, 2020 |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/what-is-the-darksaber |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221195525/https://www.starwars.com/news/what-is-the-darksaber |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> a Mandalorian lightsaber that has appeared previously in [[List of Star Wars television series#Animated series|''Star Wars'' animated series]].<ref name=\"Knox0211\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5756064/mandalorian-finale-darksaber/|title=The Darksaber Made a Crucial Appearance in ''The Mandalorian''{{'s}} Season Finale. Here's Its Significance in ''Star Wars'' Lore|last=Dockterman|first=Eliana|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=December 28, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105085326/https://time.com/5756064/mandalorian-finale-darksaber/|archivedate=January 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/the-mandalorian-finale-recap-black-lightsaber|title=''The Mandalorian'' Season Finale: What is the Darksaber?|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|author-link=Anthony Breznican|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=December 27, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200111175049/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/the-mandalorian-finale-recap-black-lightsaber|archivedate=January 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}} The Mandalorian leaves with the Child, while Karga and Dune stay behind.\n |LineColor       = C4A574\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2===<!-- Per WP:TVUPCOMING, do NOT add a year until an episode has been released. Thank you! -->\nFamuyiwa,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://discussingfilm.net/2019/08/21/rick-famuyiwa-set-to-direct-episodes-of-the-mandalorian-season-2-exclusive |title=Rick Famuyiwa Set To Direct Episodes Of \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2 (EXCLUSIVE) |date=August 21, 2019 |website=Discussing Film |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321062633/https://discussingfilm.net/2019/08/21/rick-famuyiwa-set-to-direct-episodes-of-the-mandalorian-season-2-exclusive |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Favreau, Filoni, and [[Carl Weathers]] will direct episodes in the season.<ref name=\"S2FilmingWrap\" /> The season will premiere in October 2020.<ref name=\"S2Premiere\" />\n\n== Production ==\n=== Background ===\nA live-action ''Star Wars'' TV series entered production in early 2009, with over 50 scripts written by 2012, but they were deemed too expensive to produce due to their complex content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://denofgeek.com/movies/rick-mccallum/21562/rick-mccallum-interview-dennis-potter-star-wars-tv-series-george-lucas-red-tails |title=Rick McCallum interview: Dennis Potter, Star Wars TV series, George Lucas & Red Tails |last=Peaty |first=James |date=June 3, 2012 |website=[[Den of Geek]] |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819171150/http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/rick-mccallum/21562/rick-mccallum-interview-dennis-potter-star-wars-tv-series-george-lucas-red-tails |archive-date=August 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Its title was to have been ''[[Star Wars: Underworld]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2012/01/09/is-this-the-star-wars-live-action-shows-title |title=Is This the ''Star Wars'' Live-Action Show's Title? |last=Collura |first=Scott |date=January 9, 2012 |website=IGN |access-date=March 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228085206/http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/01/09/is-this-the-star-wars-live-action-shows-title |archive-date=February 28, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2013, following the October 30, 2012 sale of [[Lucasfilm]] to [[The Walt Disney Company]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC television network]] president [[Paul Lee (television executive)|Paul Lee]] spoke to the current status of the series commenting that \"We'd love to do something with Lucasfilm, we're not sure what yet. We haven't even sat down with them. We're going to look at [the live-action series], we're going to look at all of them, and see what's right. We weren't able to discuss this with them until [the acquisition] closed and it just closed. It's definitely going to be part of the conversation.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/2013/01/10/star-wars-live-action-tv-series-3/ |title=ABC to look at 'Star Wars' live-action TV series |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=January 10, 2013 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714170844/http://www.ew.com/article/2013/01/10/star-wars-live-action-tv-series-3/ |archive-date=July 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2014, more details regarding the series were revealed, including that [[Boba Fett]] would have appeared.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/06/cancelled-star-wars-underworld-tv-series-would-have-featured-young-versions-of-han-chewie-lando-84952/ |title=Cancelled 'Star Wars: Underworld' TV Series Would Have Featured Young Versions Of Han, Chewie & Lando |last=Lyttelton |first=Oliver |date=June 11, 2014 |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004144928/https://www.indiewire.com/2014/06/cancelled-star-wars-underworld-tv-series-would-have-featured-young-versions-of-han-chewie-lando-84952/ |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Jon Favreau 2016.jpeg|thumb|upright|Jon Favreau initially pitched the idea for ''The Mandalorian''.]]\nIn 2019, Jon Favreau revealed to ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' that he had first pitched the idea for what became ''The Mandalorian'' to Kennedy during the summer of 2017, while directing the photorealistic remake of ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]'' for [[Walt Disney Pictures]].<ref name=\"Keegan\">{{cite news |last1=Keegan |first1=Rebecca |title=In Baby Yoda, Hollywood Sees Its Past, Present and Meme-able Future |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/baby-yoda-represents-past-present-future-hollywood-1263588 |accessdate=December 29, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=December 19, 2019 |location=Los Angeles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230193122/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/baby-yoda-represents-past-present-future-hollywood-1263588 |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Kennedy put Favreau in touch with Filoni, and when the two men met, Filoni began to draw doodles on napkins of what would become The Child.<ref name=\"Keegan\" />  After each day of work on ''The Lion King's'' virtual reality set in [[Playa Vista, Los Angeles|Playa Vista]], Favreau would then stay late and work a few more hours developing his secret television project for Lucasfilm.<ref name=\"Keegan\" />\n\nOn November 9, 2017, Walt Disney Company chairman and CEO [[Bob Iger]], while on a quarterly earnings call with investors, announced that Disney and Lucasfilm were developing a new live-action ''Star Wars'' television series for Disney's [[Disney+|then-unnamed upcoming streaming service]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-live-action-series-launch-disney-streaming-service-1056755 |title='Star Wars' Live-Action TV Series to Launch on Disney Streaming Service |last=Stanhope |first=Kate |last2=Jarvey |first2=Natalie |date=November 9, 2017 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005072112/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-live-action-series-launch-disney-streaming-service-1056755 |archive-date=October 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/biz/news/star-wars-tv-series-disney-streaming-service-1202611408/ |title=New 'Star Wars' Trilogy in Works With Rian Johnson, TV Series Also Coming to Disney Streaming Service |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=November 9, 2017 |website=Variety |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6ush9b0jh?url=http://variety.com/2017/biz/news/star-wars-tv-series-disney-streaming-service-1202611408/ |archive-date=November 10, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 6, 2018, it was reported that Iger had revealed during another financial report conference call with investors that multiple ''Star Wars'' live-action series were actually in development by Disney saying, \"We are developing not just one, but a few ''Star Wars'' series specifically for the Disney direct-to-consumer app. We've mentioned that and we are close to being able to reveal at least one of the entities that is developing that for us. Because the deal isn't completely closed, we can't be specific about that. I think you'll find the level of talent ... on the television front will be rather significant as well.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-tv-series-disney-developing-a-few-streaming-service-1082523 |title='Star Wars' TV Series: Disney Developing \"a Few\" for Its Streaming Service |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |last2=Couch |first2=Aaron |date=February 6, 2018 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004202538/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/star-wars-tv-series-disney-developing-a-few-streaming-service-1082523 |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2018, Lucasfilm announced that Favreau was the writer and executive producer of the forthcoming series.<ref name=\"FavreauWrite\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/08/iron-man-filmmaker-jon-favreau-will-create-a-star-wars-tv-series/ |title='Iron Man' filmmaker Jon Favreau will create a live-action 'Star Wars' series |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=March 8, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005112016/https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/08/iron-man-filmmaker-jon-favreau-will-create-a-star-wars-tv-series/ |archive-date=October 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2018, Favreau stated that half of the scripts for the first season had been completed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/jon-favreau-star-wars-tv-series-details-exclusive-nerdist-news/ |title=Exclusive Details on Jon Favreau's STAR WARS TV Series {{!}} Nerdist |last=Marnell |first=Blair |date=May 11, 2018 |website=[[Nerdist]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512022354/https://nerdist.com/jon-favreau-star-wars-tv-series-details-exclusive-nerdist-news/ |archive-date=May 12, 2018 |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comingsoon.net/tv/news/945169-jon-favreau-confirms-setting-script-status-of-star-wars-series |title=Jon Favreau Confirms Setting, Script Status of Star Wars Series |last=Evry |first=Max |date=May 11, 2018 |website=[[ComingSoon.net]] |access-date=August 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718050935/http://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/945169-jon-favreau-confirms-setting-script-status-of-star-wars-series |archive-date=July 18, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 3, Favreau announced that the series had been titled ''The Mandalorian'' and revealed the show's central premise.<ref name=\"TitlePremise\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-jon-favreau-tv-the-mandalorian-1202968077/ |title='Star Wars': Jon Favreau Reveals TV Series Details |last=Holloway |first=Daniel |date=October 3, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=October 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004021613/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-jon-favreau-tv-the-mandalorian-1202968077/ |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following day, it was revealed that additional executive producers would include [[Dave Filoni]], [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]], and [[Colin Wilson (film producer)|Colin Wilson]] with Karen Gilchrist acting as a co-executive producer. Filoni was also expected to direct the series' first episode with additional directors including [[Taika Waititi]], [[Bryce Dallas Howard]], [[Rick Famuyiwa]], and [[Deborah Chow]].<ref name=\"Directors\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-the-mandalorian-directors-first-look-1202969766/ |title=Bryce Dallas Howard, Taika Waititi, and More to Direct 'Star Wars' Live-Action TV Series |last=Stedman |first=Alex |date=October 4, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=October 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005030117/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/star-wars-the-mandalorian-directors-first-look-1202969766/ |archive-date=October 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 19, StarWars.com announced that [[Ludwig G\u00f6ransson]] would compose the musical score for the series.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/19/black-panther-composer-ludwig-goransson-star-wars-mandalorian/ |title='Black Panther' composer Ludwig G\u00f6ransson will write music for 'The Mandalorian' |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=December 19, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=December 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220015829/https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/19/black-panther-composer-ludwig-goransson-star-wars-mandalorian/ |archive-date=December 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ludwig Goransson to Compose Score for the Mandalorian |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/ludwig-goransson-to-compose-score-for-the-mandalorian |publisher=Star Wars |accessdate=3 March 2020 |date=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 12, 2019, during a press conference for ''The Lion King'' remake, Favreau revealed that he had written scripts for the second season and that pre-production was underway.<ref name=\"Season2\">{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-mandalorian-season-2-filming-jon-favreau |title=Exclusive: Jon Favreau Says He's Already Writing and Pre-Shooting 'The Mandalorian' Season 2 |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=July 12, 2019 |website=[[Collider]] |access-date=July 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712193523/http://collider.com/the-mandalorian-season-2-filming-jon-favreau/ |archive-date=July 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Favreau plans to direct an episode of the second season, and stated that he was too busy with the production of ''The Lion King'' to direct any of the series' first season.<ref name=\"plans\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/09/jon-favreau-mandalorian-season-2/ |title=Jon Favreau plans to direct a 'Mandalorian' season 2 episode himself |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=September 9, 2019 |website=EW.com |access-date=September 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913224159/https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/09/jon-favreau-mandalorian-season-2/ |archive-date=September 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an interview with [[Pedro Pascal]], The Mandalorian's name was revealed to be \"Din Djarin\".<ref name=\"Mandalorian Name\">{{Cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-real-name-confirmed-dyn-jarren/ |title=The Mandalorian's Real Name Revealed |last=Zinski |first=Dan |date=November 13, 2019 |website=[[Screen Rant]] |access-date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113194128/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-real-name-confirmed-dyn-jarren/ |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nBy November 2018, Pascal, [[Gina Carano]], and [[Nick Nolte]] had been cast in starring roles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/star-wars-pedro-pascal-mandalorian-series-1203023818/ |title=''Star Wars'': Pedro Pascal to Lead ''The Mandalorian'' Series |last=Kroll |first=Justin |last2=Otterson |first2=Joe |date=November 13, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=November 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114000343/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/star-wars-pedro-pascal-mandalorian-series-1203023818/ |archive-date=November 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-pedro-pascal-talks-disney-streaming-series-1202501235/ |title=''The Mandalorian'' Targets Pedro Pascal For Title Role In Disney+ Series |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |date=November 13, 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=November 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113232557/https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-pedro-pascal-talks-disney-streaming-series-1202501235/ |archive-date=November 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gina-carano-joins-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1160809 |title=''Star Wars'': Gina Carano Joins 'The Mandalorian' |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=November 14, 2018 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=November 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115112924/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gina-carano-joins-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1160809 |archive-date=November 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/nick-nolte-joins-pedro-pascal-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1164696 |title='Star Wars': Nick Nolte Joins Pedro Pascal in 'The Mandalorian' (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=November 30, 2018 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201003051/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/nick-nolte-joins-pedro-pascal-star-wars-series-mandalorian-1164696 |archive-date=December 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> After meeting with Favreau, Pascal initially thought he would be playing Boba Fett.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/09/15/star-wars-the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-thought-boba-fett/ |title=Star Wars: Pedro Pascal Thought He Was Playing Boba Fett in The Mandalorian |last=Schmidt |first=JK |date=September 14, 2019 |website=comicbook.com |access-date=September 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916063850/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/09/15/star-wars-the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-thought-boba-fett/ |archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 12, 2018, LucasFilm announced that [[Giancarlo Esposito]], [[Carl Weathers]], [[Emily Swallow]], [[Omid Abtahi]], and [[Werner Herzog]] had joined the main cast.<ref name=\"DeadlineCast\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/star-wars-the-mandaloriancast-disney-favreau-jedi-pascal-pedro-1202518897/ |title=''Star Wars: The Mandalorian'' Casting: Giancarlo Esposito, Carl Weathers and Werner Herzog Join Disney+ Series |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |date=December 12, 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213021650/https://deadline.com/2018/12/star-wars-the-mandaloriancast-disney-favreau-jedi-pascal-pedro-1202518897/ |archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 21, 2019, [[Taika Waititi]] was revealed to be recording a voice for the series, speculated to be bounty hunter droid [[IG-88]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/22/star-wars-it-looks-like-taika-waititi-is-ig-88-in-the-mandalorian |title=''Star Wars'': It Looks Like Taika Waititi Is IG-88 in ''The Mandalorian'' |last=Stevens |first=Colin |date=March 21, 2019 |website=IGN |access-date=March 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322030405/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/22/star-wars-it-looks-like-taika-waititi-is-ig-88-in-the-mandalorian |archive-date=March 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> but which turned out to be a new character named IG-11.<ref name=\"IG11\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/the-mandalorian-star-wars-celebration/ |title=The Mandalorian is described as Clint Eastwood in Star Wars |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=April 14, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414231148/https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/the-mandalorian-star-wars-celebration/ |archive-date=April 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Footage shown at [[Star Wars Celebration#Celebration Chicago|''Star Wars'' Celebration]] in April 2019 revealed that [[Bill Burr]] and [[Mark Boone Junior]] were in the series, with Burr portraying an outlaw.<ref name=\"BurrBoone\">{{Cite news |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/secret-footage-the-mandalorian/ |title=Here's what happened in the secret footage of ''The Mandalorian'' |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |date=April 14, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=April 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416053035/https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/14/secret-footage-the-mandalorian/ |archive-date=April 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[D23 Expo]] in August, it was revealed [[Ming-Na Wen]] would appear in the series.<ref name=\"Wen\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-ming-na-wen-joins-the-cast-of-the-disney-star-wars-series |title=The Mandalorian: Ming-Na Wen Joins the Cast of the Disney+ Star Wars Series |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |date=August 23, 2019 |website=[[IGN]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220180730/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-ming-na-wen-joins-the-cast-of-the-disney-star-wars-series |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Julia Jones]]'s casting was announced in September.<ref name=\"Julia\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-mandalorian-twilight-saga-actress-joins-cast-of-disney-live-action-star-wars-series-1202713442/ |title='The Mandalorian': Julia Jones Joins Cast of Disney+ Live-Action 'Star Wars' Series |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |last2=Boucher |first2=Geoff |date=September 6, 2019 |access-date=September 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906032029/https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-mandalorian-twilight-saga-actress-joins-cast-of-disney-live-action-star-wars-series-1202713442/ |archive-date=September 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, [[Rosario Dawson]] was reported to be appearing as [[Ahsoka Tano]] in the second season, which would be the character's first live-action on-screen appearance. Having previously appeared in the ''Star Wars'' animated media ''The Clone Wars'' ([[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|film]] and [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|television series]]) and ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]'', Ahsoka's voice was briefly heard in the live-action film ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]''; she was voiced by [[Ashley Eckstein]] in these appearances.<ref name=\"DawsonMandalorian\">{{cite web |last=Sciretta |first=Peter |title=Star Wars Exclusive: \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2 Casts Rosario Dawson as Ahsoka Tano |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/rosario-dawson-ahsoka-mandalorian/|website=[[/Film]] |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320174731/https://www.slashfilm.com/rosario-dawson-ahsoka-mandalorian/|archivedate=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Shortly after, [[Michael Biehn]] joined the cast as a bounty hunter.<ref name=\"BiehnCast\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\nPrincipal photography for the first season began during the first week of October 2018 in [[Southern California]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-star-wars-tv-series/ |title=''The Mandalorian'': Directors, First Photo, Details & More Revealed for Jon Favreau's ''Star Wars'' TV Series |last=Sciretta |first=Peter |date=October 4, 2018 |website=[[/Film]] |access-date=October 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004115434/https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-star-wars-tv-series/ |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 19, [[George Lucas]] visited the set of the series as a birthday surprise for Favreau;<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-mandalorian-set-photo-george-lucas/ |title=George Lucas Visits ''The Mandalorian'' Set in New Behind-the-Scenes Photo |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=October 19, 2018 |website=Collider |access-date=October 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020015520/http://collider.com/the-mandalorian-set-photo-george-lucas/ |archive-date=October 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> it was later revealed that Lucas had some level of involvement in creating the show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-mandalorian-filming-details-giancarlo-esposito/ |title='The Mandalorian' Actor Giancarlo Esposito Describes the New Technology Used on the 'Star Wars' Show |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=April 18, 2019 |website=Collider |access-date=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422214859/http://collider.com/the-mandalorian-filming-details-giancarlo-esposito/ |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 25, it was reported that police were investigating the grand theft of several unspecified items from ''The Mandalorian''{{'s}} set at the Manhattan Beach Studios campus in [[Manhattan Beach, California]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grand-theft-investigated-at-studio-hosting-high-profile-projects-1154992 |title=Grand Theft Investigated at Studio Hosting ''Star Wars'' TV Show 'The Mandalorian' |last=Parker |first=Ryan |date=October 25, 2018 |access-date=October 26, 2018 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026010951/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grand-theft-investigated-at-studio-hosting-high-profile-projects-1154992 |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-set-theft-investigation/ |title=''Star Wars'': Police Investigating Theft On ''Mandalorian'' Set |last=Agar |first=Chris |date=October 25, 2018 |access-date=October 26, 2018 |website=[[Screen Rant]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026055443/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-set-theft-investigation/ |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming for the first season wrapped on February 27, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-mandalorian-disney-wraps-filming-on-jon-favreaus-star-wars-tv-show/ |title=''The Mandalorian'': Disney+ Wraps Filming on Jon Favreau's 'Star Wars' TV Show |last=Baysinger |first=Tim |date=February 27, 2019 |access-date=February 27, 2019 |last2=Mass |first2=Jennifer |website=The Wrap}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Favreau, the first season was filmed on a large soundstage with a 360-degree [[video wall]] at Manhattan Beach Studios, supplemented by limited [[location shooting]] around Southern California.<ref name=\"Giardina\">{{cite news |last1=Giardina |first1=Carolyn |title=Why Jon Favreau Chose Baby Yoda: \"We Don't Know a Lot of Details About His Species\" |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=December 5, 2019 |location=Los Angeles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206084030/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The show sent camera crews to shoot distant locations like Iceland and Chile, the resulting digital assets were integrated into virtual sets built with the [[Unreal Engine|Unreal]] game engine from [[Epic Games]], and those sets were displayed on the video wall.<ref name=\"Giardina\" /> In Favreau's words: \"So, there is real photography being incorporated, but the actors aren't brought on location. The location is brought to the actors.\"<ref name=\"Giardina\" />\n\n[[Dave Filoni]], who is mostly renowned for his work on other ''Star Wars'' projects, and [[Bryce Dallas Howard]] were given individual freedom on directing their episodes, which was surprising to Howard's father [[Ron Howard]], who directed ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''.<ref>{{Citation |title=Bryce Dallas Howard's 'So Awesome' Experience Directing on \"The Mandalorian\" from IMDb at Toronto International Film Festival (2017-) |url=http://www.imdb.com/list/ls090647824/videoplayer/vi2661596953 |access-date=December 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911101432/https://www.imdb.com/list/ls090647824/videoplayer/vi2661596953 |archive-date=September 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> When Pascal would become unavailable for filming, the Mandalorian would occasionally be portrayed physically by stunt actors Brendan Wayne and [[Lateef Crowder dos Santos|Lateef Crowder]] with Wayne having worked closely with Pascal to develop the character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-double-stunt-performer.html|title=So, Who's Really Under the Mandalorian's Helmet?|last=Miller|first=Liz Shannon|date=December 9, 2019|website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|access-date=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209223508/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-pedro-pascal-double-stunt-performer.html|archive-date=December 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFilming for the second season started in mid-October 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2482786/the-mandalorian-season-2-has-already-begun-filming|title=The Mandalorian Season 2 Has Already Begun Filming|last=Hurley|first=Laura|work=Cinema Blend|date=October 21, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> and concluded on March 8, 2020.<ref name=\"S2FilmingWrap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-season-2-directors-include-dave-filoni/|title=\u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 Season 2 Bringing Back Dave Filoni to Direct Again|last=Anderton|first=Ethan|publisher=[[/Film]]|date=March 8, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Visual effects ===\nVisual effects studio [[Industrial Light & Magic]], a subsidiary of Lucasfilm, opened a new division in November 2018 targeted for streaming and episodic television called ILM TV. Based in London with support from the company's locations in San Francisco, Vancouver, and Singapore, it is expected that the new division will work extensively on live-action ''Star Wars'' television series, starting with ''The Mandalorian''.<ref name=\"ILMTV\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/artisans/news/george-lucas-star-wars-ilm-launches-tv-unit-1203022007/ |title=ILM Launches TV Unit to Serve Episodic and Streaming Content |last=Caranicas |first=Peter |date=November 7, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=November 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116072921/https://variety.com/2018/artisans/news/george-lucas-star-wars-ilm-launches-tv-unit-1203022007/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Unreal Engine 4]], a [[game engine]] developed by [[Epic Games]], is used to create the digital backgrounds. It makes the rendering of the visual effects faster than would normally be possible for a live-action series, and Favreau said the technology can be applied to a variety of challenges. So rather than using sketches on a whiteboard to map out scenes, the storyboarding was done on the game engine.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2019-07-26/disneys-lion-king-remake-is-a-hit-its-virtual-reality-technology-could-change-how-movies-are-made |title='The Lion King's' VR helped make a hit. It could also change movie making |date=July 26, 2019 |website=Los Angeles Times |access-date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729221049/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2019-07-26/disneys-lion-king-remake-is-a-hit-its-virtual-reality-technology-could-change-how-movies-are-made |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/jon-favreau-confirms-season-two-mandalorian-already-pre-production-2806291 |title=Jon Favreau Confirms Season Two Of 'The Mandalorian' Is Already In Pre-Production |last=Billings |first=Kevin |date=July 12, 2019 |website=International Business Times |access-date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729144244/https://www.ibtimes.com/jon-favreau-confirms-season-two-mandalorian-already-pre-production-2806291 |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/20/21145671/mandalorian-sets-stagecraft-epic-games-ilm-fortnite-baby-yoda-digital | title = How The Mandalorian teamed up with Fortnite creator Epic Games to create its digital sets | first=  Chaim | last =Gartenberg | date = February 20, 2020 | accessdate = February 20, 2020 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nThe music for ''The Mandalorian'' is composed by [[Ludwig G\u00f6ransson]]. Each chapter has its own soundtrack album, released the same day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-1-original-score/1486687329 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 1 (Original Score) |date=November 12, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204020906/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-1-original-score/1486687329 |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-2-original-score/1487534284 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 2 (Original Score) |date=November 15, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204080227/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-2-original-score/1487534284 |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-3-original-score/1488169340 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 3 (Original Score) |date=November 22, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127214544/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-3-original-score/1488169340 |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-4-original-score/1489004142 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 4 (Original Score) |date=November 29, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=November 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204020838/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-4-original-score/1489004142 |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-5-original-score/1489518198 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 5 (Original Score) |date=December 6, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206132926/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-5-original-score/1489518198 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-6-original-score/1490621791 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 6 (Original Score) |date=December 13, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213120731/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-6-original-score/1490621791 |archive-date=December 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-7-original-score/1491415764 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 7 (Original Score) |date=December 18, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219113655/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-7-original-score/1491415764 |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-8-original-score/1492195968 |title=The Mandalorian: Chapter 8 (Original Score) |date=December 27, 2019 |website=[[Apple Music]] |access-date=December 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227233406/https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-mandalorian-chapter-8-original-score/1492195968 |archive-date=December 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> For the score, G\u00f6ransson played many of the key instruments himself, and then added a 70-piece orchestra. He wrote four hours of music for the eight episodes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burlingame |first1=Jon |title=Composer Takes Music for the \u2018Star Wars\u2019 Series \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 to a New Universe |url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/star-wars-mandalorian-music-1203402950/ |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |publisher=Variety |date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217184801/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/star-wars-mandalorian-music-1203402950/ |archive-date=December 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n===Parenting and fatherhood===\nOne of the primary themes of ''The Mandalorian'' is [[parenting]] and [[Father|fatherhood]], particularly through the father-son relationship dynamic between the Mandalorian and the Child.<ref name=\"Britt1129\">{{cite news |last=Britt |first=Ryan |title=Baby Yoda, Daddy Mando, and How Star Wars Gave Parents a New Fantasy |work=[[Fatherly]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.fatherly.com/play/baby-yoda-star-wars-the-mandalorian-adults/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Singer1213\">{{cite news |last=Singer |first=Matt |title='The Mandalorian' Is A Good Show About How Hard It Is to Be a Single Parent |work=[[Townsquare Media#Web publications and services|ScreenCrush]] |date=December 13, 2019 |url=https://screencrush.com/the-mandalorian-episode-6-recap-single-dad/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Chase1216\">{{cite news |last=Chase |first=Eileen |title=Why The Mandalorian is, in fact, a show about a single dad |work=[[Today (American TV program)|Today]] |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://community.today.com/parentingteam/post/why-the-mandalorian-is-in-fact-a-show-about-a-single-dad |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Ryan Britt of ''[[Fatherly]]'' wrote that this is unusual in ''Star Wars'' stories, and that past examples of parenting in the franchise have tended to be poor ones, from the murderous [[Darth Vader]] (father of [[Luke Skywalker]]) to the neglectful [[List of Star Wars characters#Galen Erso|Galen Erso]], father of [[Jyn Erso]] in ''[[Rogue One]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> Britt wrote: \"For years the Star Wars franchise avoided depicting a parent-child dynamic. With Mando and Baby Yoda, that's finally changing.\"<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> The dynamic between Kuiil and IG-11 also reflect the childrearing theme in ''The Mandalorian''. The two have a relationship similar to that of a father and son, as demonstrated in the scene in which Kuiil teaches IG-11 how to operate and function after the droid is reprogrammed.<ref name=\"Phipps1218\">{{cite news |last=Phipps |first=Keith |title=''The Mandalorian'' Recap: Bait and Switch (and Switch) |work=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-recap-chapter-7-the-reckoning.html |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219022023/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-recap-chapter-7-the-reckoning.html |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' writer Kathryn VanArendonk argued that parenting has been the subject of past ''Star Wars'' stories, but almost always during later stages of parenthood, rather than an infant in early stages such as the Child. As examples, she cited [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] serving as a mentor to the adolescent Anakin Skywalker, [[Princess Leia]] lamenting over her grown son [[Kylo Ren]], or the absence of [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]]'s parents.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\">{{cite news |last=VanArendonk |first=Kathryn |title=''The Mandalorian'' Doesn\u2019t Care About Diapers |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=January 3, 2020 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/the-mandalorian-parenting-fatherhood-archetype.html |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Britt argued strong parental examples in ''Star Wars'' are important because the franchise is so often associated with the childhoods of its fans.<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> ''The Mandalorian'' particularly highlights the challenges of being a [[single parent]],<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /><ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> and a [[working parent]], as the Mandalorian struggles to continue his day job as a bounty hunter and mercenary while serving as the sole caretaker of the Child.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /><ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> Richard Newby of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' described the show as \"the adventures of a single dad looking for a job\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Newby |first=Richard |title=How 'The Mandalorian' Is Setting Up the Long Game |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 14, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/why-mandalorian-episode-5-didnt-include-mysterious-figure-1262747 |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Several reviewers have compared the dynamic between the Child and the Mandalorian to ''[[Lone Wolf and Cub]]'', a [[manga]] about a [[samurai]] warrior and his young son.<ref>{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Hannah |title=Somali and the Forest Spirit Will Fill The Mandalorian Hole in Your Life |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=January 4, 2020 |url=https://www.cbr.com/somali-and-the-forest-spirit-the-mandalorian-comparison/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pierce-Bohen |title=5 Westerns & 5 Samurai Movies To Watch If You Love The Mandalorian |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 23, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-westerns-samurai-movies-similar/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |title=How The Mandalorian's Plot Twist Evokes a Classic Manga Series |work=[[IGN]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/12/the-mandalorian-plot-twist-lone-wolf-and-cub |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Housman |first=Andrew |title=The Mandalorian: How the Series Takes Star Wars Back to Its Samurai Roots |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 20, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-lone-wolf-and-cub-influence/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Mandalorian's parental role in the series makes him a softer and more relatable character;<ref>{{cite news |last=Frank |first=Allegra |title=Baby Yoda: the Mandalorian's adorable alien co-star, explained |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/11/23/20972511/baby-yoda-meme-the-mandalorian-gif-star-wars |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> he changes in a positive way because of raising the Child, becoming less selfish and self-absorbed.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> He risked his life and drastically changed his career as a bounty hunter to accept his responsibility as the Child's caretaker and guardian,<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /><ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> marking a significant parental sacrifice.<ref name=\"Chase1216\" /> When the Mandalorian seeks work to earn money, he is now doing so to provide not only for himself, but for the Child as well.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> We see several examples of the Mandalorian parenting the Child throughout the series, such as when he stops the Child from pressing random buttons in the cockpit of the Mandalorian's spaceship, ultimately by holding him in his lap.<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> In another example, the Mandalorian establishes a [[car seat]] for the Child in the cockpit of his ship, so he can be seated safely and comfortably during their travels.<ref name=\"Atkin1230\">{{cite news |last=Atkin |first=Jessie |title=5 Reasons The Witcher Geralt Will Be a Better Dad Than the Mandalorian (& 5 Reasons He Won't) |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 30, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/5-reasons-the-witcher-geralt-will-be-a-better-dad-than-the-mandalorian-5-reasons-he-wont/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe relationship between the Mandalorian and the Child is an example of unexpected fatherhood.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /><ref name=\"Pereira1129\">{{cite news |last=Pereira |first=Sergio |title=The Mandalorian Is Basically Big Daddy in Space |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-big-daddy-in-space/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> The Mandalorian feels a connection and parental bond with the Child because of his own childhood, when he was orphaned upon the death of his parents and was adopted by the Mandalorian culture as a \"foundling\".<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> Nevertheless, fatherhood was not a role the Mandalorian was initially seeking, and he makes repeated initial attempts to avoid this responsibility.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> He first does so in \"Chapter 3: The Sin\", when he first leave the Child with the Client.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> He does so again in \"Chapter 4\" Sanctuary\", when he plans to leave the Child with Omera, a protective mother on the planet Sorgan, who is willing to take the Child into her own family.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> The Mandalorian does not fully commit to the role of fatherhood until the first-season finale, \"Chapter 8: Redemption\", when the Child himself is also adopted into the Mandalorian culture as a \"foundling\" and the Mandalorian is formally declared to be his father figure.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" />\n\nSeveral writers suggested the fact that the Mandalorian's face is concealed has a [[tabula rasa]] effect and his anonymity allows viewers to see and imagine themselves as parents.<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /><ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> Britt said this \"allow(s) us to dream about what arsenal we might deploy to protect our children\".<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> However, Singer said the show's setting in space make the challenges of child-rearing seem more exciting and exotic than they might otherwise be.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> Anthony Breznican of ''Vanity Fair'' has noted that none of the day-to-day difficulties of parenthood are portrayed in the series: \"There is no shrill squawking from Baby Yoda, no tantrum, no spit-up, no uncontrollable shrieking that burrows into a parent's psyche like a dentist's drill shredding a soft, pink nerve.\"<ref name=\"Breznican1126\">{{cite news |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |title=Baby Yoda Has Conquered the World |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 26, 2019 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127163301/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Likewise, ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' writer Kathryn VanArendonk said the show ignores or does not address many parenting details that make fatherhood difficult, such as what the Child eats, when he goes him to sleep, and whether he wears diapers. She wrote: \"''The Mandalorian'' is uninterested in diapers, and so Mando gets to be a very particular image of fatherhood: the guy who doesn't have to sweat the small stuff.\"<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> VanAnderonk described this as a [[wish fulfillment]] fantasy for parents or prospective parents: \"a vision of parenting stripped so thoroughly of all detail and specificity that all that's left are archetypes: the parent, the child\".<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" />\n\nThe Child encounters a handful of other protector figures throughout the first season, including Omera, IG-11, and Peli Motto.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> Some observers have criticized the series for the fact that the Mandalorian repeatedly leaves the Child alone or in the hands of relative strangers,<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> as well as for making decisions that place the Child in danger. One example is in \"Chapter 6: The Prisoner\", when he allows a team of dangerous mercenaries to use his ship while the Child is on board, nearly resulting in the Child's death.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /><ref name=\"White1218\">{{cite news |last=White |first=Brett |title=Is Baby Yoda Bad to the Bone? This Week's 'The Mandalorian' Has Us Wondering |work=[[New York Post|Decider]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://decider.com/2019/12/18/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-evil/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> An interaction the Mandalorian has with Peli Motto in \"Chapter 5: The Gunslinger\" is one of the most overt discussions about the challenges of caring for the Child. When the Mandalorian accidentally wakes the child, who had been sleeping in Peli's arms, she chides him: \"Do you have any idea how long it took me to get it to sleep?\"<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> She also condemns the Mandalorian for leaving the child alone on the ship, saying: \"you have an awful lot to learn about raising a young one\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Keane |first=Sean |title=The Mandalorian episode 5 recap: Baby Yoda travels to an iconic planet |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 7, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-5-the-gunslinger-recap-baby-yoda-travels-to-an-iconic-planet/ |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Townsquare Media#Web publications and services|ScreenCrush]]'' writer Matt Singer argued the Mandalorian's parenting errors makes the show that much more appealing because making mistakes is a large part of being a parent.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> Eileen Chase of ''[[Today (American TV program)|Today]]'' echoed this: \"He is not an ideal parent, just like the rest of us who have to balance parenting and work.\"<ref name=\"Chase1216\" />\n\n===Good and evil; nature versus nurture===\nThe nature of good and evil and the question of [[nature versus nurture]] is raised repeatedly throughout ''The Mandalorian'', perhaps most overtly through by Kuiil's reprogramming of IG-11 from a bounty hunter to a nurse droid and protector. <ref name=\"Phipps1227\">{{cite news |last=Phipps |first=Keith |title=''The Mandalorian'' Season Finale Recap: Tragedy of the Manufacturer's Protocol |work=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-season-1-finale-recap-episode-8-redemption.html |accessdate=January 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230211122/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-season-1-finale-recap-episode-8-redemption.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Milner1222\">{{cite news |last=Milner |first=Sarah Bea |title=The Mandalorian: Baby Yoda Learns About Good & Bad In A Powerful Way |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 22, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-makes-statement-nature-versus-nurture/ |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223125659/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-makes-statement-nature-versus-nurture/ |archive-date=December 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Even after IG-11 is reprogrammed, the Mandalorian does not believe he has truly changed, because he believes droids have an essential nature and that IG-11's nature remains murderous and untrustworthy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Libbey |first=Dirk |title=The Mandalorian: 6 Biggest Questions After Episode 8 |work=CinemaBlend |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2487459/the-mandalorian-6-biggest-questions-after-episode-8 |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227204600/https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2487459/the-mandalorian-6-biggest-questions-after-episode-8 |archive-date=December 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> But in reprogramming IG-11, Kuiil nurtures him and helps him to change; Kuiil feels that in the process of learning how to function again, IG-11 gained a new personality.<ref>{{cite news |last=Babu |first=Armaan |title='The Mandalorian': IG-11 and Kuiil's inspiring and heartwarming story deserves its own spinoff |work=Media Entertainment Arts WorldWide |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://meaww.com/the-mandalorian-ig-11-kuiil-deserves-its-own-spinoff-star-wars-disney-396037 |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Kuiil insists to the Mandalorian: \"Droids are not good or bad \u2014 they are neutral reflections of those who program them.\"<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /> Keith Phipps of ''[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]]'' wrote of IG-11 and the nature versus nurture theme: \"He's not bad. He's just programmed that way, and with care and change he can do a lot of good in the world.\"<ref name=\"Phipps1227\" />\n\nThe Kuiil and IG-11 scenes also demonstrate that the way in which the \"child\" character is raised makes a significant difference in whether the child becomes an asset or a threat to those around him. The droid was a dangerous assassin before Kuiil reprogrammed him, but thanks to the Ugnaught's parenting, he becomes a protector and helper instead.<ref name=\"Phipps1218\" /> Some writers have likewise suggested the Child is not inherently good or evil,<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Foy1221\" /> but that instead, like all children, he is impressionable and does not fully understand the events occurring around him. He is learning about the world around him and needs guidance as he develops his abilities.<ref name=\"White1218\" /><ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Burwick1219\">{{cite news |last=Burwick |first=Kevin |title=Baby Yoda Might Be Evil in The Mandalorian, Is He Wielding the Dark Side of the Force? |work=TVweb |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://tvweb.com/baby-yoda-evil-the-mandalorian-dark-side-force/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> It will largely fall to the Mandalorian to provide this guidance,<ref name=\"White1218\" /> as when the Mandalorian stops him from strangling Cara Dune.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" />\n\nHowever, multiple writers have questioned whether the violent acts the Child has repeatedly witnessed throughout ''The Mandalorian'' are having a negative impact on his development, and that he is learning to become violent himself as a result.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> Phipps wrote of this: \"That look of wonder in the Child's eyes as IG-11 kills and kills again is hilarious, but also a little chilling.\"<ref name=\"Phipps1227\" /> One particular scene in \"Chapter 7: The Reckoning\" led many reviewers and fans to question whether the Child may be demonstrating [[evil]] tendencies. During a scene on the Mandalorian's spaceship, the Child observes as the Mandalorian and Cara Dune engage in a friendly [[arm wrestling]] match. During the contest, the Child uses the Force to choke Cara, nearly strangling her before the Mandalorian intervened.<ref name=\"Foy1221\">{{cite news |last=Foy |first=Peter |title=The Mandalorian: Could Baby Yoda Actually Be... [Spoiler]? |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=December 21, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-actually-evil/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Burwick1219\" /><ref name=\"Gallagher1226\">{{cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Caitlin |title=Is Baby Yoda Evil On 'The Mandalorian'? The Force Choke Means He Could Join The Dark Side |work=[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]] |date=December 26, 2019 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/is-baby-yoda-evil-on-the-mandalorian-the-force-choke-means-he-could-join-the-dark-side-19629941 |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> Throughout the ''Star Wars'' franchise, that ability has been most commonly associated with the Dark Side of the Force, particularly Darth Vader.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /><ref name=\"Hibberd1218\" /><ref name=\"Miller1218\" />\n\nSarah Bea Milner of ''Screen Rant'' wrote: \"The moment is genuinely shocking \u2014 and more than a little disturbing.\"<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /> Some reviewers noted, however, that the Child likely mistakenly believed the Mandalorian was in danger and intervened to help.<ref name=\"Miller1218\">{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Matt |title=We Regret to Inform You Baby Yoda Might Be Evil |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a30272695/evil-baby-yoda-force-choke-the-mandalorian-episode-7/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Hedash1219\">{{cite news |last=Hedash |first=Kara |title=Wait... Is Baby Yoda Tempted By The Dark Side? |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-force-choke-dark-side/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, in the same episode, the Child uses Force healing to save Greef Karga, a power typically associated with the Light Side.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Foy1221\" /><ref name=\"Hedash1219\" /> Nevertheless, some writers have suggested viewers had been underestimating the Child's capacity for evil because he is so adorable.<ref name=\"Miller1218\" /><ref name=\"Hibberd1218\">{{cite news |last=Hibberd |first=James |title=What if Baby Yoda is secretly evil? |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/18/evil-baby-yoda/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Abdulbaki0106\">{{cite news |last=Abdulbaki |first=Mae |title='Mandalorian' Season 2 theory links Baby Yoda to a Dark side icon |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=January 6, 2020 |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/62121-mandalorian-season-2-theory-baby-yoda-prophecy-anakin-skywalker |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> Fans speculated the Child could be presenting a false personality or using the Force to manipulate people into caring about him to help ensure his survival.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> However, Caitlin Gallagher of ''[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]]'' suggested rather than building toward making the Child evil, the show could be suggesting the Mandalorian needs to find a way to raise the Child in a less violent environment.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" />\n\n== Marketing ==\nOn October 4, 2018, the first promotional image from the series was released, featuring a Mandalorian with a rifle.<ref name=\"Directors\" /> About a week later, Favreau released a photo through his official Instagram account featuring a rifle with a two-pronged barrel, an apparent callback to Boba Fett's weapon in ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mashable.com/article/star-wars-mandalorian-holiday-special-boba-fett-blaster/#21yD0UDQ1Oq6 |title=Jon Favreau's upcoming 'Star Wars' TV series nods to the infamous 'Holiday Special' |last=Rosenberg |first=Adam |date=October 13, 2018 |website=[[Mashable]] |access-date=October 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014155925/https://mashable.com/article/star-wars-mandalorian-holiday-special-boba-fett-blaster/#21yD0UDQ1Oq6 |archive-date=October 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-rifle-from-the-mandalorian-is-a-blast-from-star-war-1829729845 |title=The Rifle From The Mandalorian Is a Blast From Star Wars' Silliest Past |last=Muncy |first=Julie |date=October 13, 2018 |website=[[io9]] |access-date=October 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014113418/https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-rifle-from-the-mandalorian-is-a-blast-from-star-war-1829729845 |archive-date=October 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Jon Favreau]], [[Dave Filoni]], and the main cast hosted a panel for ''The Mandalorian'' at ''Star Wars'' Celebration Chicago on April 14, 2019, where the first footage premiered to fans in attendance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |title=SWCC 2019: 9 THINGS WE LEARNED FROM THE MANDALORIAN PANEL |website=[[Star Wars]] |access-date=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415024016/https://www.starwars.com/news/swcc-2019-9-things-we-learned-from-the-mandalorian-panel |archive-date=April 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first official poster and trailer were released at the [[D23 Expo]] on August 23, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-first-poster-revealed-for-star-wars-disney-show |title=The Mandalorian: First Poster Revealed for Star Wars Disney+ Show |last=Wade |first=Jessie |date=August 23, 2019 |website=[[IGN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824101415/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/23/the-mandalorian-first-poster-revealed-for-star-wars-disney-show |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://time.com/5657961/the-mandalorian-trailer-second-by-second-breakdown/ |title=The Mandalorian Trailer: Everything We Learned at D23 |last=Dockterman |first=Eliana |date=August 24, 2019 |website=[[TIME]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824044324/https://time.com/5657961/the-mandalorian-trailer-second-by-second-breakdown/ |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> A second and final trailer was released on October 28, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-star-wars-trailer-2/amp/ |title=The Mandalorian releases action-packed second trailer |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=October 28, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |url-status=live |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112015133/https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/28/the-mandalorian-star-wars-trailer-2/amp/ }}</ref> On November 11, a sneak peek was released during ''[[Monday Night Football]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/amp-articles/the-mandalorian-arrives-tomorrow-but-a-special-sne/1100-6471348/ |title=The Mandalorian Arrives Tomorrow, But A Special Sneak Peek Releases Tonight |last=Elfring |first=Mat |date=November 11, 2019 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=live |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112014640/https://www.gamespot.com/amp-articles/the-mandalorian-arrives-tomorrow-but-a-special-sne/1100-6471348/ }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Mandalorian'' premiered on the [[streaming service]] [[Disney+]] on November 12, 2019 in the United States.<ref name=\"Disney+ReleaseDate\">{{Cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-mandalorian-will-be-available-on-disney-from-day-o-1833985687/amp |title=The Mandalorian Will Premiere on Disney+ November 12 |last=Whitbrook |first=James |date=April 11, 2019 |website=io9.gizmodo.com |access-date=April 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412063838/https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-mandalorian-will-be-available-on-disney-from-day-o-1833985687/amp |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is available in [[4K resolution|4K]] [[High dynamic range video|HDR]], though analysis found its luminance to be well below typical HDR standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2019/11/disneys-the-mandalorian-joins-a-long-list-of-fake-hdr-content-analysis-finds/|title=Disney+\u2019s The Mandalorian joins a long list of fake HDR content, analysis finds|last=Axon|first=Samuel|date=2019-11-26|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221151717/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2019/11/disneys-the-mandalorian-joins-a-long-list-of-fake-hdr-content-analysis-finds/|archive-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"4K\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewaltdisneycompany.com/disney-spotlights-comprehensive-direct-to-consumer-strategy-at-2019-investor-day/ |title=Disney Spotlights Comprehensive Direct-to-Consumer Strategy at 2019 Investor Day |date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=[[The Walt Disney Company]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413005151/https://www.thewaltdisneycompany.com/disney-spotlights-comprehensive-direct-to-consumer-strategy-at-2019-investor-day/ |archive-date=April 13, 2019 |access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref> Disney+ releases ''The Mandalorian'' episodes on a weekly basis, with the first two episodes released only a few days apart on November 12 and 15, 2019 respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/google-amp/news/the-mandalorian-release-schedule-on-disney-plus-has-leaked/ |title=The Mandalorian release schedule on Disney Plus has leaked |last=Reichert |first=Corinne |date=November 4, 2019 |website=[[CNET]] |url-status=live |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112015822/https://www.cnet.com/google-amp/news/the-mandalorian-release-schedule-on-disney-plus-has-leaked/ }}</ref> The seventh episode was released on December 18, 2019 instead of December 20, in order to attach a sneak preview of ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'', which came out on the latter date.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsarama.com/48116-the-mandalorian-changes-dates-for-special-tie-in-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker.html |title=The Mandalorian Changes Dates For Special Tie-In to Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker |last=Arrant |first=Chris |date=December 3, 2019 |website=[[Newsarama]] |url-status=live |access-date=December 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205143203/https://www.newsarama.com/48116-the-mandalorian-changes-dates-for-special-tie-in-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker.html |archive-date=December 5, 2019 }}</ref> When Disney+ became available in several European countries in late March 2020, episodes of ''The Mandalorian'' were available weekly, opposed to having all season one episodes available at the start,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-mandalorian-will-still-roll-out-weekly-when-disney-1841765999|title=The Mandalorian Will Still Roll Out Weekly When Disney+ Comes to Europe, Which Seems Dumb|last=Whitbrook|first=James|work=[[io9]]|date=February 18, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref> the first two episodes were available at launch on March 24, 2020, followed by the third on March 27, after which each episode were released weekly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a31783698/disney-plus-uk-launch-mandalorian-episodes-release/|title=Disney+ confirms how many episodes of The Mandalorian will be available on UK launch day|last=Davies|first=Megan|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The second season is set to premiere in October 2020.<ref name=\"S2Premiere\">{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/02/04/the-mandalorian-season-2-premiere-date-october/|title=''The Mandalorian'' Set for Early Return, Disney+ Marvel Slate Starts in August|first=Matt|last=Mitovitch|work=TVLine|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204223821/https://tvline.com/2020/02/04/the-mandalorian-season-2-premiere-date-october/|archive-date=February 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical response===\n{{Television Rotten Tomatoes scores\n| align = right\n| color = #C4A574\n| title = The Mandalorian\n| label = Season 1 \n| year  = 2019\n| ref   = <ref name=\"RTS1\" /> \n| 90 | 92 | 93 | 91 | 73 | 81 | 100 | 100\n}}\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 95% approval rating for the first season with an average rating of 8.23/10, based on 15 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Action-packed and expertly crafted\u2014if at times a bit too withholding\u2014''The Mandalorian'' is a welcome addition to the ''Star Wars'' universe that benefits greatly from the cuteness of its cargo.\"<ref name=\"RTS1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_mandalorian/s01|title=The Mandalorian: Season 1|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=December 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127180258/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_mandalorian/s01/|archive-date=November 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 69 out of 100, based on 27 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-mandalorian/season-1 |title=The Mandalorian \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211133837/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-mandalorian/season-1 |archive-date=December 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nZaki Hasan of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' said the show \"in essence allows the franchise to take a [[Mulligan (games)|mulligan]] with Boba Fett. Take the look, take that ineffable 'cool,' and transfer it over to an entirely new character who offers an untouched canvas, while giving the audience something that feels familiar.\" He added, \"Three episodes in, that's really all ''The Mandalorian'' is: a feeling. A good feeling, mind you, but rather than any specific storytelling quality, it's that feeling you're talking about. The visual effects, the sound effects, the overall look of the thing is all bang-on. This is a polished production that shows off every cent of its feature film budget on every frame of its run time.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/california-streamin-everyone-loves-the-mandalorian-for-now |title=Everyone loves 'The Mandalorian.' For now |last=Hasan |first=Zaki |date=November 15, 2019 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |access-date=November 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123175734/https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/california-streamin-everyone-loves-the-mandalorian-for-now |archive-date=November 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]'', Micah Peters said, \"''The Mandalorian'' may already be difficult to care about as something more than an installment that exists solely to set up the next installment. But there are still many enjoyable things about it, and also it's a Disney show with spaceships and giant sea slugs, so it doesn't need to be ''[[Citizen Kane]]''. It might, however, be the next great TV Western.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theringer.com/tv/2019/11/14/20965328/mandalorian-justified-westerns-star-wars-disney-plus-han-solo |title='The Mandalorian' Could Be the Best TV Western Since 'Justified' |last=Peters |first=Micah |date=November 14, 2019 |website=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |access-date=November 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125194302/https://www.theringer.com/tv/2019/11/14/20965328/mandalorian-justified-westerns-star-wars-disney-plus-han-solo |archive-date=November 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Audience viewership ===\n<!--AUDIENCE RECEPTION AND RATINGS: Do not include them! Wikipedia does not support user-generated content in its articles, and thus audience ratings cannot be included. Please refer to the talk page before proceeding to edit this section, and view the multiple discussions raised on the topic. No consensus has been formed to allow this article to differ from Wikipedia's guidelines and policies by including such content. Additions of audience ratings will be reverted.-->\nWithin four days of its release, ''The Mandalorian'' had stronger U.S. demand compared to four of 2019's biggest streaming originals: [[Netflix]]'s ''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]'', ''[[When They See Us]]'', ''[[The Dark Crystal: Age of Resistance]]'', and [[Amazon Prime Video]]'s ''[[Good Omens (TV series)|Good Omens]]''. [[TV Time]], a popular app allowing users to track shows and movies they are watching (or want to watch), stated that double the number of people compared to last week are interested in ''The Mandalorian'', and noted that it had the largest gain of any TV show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/the-mandalorian-demand-premiere-stranger-things-titans-1203409008/ |title='The Mandalorian' Demand Surges in Debut Week But Trails 'Stranger Things,' DC's 'Titans' |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=November 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121095559/https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/the-mandalorian-demand-premiere-stranger-things-titans-1203409008/ |archive-date=November 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMuch of the [[social media]] reaction has been to the show's [[breakout character]], a 50-year old \"infant\" of [[Yoda]]'s species, who was kept secret until the series' pilot episode aired.<ref>{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Travis |title=It was 'The Lion King' star Donald Glover's idea to keep Baby Yoda a secret |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/it-was-donald-glovers-idea-to-keep-baby-yoda-secret-2019-12 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=January 5, 2020 |date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230033331/https://www.businessinsider.com/it-was-donald-glovers-idea-to-keep-baby-yoda-secret-2019-12 |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian initially takes \"[[The Child (Star Wars)|The Child]]\" (the official name for the character) for a bounty, but ends up becoming its ''[[de facto]]'' guardian in order to protect it. It has been shown to have the powers of [[the Force]], and has been affably nicknamed \"Baby Yoda\".<ref name=BabyYoda /> The unexpected popularity of \"Baby Yoda\" led to an explosion of unofficial merchandise for the [[Christmas and holiday season]], which quickly sold out.<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/27/why-baby-yoda-merchandise-from-the-mandalorian-is-delayed.html |title='Baby Yoda' caught the merch industry off guard, and now they're trying to catch up |last=Whitten |first=Sarah |date=November 27, 2019 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213123053/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/27/why-baby-yoda-merchandise-from-the-mandalorian-is-delayed.html |archive-date=December 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/what-is-baby-yoda-in-the-mandalorian-our-wildest-theories-so-far/ |title=Who is 'Baby Yoda' in The Mandalorian? Here are some of our wildest theories so far |date=December 4, 2019 |website=[[CNET]] |access-date=December 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129091138/https://www.cnet.com/news/what-is-baby-yoda-in-the-mandalorian-our-wildest-theories-so-far/ |archive-date=November 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Awards table|5}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"10\" | <center>2020</center>\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[18th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n| Outstanding Visual Effects in a Photoreal Episode\n| [[Richard Bluff]], Abbigail Keller, Jason Porter, Hayden Jones, Roy Cancinon <small>(for \"[[Chapter 2: The Child]]\")</small>\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"6\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/ves-awards-nominations-2020-list-the-lion-king-the-mandalorian-game-of-thrones-1202823016/|title=VES Awards Nominations: \u2018The Lion King\u2019, \u2018Alita: Battle Angel\u2019, \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 & \u2018GoT\u2019 Top List|work=Deadline|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=January 7, 2020|accessdate=January 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109042040/https://deadline.com/2020/01/ves-awards-nominations-2020-list-the-lion-king-the-mandalorian-game-of-thrones-1202823016/|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|-\n| Outstanding Virtual Cinematography in a CG Project\n| [[Richard Bluff]], Jason Porter, Landis Fields IV, Baz Idione <small>(for \"[[Chapter 6: The Prisoner]]\"; The Roost)</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Animated Character in an Episode or Real-Time Project\n| Terry Bannon, Rudy Massar, Hugo Leygnac <small>(for \"The Child\"; Mudhorn)</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Model in a Photoreal or Animated Project\n| Doug Chiang, Jay Machado, John Goodson, Landis Fields IV <small>(for \"[[Chapter 3: The Sin]]\"; The Razorcrest)</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Created Environment in an Episode, Commercial, or Real-Time Project\n| Alex Murtaza, Yanick Gaudreau, Marco Tremblay, Maryse Bouchard (for Nevarro Town)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Effects Simulations in an Episode, Commercial, or Real-Time Project\n| Xavier Martin Ramirez, Ian Baxter, Fabio Slino, Andrea Rosa <small>(for \"Chapter 2: The Child\"; Mudhorn)</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|Art Directors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Art Directors Guild Award for Excellence in Production Design for a One-Hour Period or Fantasy Single-Camera Series|One-Hour Period or Fantasy Single-Camera Series]]\n| Andrew L. Jones <small>(for \"[[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\")</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/art-directors-guild-winners-2020-complete-list-1273722/item/period-film-art-directors-guild-award-winners-2020-1273734 |title='Parasite,' 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Win Art Directors Guild Awards |website=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Carolyn |last=Giardina |date=February 1, 2019 |accessdate=February 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202063346/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/art-directors-guild-winners-2020-complete-list-1273722/item/period-film-art-directors-guild-award-winners-2020-1273734 |archive-date=February 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[International Cinematographers Guild|Publicists Guild Awards]]\n| Maxwell Weinberg Publicist Showmanship Television Award\n| [[Disney+]]\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/icg-publicists-awards-2020-winners-list-1274564|title=ICG Publicists Awards: 'Joker,' 'The Mandalorian' Among Winners|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Carita|last=Rizzo|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Nebula Award]]\n| [[Ray Bradbury Award|Ray Bradbury Award for Outstanding Dramatic Presentation]]\n| [[Jon Favreau]] <small>(for \"The Child\")</small>\n| {{pending}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2019 Nebula Awards Finalists |url=https://www.tor.com/2020/02/20/announcing-the-2019-nebula-awards-finalists/ |website=Tor.com |accessdate=22 February 2020 |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Hugo Award]]\n| [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation#Short Form|Best Dramatic Presentation - Short Form]]\n| [[Jon Favreau]], [[Taika Waititi]] <small>(for \"Redemption\")</small>\n| {{pending}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2020-hugo-awards/|title=2020 Hugo Awards|publisher=The Hugo Awards|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Future==\nIn November 2019, [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|Walt Disney Studios]] chief creative officer [[Alan F. Horn|Alan Horn]] stated that if the series is successful, a film featuring the character could be developed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/disney-chief-scorsese-marvel-mandalorian-1203403513/ |title=Disney Studios Chief Alan Horn on Scorsese v. Marvel, Challenges in a Changing Business |last=Thorne |first=Will |date=November 13, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=November 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191114001553/https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/disney-chief-scorsese-marvel-mandalorian-1203403513/ |archive-date=November 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 5, 2019, when asked if characters from the series will appear in future ''Star Wars'' productions, Favreau said that \"There's definitely the opportunity to explore these characters beyond what has been presented on the show\", and that \"There's a very fluid line between what's in the movie theaters and what's on the screen at home\".<ref name=\"FavreauDirector\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |title=Why Jon Favreau Chose Baby Yoda: \"We Don't Know a Lot of Details About His Species\" |last=Giardina |first=Carolyn |date=December 5, 2019 |access-date=December 8, 2019 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206084030/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2020, Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]] said that spin-offs of ''The Mandalorian'' are being considered, stating that there is \"the possibility of infusing [the series] with more characters and taking those characters in their own direction in terms of series\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-bob-iger-teases-mandalorian-falcon-winter-soldier-wandavision-dates-1276326 |title=Disney's Bob Iger Considering 'Mandalorian' Spinoff Shows |last=Couch |first=Aaron |date=February 4, 2020 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |access-date=February 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204230308/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-bob-iger-teases-mandalorian-falcon-winter-soldier-wandavision-dates-1276326 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Documentary series==\nIn April 2020, Disney announced an eight-episode documentary series titled ''Disney Gallery: The Mandalorian'', to premiere on Disney+ on May 4, 2020, [[Star Wars Day|''Star Wars'' Day]]. Hosted by Favreau, the series features interviews, never-before-seen footage, and roundtable conversations to explore behind the scenes of ''The Mandalorian''. Subsequent episodes of ''Disney Gallery: The Mandalorian'' will air weekly on Fridays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/disney-gallery-the-mandalorian-announce|title=Go Behind the Scenes in the New Disney+ Series ''Disney Gallery: The Mandalorian''|website=StarWars.com|date=April 15, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Disney+ series}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{Wookieepedia|The Mandalorian|''The Mandalorian''}}\n* [https://www.starwars.com/series/the-mandalorian  The Mandalorian on ''StarWars.com'']\n{{The Mandalorian}}\n{{Star Wars}}\n{{Lucasfilm}}\n{{Disney+}}\n{{Jon Favreau}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandalorian, The}}\n[[Category:The Mandalorian| ]]\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Action television series]]\n[[Category:American television programs featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Disney+ original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Interquel television series]]\n[[Category:Space adventure television series]]\n[[Category:Space opera television series]]\n[[Category:Space Western television series]]\n[[Category:Star Wars television series]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Jon Favreau]]\n", "name_user": "ElLutzo", "label": "safe", "comment": "move notes to season 1 directly after episode list of season 1", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Mandalorian"}
{"title_page": "Stuart P. Baker", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Stuart P. Baker\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|birth_date= \n|birth_place= \n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1989\u2013present\n|rank= [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[Carrier Strike Group 9]]<br/>[[CVW-9]]<br/>[[VFA-137]]\n|battles= [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|awards= [[Defense Superior Service Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (2)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Stuart P. Baker''' is a [[United States Navy]] officer, holding the rank of [[Rear admiral (United States)|rear admiral]].<ref name=NavyBio>{{cite web|url=https://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/bio.asp?bioID=990|title=Rear Admiral Stuart P. Baker, Commander, Carrier Strike Group Nine|publisher=United States Navy|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaker is a native of [[La Crosse, Wisconsin]]; graduated in 1989 from [[Miami University]] in Ohio with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in Paper Science and Engineering; and received his commission via the [[Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps]].<ref name=NavyBio/>\n\n==Naval career==\nBaker became an [[naval aviator]] in 1991.<ref name=NavyBio/> He received a master's degree from the [[Naval War College]].<ref name=NavyBio/> He served in [[Operation Southern Watch]] stationed aboard the {{USS|Constellation|CV-64|6}}. After spending time with [[Carrier Air Wing Fourteen]] as a [[CVW-14]] strike operations officer, he was deployed in support of United States operations in the [[Iraq War]], serving with [[VFA-146]] aboard the {{USS|John C. Stennis}} in the [[Arabian Gulf]] and [[CVW-9]] aboard the same ship. He also commanded [[VFA-137]] on the {{USS|Abraham Lincoln|CVN-72|6}}.<ref name=NavyBio/> He was selected for promotion to rear admiral in 2017.<ref>[https://www.afcea.org/content/baker-assigned-office-chief-naval-operations Baker Assigned to Office of the Chief of Naval Operations], ''Signal'', [[AFCEA]] (September 14, 2017).</ref>\n\nBaker's assignments ashore have included being stationed with [[Strike Fighter Weapons School Pacific]], the [[Naval Strike and Air Warfare Center]] as executive officer of the [[United States Navy Strike Fighter Tactics Instructor program|TOPGUN]] program and [[United States Fleet Forces Command]].\n\nIn 2020, Baker was the commanding officer of [[Carrier Strike Group 9]], deployed in the Pacific; he was stationed aboard the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}},<ref>Sam LaGrone, [https://news.usni.org/2020/04/05/navy-probe-into-letter-from-carrier-roosevelt-co-ends-monday-report-says-brett-crozier-has-covid-19 Navy Probe into Letter From Carrier Roosevelt CO Ends Monday; Report Says Brett Crozier Has COVID-19], USNI News (April 5, 2020).</ref> the [[flagship]] of the strike group,<ref name=Dyer>Andrew Dyer, [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/military/story/2020-01-17/theodore-roosevelt-carrier-strike-group-deploys Theodore Roosevelt carrier strike group deploys], ''San Diego Union-Tribune'' (January 17, 2020).</ref> which consists of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'' and seven other ships.<ref name = losses>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/coronavirus-roosevelt-carrier-crozier.html|title=\u2018There Will Be Losses\u2019: How a Captain\u2019s Plea Exposed a Rift in the Military|date=13 April 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> The ''Theodore Roosevelt'' departed from its [[Naval Base San Diego]] home port in mid-January, with more than 6,000 sailors on board, for a seven-month deployment in the Western Pacific ([[United States Indo-Pacific Command|Indo-Pacific Command]]) region.<ref name=Dyer/> In March, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]], there was an [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS\u00a0Theodore Roosevelt\u00a0(CVN-71)|outbreak]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] aboard the ship, which was ordered to port in Guam. The ''Theodore Roosevelt''{{'}}s captain, [[Brett Crozier]], urged to have most of the sailors immediately removed from the ship, quarantined ashore, and [[COVID-19 testing|tested for the virus]] to prevent the spread of the disease.<ref name = losses/> Baker, his superior officer, disagreed, feeling such an action was impractical and too drastic.<ref name = losses/> On March 29, after four days of his pleas being rebuffed by Baker and other superiors, Crozier sent a four-page memorandum to ten Navy officers including Baker and his two immediate superiors, Admiral [[John C. Aquilino]] and Vice Admiral [[DeWolfe Miller III (United States Navy)|DeWolfe Miller III]]. Crozier begged for the ship to be mostly evacuated because of the risk to the crew.<ref>{{cite news|authors=Dan Lamothe, Shawn Boburg & Paul Sonne|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/how-an-outbreak-on-the-uss-roosevelt-became-a-defining-moment-for-the-us-military/2020/04/16/2735f85c-7f24-11ea-8de7-9fdff6d5d83e_story.html|title=How an outbreak on the USS Theodore Roosevelt became a defining moment for the U.S. military|date=April 16, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>Rebecca Kheel, [https://thehill.com/policy/defense/493192-fired-captain-sent-memo-to-fewer-people-than-former-navy-head-alleged-report Fired captain sent memo to fewer people than former Navy head alleged: report], ''The Hill'' (April 16, 2020).</ref> A few days later Crozier was relieved of command by Acting Secretary of the Navy [[Thomas Modly]], who blamed Crozier for sending his memorandum over \"non-secure unclassified email\" to a \"broad array of people\" and accused Crozier of having \"unnecessarily raised the alarm\" about the virus.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |publisher=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The day after Crozier's letter became public, the Navy began to evacuate the ship.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> By 13 April 585 crew members had tested positive for the disease and one had died.<ref name = dies>Lara Seligman, [https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/13/sailor-uss-roosevelt-dies-coronavirus-183164 Sailor from USS Theodore Roosevelt dies of coronavirus], ''Politico'' (April 13, 2020).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Stuart P.}}\n[[Category:People from La Crosse, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:United States Navy rear admirals (lower half)]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n[[Category:Naval War College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Stuart P. Baker\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|birth_date= \n|birth_place= \n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1989\u2013present\n|rank= [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[Carrier Strike Group 9]]<br/>[[CVW-9]]<br/>[[VFA-137]]\n|battles= [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|awards= [[Defense Superior Service Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (2)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Stuart P. Baker''' is a [[United States Navy]] officer, holding the rank of [[Rear admiral (United States)|rear admiral]].<ref name=NavyBio>{{cite web|url=https://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/bio.asp?bioID=990|title=Rear Admiral Stuart P. Baker, Commander, Carrier Strike Group Nine|publisher=United States Navy|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaker is a native of [[La Crosse, Wisconsin]]; graduated in 1989 from [[Miami University]] in Ohio with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in Paper Science and Engineering; and received his commission via the [[Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps]].<ref name=NavyBio/>\n\n==Naval career==\nBaker became an [[naval aviator]] in 1991.<ref name=NavyBio/> He received a master's degree from the [[Naval War College]].<ref name=NavyBio/> He served in [[Operation Southern Watch]] stationed aboard the {{USS|Constellation|CV-64|6}}. After spending time with [[Carrier Air Wing Fourteen]] as a [[CVW-14]] strike operations officer, he was deployed in support of United States operations in the [[Iraq War]], serving with [[VFA-146]] aboard the {{USS|John C. Stennis}} in the [[Arabian Gulf]] and [[CVW-9]] aboard the same ship. He also commanded [[VFA-137]] on the {{USS|Abraham Lincoln|CVN-72|6}}.<ref name=NavyBio/> He was selected for promotion to rear admiral in 2017.<ref>[https://www.afcea.org/content/baker-assigned-office-chief-naval-operations Baker Assigned to Office of the Chief of Naval Operations], ''Signal'', [[AFCEA]] (September 14, 2017).</ref>\n\nBaker's assignments ashore have included being stationed with [[Strike Fighter Weapons School Pacific]], the [[Naval Strike and Air Warfare Center]] as executive officer of the [[United States Navy Strike Fighter Tactics Instructor program|TOPGUN]] program and [[United States Fleet Forces Command]].\n\nIn 2020, Baker was the commanding officer of [[Carrier Strike Group 9]], deployed in the Pacific; he was stationed aboard the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}},<ref>Sam LaGrone, [https://news.usni.org/2020/04/05/navy-probe-into-letter-from-carrier-roosevelt-co-ends-monday-report-says-brett-crozier-has-covid-19 Navy Probe into Letter From Carrier Roosevelt CO Ends Monday; Report Says Brett Crozier Has COVID-19], USNI News (April 5, 2020).</ref> the [[flagship]] of the strike group,<ref name=Dyer>Andrew Dyer, [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/military/story/2020-01-17/theodore-roosevelt-carrier-strike-group-deploys Theodore Roosevelt carrier strike group deploys], ''San Diego Union-Tribune'' (January 17, 2020).</ref> which consists of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'' and seven other ships.<ref name = losses>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/coronavirus-roosevelt-carrier-crozier.html|title=\u2018There Will Be Losses\u2019: How a Captain\u2019s Plea Exposed a Rift in the Military|date=13 April 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> The ''Theodore Roosevelt'' departed from its [[Naval Base San Diego]] home port in mid-January, with more than 6,000 sailors on board, for a seven-month deployment in the Western Pacific ([[United States Indo-Pacific Command|Indo-Pacific Command]]) region.<ref name=Dyer/> In March, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]], there was an [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS\u00a0Theodore Roosevelt\u00a0(CVN-71)|outbreak]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] aboard the ship, which was ordered to port in Guam. The ''Theodore Roosevelt''{{'}}s captain, [[Brett Crozier]], urged to have most of the sailors immediately removed from the ship, quarantined ashore, and [[COVID-19 testing|tested for the virus]] to prevent the spread of the disease.<ref name = losses/> Baker, his superior officer, disagreed, feeling such an action was impractical and too drastic.<ref name = losses/> On March 29, after four days of his pleas being rebuffed by Baker and other superiors, Crozier sent a four-page memorandum to ten Navy officers including Baker and his two immediate superiors, Admiral [[John C. Aquilino]] and Vice Admiral [[DeWolfe Miller III (United States Navy)|DeWolfe Miller III]]. Crozier begged for the ship to be mostly evacuated because of the risk to the crew.<ref>{{cite news|authors=Dan Lamothe, Shawn Boburg & Paul Sonne|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/how-an-outbreak-on-the-uss-roosevelt-became-a-defining-moment-for-the-us-military/2020/04/16/2735f85c-7f24-11ea-8de7-9fdff6d5d83e_story.html|title=How an outbreak on the USS Theodore Roosevelt became a defining moment for the U.S. military|date=April 16, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> A few days later Crozier was relieved of command by Acting Secretary of the Navy [[Thomas Modly]], who blamed Crozier for sending his memorandum over \"non-secure unclassified email\" to a \"broad array of people\" and accused Crozier of having \"unnecessarily raised the alarm\" about the virus.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |publisher=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The day after Crozier's letter became public, the Navy began to evacuate the ship.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> By 13 April 585 crew members had tested positive for the disease and one had died.<ref name = dies>Lara Seligman, [https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/13/sailor-uss-roosevelt-dies-coronavirus-183164 Sailor from USS Theodore Roosevelt dies of coronavirus], ''Politico'' (April 13, 2020).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Stuart P.}}\n[[Category:People from La Crosse, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:United States Navy rear admirals (lower half)]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n[[Category:Naval War College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Neutrality", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNaval career:ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuart_P._Baker"}
{"title_page": "Gurbaksh Chahal", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Indian-American internet entrepreneur|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gurbaksh Singh Chahal\n| image              = File:Gurbaksh Chahal.jpg\n| caption            = Gurbaksh Chahal\n| image_upright      = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1982|7|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tarn Taran Sahib]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Entrepreneur\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| known_for          = Founder of ClickAgents, BlueLithium, [[RadiumOne]], Gravity4, Taara Labs, RedLotus\n| net_worth          = 100 million USD (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/came-to-america-with-nothing-and-made-a-fortune-2012-1|title=13 People Who Came To America With Nothing And Made A Fortune|last=Goldschein|first=Eric|website=Business Insider|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| party              = [[Democratic Party (United States)]]<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1235519214527475712|user=gchahal|title=As a Democrat ....|author=Gurbaksh Chahal|date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200305110247/https://twitter.com/gchahal/status/1235519214527475712|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n| partner            = [[Rubina Bajwa]]\n| URL                = [https://gurbakshchahal.com/ GurbakshChahal.com]\n}}\n\n'''Gurbaksh Singh Chahal''' (born July 17, 1982) is an Indian-American internet entrepreneur who founded several internet advertising companies. \n\nChahal founded his first advertising network at an age of 16 and two years later, became a millionaire after selling it to [[ValueClick]] at nearly $40 million. In 2004, he co-founded BlueLithium, which went on to become the fifth largest ad-network in USA, before being sold to Yahoo in a $300 million deal. Chahal has since founded other internet-based companies including [[RadiumOne]] and Gravity4. He is currently the CEO of RedLotus. \n\nIn 2010, [[Bloomberg Businessweek]] named him among the 15 best young entrepreneurs of the year. In 2012,  Chahal was enlisted among the 25 richest entrepreneurs under the age of 30 by [[Complex (magazine)|Complex magazine]]. In 2013, he was named as one of the [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award|entrepreneurs of the year]] by [[Ernst and Young]].\n\nIn 2013, Chahal was convicted for [[domestic violence]] and [[battery (crime)|battery]], and was sentenced to [[probation]]. He claimed innocence, but was terminated from his role as CEO of RadiumOne by the Board of Directors. In 2016, after new charges of domestic violence against a second woman with whom he was in a relationship, his probation was revoked. He resigned as CEO of Gravity4, and served six months in jail.\n== Early life ==\nChahal was born to Avtar Singh and Arjinder Chahal, a nurse in [[Tarn Taran Sahib]], a city in [[India]]\u2019s [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] state on July 17, 1982; he was the youngest of four children.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=jiH8UqXUKvgC|title=The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|date=October 23, 2008|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-230-62108-4|location=|pages=3|language=en}}</ref> In 1985, during the aftermath of the [[Khalistan movement|Khalistani insurgency]], his parents emigrated to the United States, his father having won a green card lottery.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=jiH8UqXUKvgC|title=The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions|date=October 23, 2008|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-230-62108-4|language=en}}</ref> Chahal emigrated the following year, at age four. The family lived in a one-bedroom apartment in [[San Jose, California]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=40|language=en}}</ref> His father got a job in the Postal Service; his mother worked as an assistant to a nurse.<ref name=\":3\" /> He has two elder sisters \u2014 Nirmal and Kamal, and an elder brother Taj Chahal; the latter two had worked with Chahal in his ventures.<ref name=\":0\" /> His family were devout followers of [[Sikhism]].<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nAt age 16, Chahal dropped out of [[Independence High School (San Jose, California)|Independence High School]] to pursue a career in Internet advertising; his parents wished him to be a doctor, and Chahal has since noted this to be the biggest risk-prone decision taken in his career.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/style/article/Advice-from-young-millionaire-Gurbaksh-Chahal-3264414.php |title=Advice from young millionaire Gurbaksh Chahal |last=Zinko |first=Carolyne |date=October 26, 2008 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |access-date=January 6, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2008/11/04/cassidy-meet-g-silicon-valleys-celebrity-entrepreneur/|title=Cassidy: Meet G, Silicon Valley's celebrity entrepreneur|date=November 4, 2008|website=The Mercury News|language=en-US|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/staff-blog/what-really-scares-entrepreneurs.html|title=What Really Scares Entrepreneurs?|last=Lagorio-Chafkin|first=Christine|date=March 8, 2011|website=Inc.com|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> He has claimed of being subject to intense racial bullying during his school years including being forced to remove his [[Dastar|turban]], at knife-point.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-04-20/gwallets-chahal-balances-flashy-lifestyle-family-commitmentbusinessweek-business-news-stock-market-and-financial-advice|title=GWallet's Chahal Balances Flashy Lifestyle, Family Commitment|last=King|first=Rachael|date=April 20, 2010|website=Bloomberg|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.varsity.co.uk/news/2502|title=Gurbaksh Chahal: Dreaming in Gold|website=Varsity Online|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\n\nChahal started his career buying and reselling printers on [[eBay]], after being turned away from a job at [[McDonald's]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=jiH8UqXUKvgC|title=The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions|date=October 23, 2008|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-230-62108-4|location=|pages=9\u201310, 12|language=en}}</ref> His initial forays into business world were to support his family, and largely derived from his father's interests in stock-trading.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1743178/radiumone-ceo-his-mcdonalds-rejection-social-ads-and-do-not-track-legislation|title=RadiumOne CEO on His McDonald's Rejection, Social Ads, and Do-Not-Track Legislation|last=Ferenstein|first=Gregory|date=March 29, 2011|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ClickAgents ===\nIn 1998, Chahal founded ''ClickAgents'', an [[advertising network]] focused on performance-based advertising, on the lines of [[DoubleClick]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://darpanmagazine.com/people/businessleaders/gurbaksh-chahal-entrepreneur-extraordinaire/|title=People {{!}} Gurbaksh Chahal - Entrepreneur Extraordinaire|website=darpanmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> By 2000, it had numerous customers and had a staff-strength of 34.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=41|language=en}}</ref> It was acquired by [[Alliance Data|ValueClick]] in November 2000 in an all-stock deal valued at nearly $40 million, which paid his parents' mortgages lifting them out of poverty and made him an overnight millionaire.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://adage.com/article/news/valueclick-acquires-click-agents/10457/ |title=ValueClick acquires Click Agents |date=November 3, 2000 |work=AdvertisingAge |access-date=April 9, 2017 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410215832/http://adage.com/article/news/valueclick-acquires-click-agents/10457/ |archive-date=April 10, 2017 |publisher=Crain Communications |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2009/12/01/gwallet-raises-12-5m-for-more-ethical-virtual-currency-system/|title=gWallet raises $12.5M for more ethical virtual currency/offers system|date=December 1, 2009|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> \n\n=== BlueLithium ===\nIn 2004, Chahal co-founded BlueLithium, a company that specialized in [[Targeted advertising|behavioral targeting]], a technique whereby web users' habits online are tracked in order to show customized ads.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2391674.ece |title=Yahoo snaps up BlueLithium in $300m deal |last=Blakely |first=Rhys |date=September 5, 2007 |website=Times Online |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706001036/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2391674.ece |archive-date=July 6, 2008 |access-date=March 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1743178/radiumone-ceo-talks-mcdonalds-rejection-social-ads-and-do-not-track-legislation |title=RadiumOne CEO on His McDonald's Rejection, Social Ads, and Do-Not-Track Legislation |last=Ferenstein |first=Gregory |date=March 29, 2011 |website=Fast Company |access-date=March 1, 2015}}</ref> The ad-tech industry praised it with [[Business 2.0]] noting it to be among the 11 most disruptive innovations of 2006,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2006/09/15/technology/disruptors_bluelithium.biz2/index.htm|title=Business 2.0...Big Innovations: BlueLithium - Sep. 20, 2006|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> and by the same year, it had expanded operations to foreign countries, having purchased AdRevolver.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=42|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2004/11/22/daily5.html|title=BlueLithium to buy AdRevolver|work=[[American City Business Journals#Newspapers|Silicon Valley Business Journal]]|date=November 22, 2004|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> ''MingleNow'', a social network was simultaneously launched, which was accorded a partnership deal by [[Anheuser-Busch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/beer-fuels-social-networking-minglenow-clinks-anheuser-busch/|title=Beer fuels social networking: MingleNow 'Clinks' Anheuser-Busch|last=Bogatin|first=Donna|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> It was named among the top 100 private companies of America by AlwaysOn for three consecutive years<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://darpanmagazine.com/people/businessleaders/gurbaksh-chahal-entrepreneur-extraordinaire/|title=People {{!}} Gurbaksh Chahal - Entrepreneur Extraordinaire|website=darpanmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> and in 2007, [[Yahoo!]] bought it for $300 million in cash; Chahal remained CEO during interim period.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/09/04/yahoo-acquires-ad-network-bluelithium/ |title=Yahoo! Acquires Ad Network BlueLithium |date=September 4, 2007 |website=TechCrunch |access-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2007-09-03/targeting-you-yahoo-moves-deeper-into-behaviorial-targeting-with-bluelithium-purchase|title=Targeting You: Yahoo Moves Deeper into Behaviorial Targeting with BlueLithium Purchase|last=Hof|first=Rob|date=September 4, 2007|website=Bloomberg|access-date=}}</ref> It was the fifth largest ad-network in USA and second largest in UK, at time of sale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN0444409120070905|title=Yahoo buys behavioral ad firm for $300 mln|date=September 5, 2007|work=Reuters|access-date=February 9, 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== RadiumOne ===\n[[File:Gurbaksh Chahal receives E&Y Entrepreneur of the Year.jpg|thumb|Gurbaksh Chahal accepts E&Y Entrepreneur of the Year Award for RadiumOne, 2013]]\n\nIn 2009, Chahal founded RadiumOne, another online ad company<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2010/10/18/new-ad-network-radiumone-aims-to-tap-social-mega-trend/ |title=New Ad Network RadiumOne Aims To Tap Social 'Mega Trend' |last=McMahan |first=Ty |date=October 18, 2010 |work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> of a slightly different genre<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=44|language=en}}</ref>, which started as a loyalty and rewards program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/business/ontherecord/article/Gurbaksh-Chahal-turns-RadiumOne-to-gold-4010360.php|title=Gurbaksh Chahal turns RadiumOne to gold|last=Lee|first=Ellen|date=November 5, 2012|website=SFGate|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> but later, migrated to targeted-advertising domain, having acquired multiple social-media-centered startups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2011/12/14/radiumone-buys-mobile-photo-sharing-app-developer-focal-labs/|title=RadiumOne Buys Mobile Photo Sharing App Developer Focal Labs|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> It garnered significant reputation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2011/05/20/radiumone-about-to-corner-the-market-on-social-data-before-competitors-even-know-whats-happening/|title=RadiumOne About To Corner The Market On Social Data Before Competitors Even Know What's Happening|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> for its patented ad-technology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmo.com.au/article/540068/radiumone_brings_programmatic_advertising_tech_platform_australia/|title=RadiumOne brings programmatic advertising tech platform to Australia|last=Cameron (CMO)|first=Nadia|last2=10 March|first2=2014 12:26|website=www.cmo.com.au|language=en-au|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2010/10/18/new-ad-network-radiumone-aims-to-tap-social-mega-trend/|title=New Ad Network RadiumOne Aims To Tap Social 'Mega Trend'|last=McMahan|first=Ty|date=October 18, 2010|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> with Chahal being poised to be a billionaire<ref name=\":10\" />, and was valued at about US$500 million at its peak. In 2014, the company failed to move on with IPO, as Chahal plead guilty to domestic violence. In 2017 it was purchased by [[RhythmOne]] for US$22 million.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n=== Gravity4 ===\nIn July 2014, Chahal launched Gravity4 (since renamed to DaVinci Marketing Cloud).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mrweb.com/drno/news25671.htm |title=Name Change Marks Renaissance for Gravity4 |last=Crowther |first=Mel |last2=Thomas |first2=Nick |date=January 31, 2018 |website=MrWeb |access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> It made a failed bid to buy back RadiumOne and closed in 2017, being unable to integrate the purchased ad-tech startups.<ref name=\"SFChronicleHuet\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/business/article/Gurbaksh-Chahal-flew-high-and-fell-fast-9140090.php|title=Gurbaksh Chahal flew high and fell fast|last=Huet|first=Ellen|date=August 13, 2016|website=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.techcircle.in/2019/11/12/post-radiumone-gurbaksh-chahal-seeks-success-again-with-redlotus-in-talks-to-raise-50-mn|title=Post RadiumOne, Gurbaksh Chahal seeks success again with RedLotus; in talks to raise $50 mn|date=November 12, 2019|website=Techcircle|language=en-US|access-date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n=== RedLotus ===\nIn 2019, Chahal founded TaaraLabs, an incubator and RedLotus in Hong Kong, which specializes in [[Artificial intelligence|AI]]-based targeted advertising.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.techcircle.in/2019/11/12/post-radiumone-gurbaksh-chahal-seeks-success-again-with-redlotus-in-talks-to-raise-50-mn |title=Post RadiumOne, Gurbaksh Chahal seeks success again with RedLotus; in talks to raise $50 mn |last=Ganguly |first=Payal |date=November 12, 2019 |website=TechCircle |language=en-US |access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://mandiner.hu/cikk/20191229_az_erettsegizetlen_milliardos|title=Az \u00e9retts\u00e9gizetlen milli\u00e1rdos|last=D\u00e1niel|first=Ol\u00e1h|date=|website=mandiner.hu|language=hu|url-access=subscription|access-date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and philanthropy==\n[[File:Gurbaksh Chahal with Donald Trump at the Leaders in Management Award function, Pace University.jpg|thumb|Chahal with [[Donald Trump]] at the 2009 Leaders in Management Award function, [[Pace University]].]]\nIn 2010, [[Bloomberg Businessweek]] named him among the 15 best young entrepreneurs of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/10/04/0419_best_young_tech_entrepreneurs/4.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202224009/http://images.businessweek.com/ss/10/04/0419_best_young_tech_entrepreneurs/4.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 2, 2013|title=Best Young Tech Entrepreneurs 2010: GWallet - BusinessWeek|date=December 2, 2013|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> In the same year, Chahal's alma mater [[Evergreen Valley College]] awarded him with an Honorary Degree in Business Administration<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=EVERGREEN VALLEY COLLEGE PRESENTS AN HONORARY DEGREE TO LOCAL SAN JOSE GUY TURNED MILLIONNAIRE|work=Two Colleges:One Community - Official Newsletter of San Jose . Evergreen Community College District|access-date=|date= July 2010|issue=41|page=3}}</ref> and [[Pace University]] conferred the Leaders in Management Award and a Honorary Doctorate in Commercial Sciences; he had earlier established an endowed entrepreneurial scholarship program over the university.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Internet-star-Chahal-getting-honorary-doctorate-3190862.php|title=Internet star Chahal getting honorary doctorate|last=Zinko|first=Carolyne|date=April 29, 2010|website=SFGate|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> In 2012, [[Complex (magazine)|Complex magazine]] put him in a list of the 25 richest entrepreneurs under the age of 30;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2012/08/the-25-richest-tech-entrepreneurs-under-30/|title=The 25 Richest Tech Entrepreneurs Under 3017. Aaron Levie, 27|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> in the same year he received the Light of India Amrapali Young Achievers award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/light-of-india_b_1729802|title=Global Indians Illuminate Fifth Avenue at Light of India Awards|last1=Luce|first1=Jim|date=August 2, 2012|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=January 31, 2020|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/global/light-of-india-awards-brings-global-indians-together/article_1cf2fc29-b789-5614-b741-8cd187fda662.html|title='Light of India' Awards Brings Global Indians Together|last1=Vijayakar|first1=R. M.|date=June 27, 2012|work=India West|language=en}}</ref> In 2013, he was named as one of the [[Ernst and Young]] entrepreneurs of the year<ref name=\"businessinsider.com\">{{Cite news|last=Carson|first=Biz|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/gurbaksh-chahal-rise-and-fall-background-history-2015-11|title=The rise and fall of Gurbaksh Chahal: How one tech CEO went from fame, fortune, and Oprah's couch to possible jail time|date=August 14, 2016|work=Business Insider|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\" /> and the following year, Complex noted him among the top 10 technology entrepreneurs of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/07/10-tech-entrepreneurs-who-risked-it-all-and-made-it|title=10 Tech Entrepreneurs Who Risked It All and Made It|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, [[Delhi Sikh Gurdwara Management Committee]] honored him for contributions made to the field of entrepreneurship.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/gurbaksh-chahal-honoured-by-dsgmc-shares-the-moment-with-former-pm-manmohan-singh-7426791.html|title=Gurbaksh Chahal honoured by DSGMC, shares the moment with former PM Manmohan Singh|website=Firstpost|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Chahal has been a guest lecturer at several universities including [[London School of Economics]], [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]] et al.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://evideo.elab.nyc/entrepreneurs-roundtable-special-guest-speaker-gurbaksh-chahal-2-of-16_e8bfc1535.html|title=Entrepreneurs Roundtable - Special Guest Speaker Gurbaksh Chahal (2 Of 16)|website=evideo.elab.nyc|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Top 10 Mistakes Made by Entrepreneurs|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gtHZUr3mdlY|language=en|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lse.ac.uk/lse-player/home.aspx|title=LSE Player|last=Science|first=London School of Economics and Political|website=London School of Economics and Political Science|language=en-GB|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uctv.tv/shows/Ambition-Discipline-Purpose-The-Journey-of-Being-an-Entrepreneur-with-Gurbaksh-Chahal-24409|title=VIDEO: Ambition. Discipline. Purpose. The Journey of Being an Entrepreneur with Gurbaksh Chahal|last=|date=|website=www.uctv.tv|language=en|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, after the [[Wisconsin Sikh temple shooting]], he committed US$1 million to found BeProud (since renamed to Chahal Foundation), a [[Foundation (nonprofit)|charitable foundation]] that supports the families of [[hate crime]] victims and combats [[child trafficking in India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/224248|title=Serial Entrepreneur Gurbaksh Chahal Commits $1 Million to Stop Hate Crimes|last=Evans|first=Teri|date=August 21, 2012|website=Entrepreneur|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Sikh-entrepreneur-to-launch-Be-Proud-movement-to-fight-hate/articleshow/16164261.cms|title=Sikh entrepreneur to launch 'Be Proud' movement to fight hate {{!}} India News - Times of India|last=Sep 2|first=Atul Sethi {{!}} TNN {{!}}|last2=2012|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020|last3=Ist|first3=02:11}}</ref><ref name=\":13\" /> It had liaisoned with [[Church of the Latter-Day Saints]] to provide employment scopes for rural women in Maharashtra, India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news-in.churchofjesuschrist.org/many-organizations-including-lds-charities-joined-forces-to-create-feminine-hygiene-kits|title=LDS Charities and Feminine Hygiene|date=May 9, 2018|website=news-in.churchofjesuschrist.org|language=en|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, Chahal committed to evolving Punjab as the next tech capital of India, and create over a million jobs for the youth populace by 2030 through suitable investments. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashar|first=A.S.|url=|title=Punjab's Economic Salvation may lie in promotion of IT Sector|date=June 9, 2019|work=Punjab Express|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sheetal|first=|url=|title=Tracing the path of progress|date=June 9, 2019|work=Punjab Tribune|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Internet entrepreneur aims to create million jobs in Punjab's IT sector|date=June 9, 2019|work=Daily Post|access-date=}}</ref> In 2020, Chahal donated face masks, test kits, [[Personal protective equipment|personal protective equipments]] and ventilators to hospitals across several countries (including Hong Kong and India) during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Coronavirus pandemic]], and extended procurement networks to help governments in mitigating the supply-chain chaos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rthk.hk/tv/dtt31/programme/thismorning/episode/617329|title=\u6e2f\u53f0\u96fb\u8996 31 \u65e9\u8fb0\u3002\u65e9\u6668 - \u624b\u8a9e\u76f4\u64ad\u7bc0\u76ee\ufe30\u5ec1\u7d19\u6436\u52ab\u6848\uff1b\u300a\u65e9\u8fb0\u4e00\u4ef6\u4e8b\u300b\uff1a\u75ab\u5883\u6709\u60c5\uff1b\u300a\u65e9\u8fb0\u4fdd\u6297\u529b\u300b\uff1a\u7dad\u4ed6\u547dC|website=www.rthk.hk|language=zh-hant|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/rubina-bajwa-and-beau-gurbaksh-chahal-team-up-to-help-hong-kong-charity-prevent-spread-of-coronavirus/articleshow/74084543.cms|title=Rubina Bajwa and beau Gurbaksh Chahal team up to help Hong Kong charity prevent spread of Coronavirus - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkcnews.com/article/27053/\u53e3\u7f69\u77ed\u7f3a-27053/\u300c\u653f\u5e9c\u505a\u5497\u5572\u54a9\uff1f\u300d\u2014\u2014\u6c11\u9593\u6536\u96c6\u53e3\u7f69\u52a9\u57fa\u5c64-|title=\u300c\u653f\u5e9c\u505a\u5497\u5572\u54a9\uff1f\u300d\u2014\u2014\u6c11\u9593\u6536\u96c6\u53e3\u7f69\u52a9\u57fa\u5c64 {{!}} \u8b80\u8005\u4f86\u8ad6|website=\u773e\u65b0\u805e|language=zh|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/we-are-working-on-delivering-test-kits-ventilators-and-respirators-rubina-bajwa-and-gurbaksh-chahals-initiative-for-covid-19-patients/articleshow/74844533.cms|title=\"We are working on delivering test kits, ventilators, and respirators\u201d; Rubina Bajwa and Gurbaksh Chahal\u2019s initiative for Covid-19 patients - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/the-world-needs-as-much-help-it-can-get-at-this-time-says-rubina-bajwa-as-beau-gurbaksh-chahal-extends-help-for-covid-19-relief/articleshow/75025243.cms|title=\u201cThe world needs as much help it can get at this time\u201d, says Rubina Bajwa as beau Gurbaksh Chahal extends help for Covid-19 relief - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Chahal with U.S. President Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|Chahal with Obama at a Fundraising Dinner in San Francisco, 2012]]\nChahal is currently in a relationship with [[Punjabi cinema|Punjabi film]] actress [[Rubina Bajwa]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/news/exclusive-rubina-bajwa-confirms-her-relationship-gurbaksh-chahal-says-he-centre-my-world-491048|title=EXCLUSIVE: Rubina Bajwa CONFIRMS her relationship with Gurbaksh Chahal; Says 'He is the centre of my world'|last=Kaur|first=Ranpreet|date=December 10, 2019|website=PINKVILLA|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/rubina-bajwa-spends-the-last-few-days-of-2019-vacationing-with-beau-gurbaksh-singh-chahal-and-the-pics-will-make-you-crave-for-a-holiday/articleshow/72993511.cms|title=Rubina Bajwa spends the last few days of 2019 vacationing with beau Gurbaksh Singh Chahal and the pics will make you crave for a holiday! - Times of India|date=December 27, 2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>; he previously resided in [[San Francisco Bay Area]] but is currently based in [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\":15\" /> \n\nChahal has attracted attention for his physique and extravagant lifestyle including a fleet of luxurious cars and a penthouse apartment.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has been featured over [[Fox Business]] and [[CNBC]]'s High Net Worth<ref name=\":16\" /> and has been invited as an guest over [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/millionaire-moguls/10|title=Millionaire Moguls|work=Oprah.com|access-date=February 4, 2020|language=en-us}}</ref> He has been also featured over [[The Secret Millionaire]], where he went undercover in [[San Francisco]] and gave away $110,000 of his wealth<ref>{{Cite news|last=ZIPKIN|first=GURBAKSH CHAHAL; as told to AMY|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/07/jobs/07boss.html|title=First, $99. Then, Millions.|date=September 6, 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 4, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2008/12/16/bluelithium-founder-gurbaksh-chahal-keeps-his-millions-secret-for-once/|title=BlueLithium founder Gurbaksh Chahal keeps his millions \"Secret\" for once|date=December 17, 2008|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>, [[The Bonnie Hunt Show]], where he auctioned off his pen for charity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-bonnie-hunt-show/episode-67-season-1/the-bonnie-hunt-show/295098|title=The Bonnie Hunt Show {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>, and on [[Extra (American TV program)|ExtraTV]] as America's most eligible bachelor.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> In 2011, [[Men's Health]] awarded him the seventh spot in the list of the world's fittest and richest men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.menshealth.com/trending-news/a19540258/worlds-fittest-richest-guys/|title=The World's Richest and Fittest Guys|last=Sine|first=Richard|date=April 11, 2011|website=Men's Health|language=en-US|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> \n\nChahal profess to be a devout Sikh, who was largely inspired by his grandmother<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/supplement/story/20110905-i-take-my-culture-wherever-i-go-747348-2011-08-24|title=I take my culture wherever I go|last=Chitkara|first=Vanita|date=|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> and takes a keen interest in Bollywood, admiring [[Shah Rukh Khan]] and [[A. R. Rahman]] in particular.<ref name=\":4\" /> Chahal was a regular donor to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidates; he was twice invited to White House during [[Barack Obama]]'s presidency.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peterson|first=Andrea|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/04/29/dccc-distances-itself-from-tech-ceo-fired-after-domestic-violence-conviction/|title=DCCC distances itself from tech CEO fired after domestic violence conviction|date=April 29, 2014|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiapost.com/avtar-chahal-meets-obama-first-lady/|title=Avtar Chahal meets Obama, First Lady|website=India Post|language=en-US|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> \n\nHe is also a motivational speaker,<ref name=\":13\" /> advocates [[one-dollar salary]] for CEOs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3021501/im-a-ceo-with-a-paycheck-of-0-and-you-should-join-me|title=I'm A CEO With A Paycheck Of $0\u2013And You Should Join Me|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|date=November 13, 2013|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>, and has written an autobiography called ''The Dream.''<ref name=\":14\" /> During the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|2020 Coronavirus pandemic]], Chahal became a vocal critic of governments and urged them to update their monetary policies in order to salvage their economies. He also spoke out against increasing xenophobia targeting the Chinese populace.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/indias-virus-stricken-economy-is-in-a-dire-need-of-a-vaccine/articleshow/74799325.cms|title=View: India's virus-stricken economy is in a dire need of a vaccine|date=March 25, 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/letters/article/3077003/coronavirus-twin-crisis-why-hong-kongs-carrie-lam-must-match-west|title=Why Carrie Lam must bring out the big guns to fight virus|date=March 27, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/don-t-be-racist-blame-the-government-not-its-people-opinion/story-K8HjJ9xTrjXsYgOeVaQ2hN.html|title=Don\u2019t be racist: Blame the government, not its people {{!}} Opinion|date=March 27, 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/views/coronavirus-lockdown-but-what-is-india-missing-5566591.htm|title=Coronavirus lockdown: But what is India missing?|website=cnbctv18.com|language=en-US|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/views/numbers-dont-lie-but-in-the-world-of-covid-19-they-do-5611231.htm|title=Numbers Don\u2019t Lie: But, in the world of COVID-19 they do|website=cnbctv18.com|language=en-US|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/economy/covid-19-why-india-must-offer-more-financial-stimulus-and-not-just-put-employers-in-debt-5090231.html|title=COVID-19 {{!}} Why India must offer more financial stimulus and not just put employers in debt|website=Moneycontrol|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Domestic violence and battery conviction ===\nIn August 2013, the [[San Francisco District Attorney's Office]] (SFDA) charged Chahal with committing acts of domestic violence against his girlfriend.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Newton|date=2014|editor-last=Lee|editor-first=Newton|title=Personal Total Information Awareness|journal=Facebook Nation|language=en|publisher=Springer|pages=305\u2013345|doi=10.1007/978-1-4939-1740-2_15|isbn=978-1-4939-1740-2}}</ref> Chahal proclaimed his innocence<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/crime/article/Internet-mogul-pleads-not-guilty-to-assault-4719376.php|title=Internet mogul pleads not guilty to assault|last=Alexander|first=Kurtis|last2=Ho|first2=Vivian|date=August 8, 2013|website=San Francisco Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref> but nevertheless entered into a [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] plea to one charge of domestic violence battery and one charge of [[battery (crime)|battery]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/internet-mogul-accused-of-domestic-violence-pleads-guilty-to-two-misdemeanors/|title=Internet mogul accused of domestic violence pleads guilty to two misdemeanors|date=April 18, 2014|website=The San Francisco Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> He was sentenced to three years' [[probation]], ordered to pay a fine, and compelled to undergo a 52-week domestic violence training course along with 25 hours of [[community service]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Subsequently, he was fired from his position as CEO of RadiumOne and the company failed to move on with IPO <ref name=\"Fortune2014\">{{Cite web|url=http://finance.fortune.cnn.com/2014/04/25/its-time-for-radiumone-to-fire-its-abusive-ceo/|title=It's time for RadiumOne's abusive CEO to go|last=Primack|first=Dan|date=April 25, 2014|website=Fortune|publisher=CNN Money|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140601064812/http://finance.fortune.cnn.com/2014/04/25/its-time-for-radiumone-to-fire-its-abusive-ceo/|archive-date=June 1, 2014|access-date=March 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Nagle\">{{Cite news|last=Elder|first=Jeff|title=Tech Firm Tried to Save IPO Amid CEO Scandal|date=September 10, 2015|work=Wall Street Journal|issn=00999660|id={{ProQuest|1710603396}}}}</ref>; Chahal has since alleged that his guilty plea was coerced by the board of RadiumOne.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/gurbaksh-chahal-former-ceo-fired-after-domestic-violence-plea-settles-dispute-with-radiumone/|title=Gurbaksh Chahal, former CEO fired after domestic violence plea, settles dispute with RadiumOne|date=July 21, 2014|website=The San Francisco Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/gurbaksh-chahal-blasts-media-board-2014-4|title=RADIUMONE CEO: My Board Betrayed Me, Even Though I Made Them A Fortune|last=Weisenthal|first=Joe|website=Business Insider|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the [[San Francisco County Superior Court]] found Chahal guilty of violating his September 2014 probation, upon another prosecution by SFDA for acts of domestic violence against a second woman with whom he was in a relationship.<ref name=\"sentencing\">{{Cite news|last=Rainey|first=Libby|url=http://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/SF-judge-to-decide-fate-of-Gurbaksh-Chahal-in-9139376.php|title=Tech mogul Gurbaksh Chahal gets 1 year in domestic violence case|date=August 12, 2016|work=San Francisco Chroncile|access-date=November 1, 2016}}</ref> He was sentenced to a year in jail and resigned from his position as CEO of Gravity4.<ref name=\"sentencing\" /> The California State Appeals Court upheld the verdict in April 2018<ref name=\"sfgate.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/Court-upholds-ruling-against-SF-tech-mogul-Chahal-12870668.php|title=Court upholds ruling against SF tech mogul Chahal in domestic violence case|last=Ma|first=Annie|date=April 28, 2018|work=SFGate|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref> and Chahal served six months in [[San Francisco County Jails|San Francisco County Jail]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/ojs-lawyer-and-the-woman-abusing-princeling-of-silicon-valley|title=O.J.'s Lawyer and the Woman-Abusing Princeling of Silicon Valley|first=Michael|last=Daly|date=September 3, 2018|via=www.thedailybeast.com}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions'', Palgrave Macmillan (October 23, 2008) {{ISBN|0-230-61095-1}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|3223893|name=Gurbaksh Chahal}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gtHZUr3mdlY A panel discussion with Chahal], Conference on Entrepreneurship, [[Stanford University Graduate School of Business]], March 2010\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chahal, Gurbaksh}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American media executives]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:American technology writers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in advertising]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Tarn Taran Sahib]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:American people of Punjabi descent]]\n[[Category:American businessmen of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:21st-century American inventors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Indian-American internet entrepreneur|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gurbaksh Singh Chahal\n| image              = File:Gurbaksh Chahal.jpg\n| caption            = Gurbaksh Chahal\n| image_upright      = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1982|7|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tarn Taran Sahib]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Entrepreneur\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| known_for          = Founder of ClickAgents, BlueLithium, [[RadiumOne]], Gravity4, Taara Labs, RedLotus\n| net_worth          = 100 million USD (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/came-to-america-with-nothing-and-made-a-fortune-2012-1|title=13 People Who Came To America With Nothing And Made A Fortune|last=Goldschein|first=Eric|website=Business Insider|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| party              = [[Democratic Party (United States)]]<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1235519214527475712|user=gchahal|title=As a Democrat ....|author=Gurbaksh Chahal|date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200305110247/https://twitter.com/gchahal/status/1235519214527475712|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n| partner            = [[Rubina Bajwa]]\n| URL                = [https://gurbakshchahal.com/ GurbakshChahal.com]\n}}\n\n'''Gurbaksh Singh Chahal''' (born July 17, 1982) is an Indian-American internet entrepreneur who founded several internet advertising companies. \n\nChahal founded his first advertising network at an age of 16 and two years later, became a millionaire after selling it to [[ValueClick]] at nearly $40 million. In 2004, he co-founded BlueLithium, which went on to become the fifth largest ad-network in USA, before being sold to Yahoo in a $300 million deal. Chahal has since founded other internet-based companies including [[RadiumOne]] and Gravity4. He is currently the CEO of RedLotus. \n\nIn 2010, [[Bloomberg Businessweek]] named him among the 15 best young entrepreneurs of the year. In 2012,  Chahal was enlisted among the 25 richest entrepreneurs under the age of 30 by [[Complex (magazine)|Complex magazine]]. In 2013, he was named as one of the [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award|entrepreneurs of the year]] by [[Ernst and Young]].\n\nIn 2013, Chahal was convicted for [[domestic violence]] and [[battery (crime)|battery]], and was sentenced to [[probation]]. He claimed innocence, but was terminated from his role as CEO of RadiumOne by the Board of Directors. In 2016, after new charges of domestic violence against a second woman with whom he was in a relationship, his probation was revoked. He resigned as CEO of Gravity4, and served six months in jail.\n== Early life ==\nChahal was born to Avtar Singh and Arjinder Chahal, a nurse in [[Tarn Taran Sahib]], a city in [[India]]\u2019s [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] state on July 17, 1982; he was the youngest of four children.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=jiH8UqXUKvgC|title=The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|date=October 23, 2008|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-230-62108-4|location=|pages=3|language=en}}</ref> In 1985, during the aftermath of the [[Khalistan movement|Khalistani insurgency]], his parents emigrated to the United States, his father having won a green card lottery.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=jiH8UqXUKvgC|title=The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions|date=October 23, 2008|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-230-62108-4|language=en}}</ref> Chahal emigrated the following year, at age four. The family lived in a one-bedroom apartment in [[San Jose, California]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=40|language=en}}</ref> His father got a job in the Postal Service; his mother worked as an assistant to a nurse.<ref name=\":3\" /> He has two elder sisters \u2014 Nirmal and Kamal, and an elder brother Taj Chahal; the latter two had worked with Chahal in his ventures.<ref name=\":0\" /> His family were devout followers of [[Sikhism]].<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nAt age 16, Chahal dropped out of [[Independence High School (San Jose, California)|Independence High School]] to pursue a career in Internet advertising; his parents wished him to be a doctor, and Chahal has since noted this to be the biggest risk-prone decision taken in his career.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/style/article/Advice-from-young-millionaire-Gurbaksh-Chahal-3264414.php |title=Advice from young millionaire Gurbaksh Chahal |last=Zinko |first=Carolyne |date=October 26, 2008 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |access-date=January 6, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2008/11/04/cassidy-meet-g-silicon-valleys-celebrity-entrepreneur/|title=Cassidy: Meet G, Silicon Valley's celebrity entrepreneur|date=November 4, 2008|website=The Mercury News|language=en-US|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/staff-blog/what-really-scares-entrepreneurs.html|title=What Really Scares Entrepreneurs?|last=Lagorio-Chafkin|first=Christine|date=March 8, 2011|website=Inc.com|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> He has claimed of being subject to intense racial bullying during his school years including being forced to remove his [[Dastar|turban]], at knife-point.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-04-20/gwallets-chahal-balances-flashy-lifestyle-family-commitmentbusinessweek-business-news-stock-market-and-financial-advice|title=GWallet's Chahal Balances Flashy Lifestyle, Family Commitment|last=King|first=Rachael|date=April 20, 2010|website=Bloomberg|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.varsity.co.uk/news/2502|title=Gurbaksh Chahal: Dreaming in Gold|website=Varsity Online|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\n\nChahal started his career buying and reselling printers on [[eBay]], after being turned away from a job at [[McDonald's]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=jiH8UqXUKvgC|title=The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions|date=October 23, 2008|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-230-62108-4|location=|pages=9\u201310, 12|language=en}}</ref> His initial forays into business world were to support his family, and largely derived from his father's interests in stock-trading.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1743178/radiumone-ceo-his-mcdonalds-rejection-social-ads-and-do-not-track-legislation|title=RadiumOne CEO on His McDonald's Rejection, Social Ads, and Do-Not-Track Legislation|last=Ferenstein|first=Gregory|date=March 29, 2011|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ClickAgents ===\nIn 1998, Chahal founded ''ClickAgents'', an [[advertising network]] focused on performance-based advertising, on the lines of [[DoubleClick]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://darpanmagazine.com/people/businessleaders/gurbaksh-chahal-entrepreneur-extraordinaire/|title=People {{!}} Gurbaksh Chahal - Entrepreneur Extraordinaire|website=darpanmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> By 2000, it had numerous customers and had a staff-strength of 34.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=41|language=en}}</ref> It was acquired by [[Alliance Data|ValueClick]] in November 2000 in an all-stock deal valued at nearly $40 million, which paid his parents' mortgages lifting them out of poverty and made him an overnight millionaire.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://adage.com/article/news/valueclick-acquires-click-agents/10457/ |title=ValueClick acquires Click Agents |date=November 3, 2000 |work=AdvertisingAge |access-date=April 9, 2017 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410215832/http://adage.com/article/news/valueclick-acquires-click-agents/10457/ |archive-date=April 10, 2017 |publisher=Crain Communications |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2009/12/01/gwallet-raises-12-5m-for-more-ethical-virtual-currency-system/|title=gWallet raises $12.5M for more ethical virtual currency/offers system|date=December 1, 2009|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> \n\n=== BlueLithium ===\nIn 2004, Chahal co-founded BlueLithium, a company that specialized in [[Targeted advertising|behavioral targeting]], a technique whereby web users' habits online are tracked in order to show customized ads.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2391674.ece |title=Yahoo snaps up BlueLithium in $300m deal |last=Blakely |first=Rhys |date=September 5, 2007 |website=Times Online |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706001036/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2391674.ece |archive-date=July 6, 2008 |access-date=March 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1743178/radiumone-ceo-talks-mcdonalds-rejection-social-ads-and-do-not-track-legislation |title=RadiumOne CEO on His McDonald's Rejection, Social Ads, and Do-Not-Track Legislation |last=Ferenstein |first=Gregory |date=March 29, 2011 |website=Fast Company |access-date=March 1, 2015}}</ref> The ad-tech industry praised it with [[Business 2.0]] noting it to be among the 11 most disruptive innovations of 2006,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2006/09/15/technology/disruptors_bluelithium.biz2/index.htm|title=Business 2.0...Big Innovations: BlueLithium - Sep. 20, 2006|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> and by the same year, it had expanded operations to foreign countries, having purchased AdRevolver.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=42|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2004/11/22/daily5.html|title=BlueLithium to buy AdRevolver|work=[[American City Business Journals#Newspapers|Silicon Valley Business Journal]]|date=November 22, 2004|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> ''MingleNow'', a social network was simultaneously launched, which was accorded a partnership deal by [[Anheuser-Busch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/beer-fuels-social-networking-minglenow-clinks-anheuser-busch/|title=Beer fuels social networking: MingleNow 'Clinks' Anheuser-Busch|last=Bogatin|first=Donna|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> It was named among the top 100 private companies of America by AlwaysOn for three consecutive years<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://darpanmagazine.com/people/businessleaders/gurbaksh-chahal-entrepreneur-extraordinaire/|title=People {{!}} Gurbaksh Chahal - Entrepreneur Extraordinaire|website=darpanmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> and in 2007, [[Yahoo!]] bought it for $300 million in cash; Chahal remained CEO during interim period.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/09/04/yahoo-acquires-ad-network-bluelithium/ |title=Yahoo! Acquires Ad Network BlueLithium |date=September 4, 2007 |website=TechCrunch |access-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2007-09-03/targeting-you-yahoo-moves-deeper-into-behaviorial-targeting-with-bluelithium-purchase|title=Targeting You: Yahoo Moves Deeper into Behaviorial Targeting with BlueLithium Purchase|last=Hof|first=Rob|date=September 4, 2007|website=Bloomberg|access-date=}}</ref> It was the fifth largest ad-network in USA and second largest in UK, at time of sale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN0444409120070905|title=Yahoo buys behavioral ad firm for $300 mln|date=September 5, 2007|work=Reuters|access-date=February 9, 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== RadiumOne ===\n[[File:Gurbaksh Chahal receives E&Y Entrepreneur of the Year.jpg|thumb|Gurbaksh Chahal accepts E&Y Entrepreneur of the Year Award for RadiumOne, 2013]]\n\nIn 2009, Chahal founded RadiumOne, another online ad company<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2010/10/18/new-ad-network-radiumone-aims-to-tap-social-mega-trend/ |title=New Ad Network RadiumOne Aims To Tap Social 'Mega Trend' |last=McMahan |first=Ty |date=October 18, 2010 |work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> of a slightly different genre<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j2EMaVV1pE8C|title=Pioneers of Digital: Success Stories from Leaders in Advertising, Marketing, Search and Social Media|last=Carson|first=Mel|last2=Springer|first2=Paul|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|isbn=978-0-7494-6605-3|location=|pages=44|language=en}}</ref>, which started as a loyalty and rewards program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/business/ontherecord/article/Gurbaksh-Chahal-turns-RadiumOne-to-gold-4010360.php|title=Gurbaksh Chahal turns RadiumOne to gold|last=Lee|first=Ellen|date=November 5, 2012|website=SFGate|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> but later, migrated to targeted-advertising domain, having acquired multiple social-media-centered startups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2011/12/14/radiumone-buys-mobile-photo-sharing-app-developer-focal-labs/|title=RadiumOne Buys Mobile Photo Sharing App Developer Focal Labs|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> It garnered significant reputation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2011/05/20/radiumone-about-to-corner-the-market-on-social-data-before-competitors-even-know-whats-happening/|title=RadiumOne About To Corner The Market On Social Data Before Competitors Even Know What's Happening|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> for its patented ad-technology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmo.com.au/article/540068/radiumone_brings_programmatic_advertising_tech_platform_australia/|title=RadiumOne brings programmatic advertising tech platform to Australia|last=Cameron (CMO)|first=Nadia|last2=10 March|first2=2014 12:26|website=www.cmo.com.au|language=en-au|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2010/10/18/new-ad-network-radiumone-aims-to-tap-social-mega-trend/|title=New Ad Network RadiumOne Aims To Tap Social 'Mega Trend'|last=McMahan|first=Ty|date=October 18, 2010|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> with Chahal being poised to be a billionaire<ref name=\":10\" />, and was valued at about US$500 million at its peak. In 2014, the company failed to move on with IPO, as Chahal plead guilty to domestic violence. In 2017 it was purchased by [[RhythmOne]] for US$22 million.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n=== Gravity4 ===\nIn July 2014, Chahal launched Gravity4 (since renamed to DaVinci Marketing Cloud).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mrweb.com/drno/news25671.htm |title=Name Change Marks Renaissance for Gravity4 |last=Crowther |first=Mel |last2=Thomas |first2=Nick |date=January 31, 2018 |website=MrWeb |access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> It made a failed bid to buy back RadiumOne and closed in 2017, being unable to integrate the purchased ad-tech startups.<ref name=\"SFChronicleHuet\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/business/article/Gurbaksh-Chahal-flew-high-and-fell-fast-9140090.php|title=Gurbaksh Chahal flew high and fell fast|last=Huet|first=Ellen|date=August 13, 2016|website=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.techcircle.in/2019/11/12/post-radiumone-gurbaksh-chahal-seeks-success-again-with-redlotus-in-talks-to-raise-50-mn|title=Post RadiumOne, Gurbaksh Chahal seeks success again with RedLotus; in talks to raise $50 mn|date=November 12, 2019|website=Techcircle|language=en-US|access-date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n=== RedLotus ===\nIn 2019, Chahal founded TaaraLabs, an incubator and RedLotus in Hong Kong, which specializes in [[Artificial intelligence|AI]]-based targeted advertising.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.techcircle.in/2019/11/12/post-radiumone-gurbaksh-chahal-seeks-success-again-with-redlotus-in-talks-to-raise-50-mn |title=Post RadiumOne, Gurbaksh Chahal seeks success again with RedLotus; in talks to raise $50 mn |last=Ganguly |first=Payal |date=November 12, 2019 |website=TechCircle |language=en-US |access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://mandiner.hu/cikk/20191229_az_erettsegizetlen_milliardos|title=Az \u00e9retts\u00e9gizetlen milli\u00e1rdos|last=D\u00e1niel|first=Ol\u00e1h|date=|website=mandiner.hu|language=hu|url-access=subscription|access-date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and philanthropy==\n[[File:Gurbaksh Chahal with Donald Trump at the Leaders in Management Award function, Pace University.jpg|thumb|Chahal with [[Donald Trump]] at the 2009 Leaders in Management Award function, [[Pace University]].]]\nIn 2010, [[Bloomberg Businessweek]] named him among the 15 best young entrepreneurs of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/10/04/0419_best_young_tech_entrepreneurs/4.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202224009/http://images.businessweek.com/ss/10/04/0419_best_young_tech_entrepreneurs/4.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 2, 2013|title=Best Young Tech Entrepreneurs 2010: GWallet - BusinessWeek|date=December 2, 2013|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> In the same year, Chahal's alma mater [[Evergreen Valley College]] awarded him with an Honorary Degree in Business Administration<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=EVERGREEN VALLEY COLLEGE PRESENTS AN HONORARY DEGREE TO LOCAL SAN JOSE GUY TURNED MILLIONNAIRE|work=Two Colleges:One Community - Official Newsletter of San Jose . Evergreen Community College District|access-date=|date= July 2010|issue=41|page=3}}</ref> and [[Pace University]] conferred the Leaders in Management Award and a Honorary Doctorate in Commercial Sciences; he had earlier established an endowed entrepreneurial scholarship program over the university.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Internet-star-Chahal-getting-honorary-doctorate-3190862.php|title=Internet star Chahal getting honorary doctorate|last=Zinko|first=Carolyne|date=April 29, 2010|website=SFGate|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> In 2012, [[Complex (magazine)|Complex magazine]] put him in a list of the 25 richest entrepreneurs under the age of 30;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2012/08/the-25-richest-tech-entrepreneurs-under-30/|title=The 25 Richest Tech Entrepreneurs Under 3017. Aaron Levie, 27|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> in the same year he received the Light of India Amrapali Young Achievers award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/light-of-india_b_1729802|title=Global Indians Illuminate Fifth Avenue at Light of India Awards|last1=Luce|first1=Jim|date=August 2, 2012|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=January 31, 2020|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/global/light-of-india-awards-brings-global-indians-together/article_1cf2fc29-b789-5614-b741-8cd187fda662.html|title='Light of India' Awards Brings Global Indians Together|last1=Vijayakar|first1=R. M.|date=June 27, 2012|work=India West|language=en}}</ref> In 2013, he was named as one of the [[Ernst and Young]] entrepreneurs of the year<ref name=\"businessinsider.com\">{{Cite news|last=Carson|first=Biz|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/gurbaksh-chahal-rise-and-fall-background-history-2015-11|title=The rise and fall of Gurbaksh Chahal: How one tech CEO went from fame, fortune, and Oprah's couch to possible jail time|date=August 14, 2016|work=Business Insider|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\" /> and the following year, Complex noted him among the top 10 technology entrepreneurs of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/07/10-tech-entrepreneurs-who-risked-it-all-and-made-it|title=10 Tech Entrepreneurs Who Risked It All and Made It|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, [[Delhi Sikh Gurdwara Management Committee]] honored him for contributions made to the field of entrepreneurship.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/gurbaksh-chahal-honoured-by-dsgmc-shares-the-moment-with-former-pm-manmohan-singh-7426791.html|title=Gurbaksh Chahal honoured by DSGMC, shares the moment with former PM Manmohan Singh|website=Firstpost|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Chahal has been a guest lecturer at several universities including [[London School of Economics]], [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]] et al.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://evideo.elab.nyc/entrepreneurs-roundtable-special-guest-speaker-gurbaksh-chahal-2-of-16_e8bfc1535.html|title=Entrepreneurs Roundtable - Special Guest Speaker Gurbaksh Chahal (2 Of 16)|website=evideo.elab.nyc|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Top 10 Mistakes Made by Entrepreneurs|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gtHZUr3mdlY|language=en|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lse.ac.uk/lse-player/home.aspx|title=LSE Player|last=Science|first=London School of Economics and Political|website=London School of Economics and Political Science|language=en-GB|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uctv.tv/shows/Ambition-Discipline-Purpose-The-Journey-of-Being-an-Entrepreneur-with-Gurbaksh-Chahal-24409|title=VIDEO: Ambition. Discipline. Purpose. The Journey of Being an Entrepreneur with Gurbaksh Chahal|last=|date=|website=www.uctv.tv|language=en|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, after the [[Wisconsin Sikh temple shooting]], he committed US$1 million to found BeProud (since renamed to Chahal Foundation), a [[Foundation (nonprofit)|charitable foundation]] that supports the families of [[hate crime]] victims and combats [[child trafficking in India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/224248|title=Serial Entrepreneur Gurbaksh Chahal Commits $1 Million to Stop Hate Crimes|last=Evans|first=Teri|date=August 21, 2012|website=Entrepreneur|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Sikh-entrepreneur-to-launch-Be-Proud-movement-to-fight-hate/articleshow/16164261.cms|title=Sikh entrepreneur to launch 'Be Proud' movement to fight hate {{!}} India News - Times of India|last=Sep 2|first=Atul Sethi {{!}} TNN {{!}}|last2=2012|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=February 10, 2020|last3=Ist|first3=02:11}}</ref><ref name=\":13\" /> It had liaisoned with [[Church of the Latter-Day Saints]] to provide employment scopes for rural women in Maharashtra, India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news-in.churchofjesuschrist.org/many-organizations-including-lds-charities-joined-forces-to-create-feminine-hygiene-kits|title=LDS Charities and Feminine Hygiene|date=May 9, 2018|website=news-in.churchofjesuschrist.org|language=en|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, Chahal committed to evolving Punjab as the next tech capital of India, and create over a million jobs for the youth populace by 2030 through suitable investments. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashar|first=A.S.|url=|title=Punjab's Economic Salvation may lie in promotion of IT Sector|date=June 9, 2019|work=Punjab Express|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sheetal|first=|url=|title=Tracing the path of progress|date=June 9, 2019|work=Punjab Tribune|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Internet entrepreneur aims to create million jobs in Punjab's IT sector|date=June 9, 2019|work=Daily Post|access-date=}}</ref> In 2020, Chahal donated face masks, test kits, [[Personal protective equipment|personal protective equipments]] and ventilators to hospitals across several countries (including Hong Kong and India) during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Coronavirus pandemic]], and extended procurement networks to help governments in mitigating the supply-chain chaos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rthk.hk/tv/dtt31/programme/thismorning/episode/617329|title=\u6e2f\u53f0\u96fb\u8996 31 \u65e9\u8fb0\u3002\u65e9\u6668 - \u624b\u8a9e\u76f4\u64ad\u7bc0\u76ee\ufe30\u5ec1\u7d19\u6436\u52ab\u6848\uff1b\u300a\u65e9\u8fb0\u4e00\u4ef6\u4e8b\u300b\uff1a\u75ab\u5883\u6709\u60c5\uff1b\u300a\u65e9\u8fb0\u4fdd\u6297\u529b\u300b\uff1a\u7dad\u4ed6\u547dC|website=www.rthk.hk|language=zh-hant|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/rubina-bajwa-and-beau-gurbaksh-chahal-team-up-to-help-hong-kong-charity-prevent-spread-of-coronavirus/articleshow/74084543.cms|title=Rubina Bajwa and beau Gurbaksh Chahal team up to help Hong Kong charity prevent spread of Coronavirus - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkcnews.com/article/27053/\u53e3\u7f69\u77ed\u7f3a-27053/\u300c\u653f\u5e9c\u505a\u5497\u5572\u54a9\uff1f\u300d\u2014\u2014\u6c11\u9593\u6536\u96c6\u53e3\u7f69\u52a9\u57fa\u5c64-|title=\u300c\u653f\u5e9c\u505a\u5497\u5572\u54a9\uff1f\u300d\u2014\u2014\u6c11\u9593\u6536\u96c6\u53e3\u7f69\u52a9\u57fa\u5c64 {{!}} \u8b80\u8005\u4f86\u8ad6|website=\u773e\u65b0\u805e|language=zh|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/we-are-working-on-delivering-test-kits-ventilators-and-respirators-rubina-bajwa-and-gurbaksh-chahals-initiative-for-covid-19-patients/articleshow/74844533.cms|title=\"We are working on delivering test kits, ventilators, and respirators\u201d; Rubina Bajwa and Gurbaksh Chahal\u2019s initiative for Covid-19 patients - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/the-world-needs-as-much-help-it-can-get-at-this-time-says-rubina-bajwa-as-beau-gurbaksh-chahal-extends-help-for-covid-19-relief/articleshow/75025243.cms|title=\u201cThe world needs as much help it can get at this time\u201d, says Rubina Bajwa as beau Gurbaksh Chahal extends help for Covid-19 relief - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Chahal with U.S. President Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|Chahal with Obama at a Fundraising Dinner in San Francisco, 2012]]\nChahal is currently in a relationship with [[Punjabi cinema|Punjabi film]] actress [[Rubina Bajwa]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/news/exclusive-rubina-bajwa-confirms-her-relationship-gurbaksh-chahal-says-he-centre-my-world-491048|title=EXCLUSIVE: Rubina Bajwa CONFIRMS her relationship with Gurbaksh Chahal; Says 'He is the centre of my world'|last=Kaur|first=Ranpreet|date=December 10, 2019|website=PINKVILLA|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/rubina-bajwa-spends-the-last-few-days-of-2019-vacationing-with-beau-gurbaksh-singh-chahal-and-the-pics-will-make-you-crave-for-a-holiday/articleshow/72993511.cms|title=Rubina Bajwa spends the last few days of 2019 vacationing with beau Gurbaksh Singh Chahal and the pics will make you crave for a holiday! - Times of India|date=December 27, 2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>; he previously resided in [[San Francisco Bay Area]] but is currently based in [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\":15\" /> \n\nChahal has attracted attention for his physique and extravagant lifestyle including a fleet of luxurious cars and a penthouse apartment.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has been featured over [[Fox Business]] and [[CNBC]]'s High Net Worth<ref name=\":16\" /> and has been invited as an guest over the [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/millionaire-moguls/10|title=Millionaire Moguls|work=Oprah.com|access-date=February 4, 2020|language=en-us}}</ref> He has been also featured over [[The Secret Millionaire]], where he went undercover in [[San Francisco]] and gave away $110,000 of his wealth<ref>{{Cite news|last=ZIPKIN|first=GURBAKSH CHAHAL; as told to AMY|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/07/jobs/07boss.html|title=First, $99. Then, Millions.|date=September 6, 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 4, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2008/12/16/bluelithium-founder-gurbaksh-chahal-keeps-his-millions-secret-for-once/|title=BlueLithium founder Gurbaksh Chahal keeps his millions \"Secret\" for once|date=December 17, 2008|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>, [[The Bonnie Hunt Show]], where he auctioned off his pen for charity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-bonnie-hunt-show/episode-67-season-1/the-bonnie-hunt-show/295098|title=The Bonnie Hunt Show {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>, and on [[Extra (American TV program)|ExtraTV]] as America's most eligible bachelor.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> In 2011, [[Men's Health]] awarded him the seventh spot in the list of the world's fittest and richest men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.menshealth.com/trending-news/a19540258/worlds-fittest-richest-guys/|title=The World's Richest and Fittest Guys|last=Sine|first=Richard|date=April 11, 2011|website=Men's Health|language=en-US|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> \n\nChahal profess to be a devout Sikh, who was largely inspired by his grandmother<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/supplement/story/20110905-i-take-my-culture-wherever-i-go-747348-2011-08-24|title=I take my culture wherever I go|last=Chitkara|first=Vanita|date=|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> and takes a keen interest in Bollywood, admiring [[Shah Rukh Khan]] and [[A. R. Rahman]] in particular.<ref name=\":4\" /> Chahal was a regular donor to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidates; he was twice invited to White House during [[Barack Obama]]'s presidency.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peterson|first=Andrea|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/04/29/dccc-distances-itself-from-tech-ceo-fired-after-domestic-violence-conviction/|title=DCCC distances itself from tech CEO fired after domestic violence conviction|date=April 29, 2014|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiapost.com/avtar-chahal-meets-obama-first-lady/|title=Avtar Chahal meets Obama, First Lady|website=India Post|language=en-US|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> \n\nHe is also a motivational speaker,<ref name=\":13\" /> advocates [[one-dollar salary]] for CEOs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3021501/im-a-ceo-with-a-paycheck-of-0-and-you-should-join-me|title=I'm A CEO With A Paycheck Of $0\u2013And You Should Join Me|last=Chahal|first=Gurbaksh|date=November 13, 2013|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>, and has written an autobiography called ''The Dream.''<ref name=\":14\" /> During the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|2020 Coronavirus pandemic]], Chahal became a vocal critic of governments and urged them to update their monetary policies in order to salvage their economies. He also spoke out against increasing xenophobia targeting the Chinese populace.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/indias-virus-stricken-economy-is-in-a-dire-need-of-a-vaccine/articleshow/74799325.cms|title=View: India's virus-stricken economy is in a dire need of a vaccine|date=March 25, 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/letters/article/3077003/coronavirus-twin-crisis-why-hong-kongs-carrie-lam-must-match-west|title=Why Carrie Lam must bring out the big guns to fight virus|date=March 27, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/don-t-be-racist-blame-the-government-not-its-people-opinion/story-K8HjJ9xTrjXsYgOeVaQ2hN.html|title=Don\u2019t be racist: Blame the government, not its people {{!}} Opinion|date=March 27, 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/views/coronavirus-lockdown-but-what-is-india-missing-5566591.htm|title=Coronavirus lockdown: But what is India missing?|website=cnbctv18.com|language=en-US|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/views/numbers-dont-lie-but-in-the-world-of-covid-19-they-do-5611231.htm|title=Numbers Don\u2019t Lie: But, in the world of COVID-19 they do|website=cnbctv18.com|language=en-US|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/economy/covid-19-why-india-must-offer-more-financial-stimulus-and-not-just-put-employers-in-debt-5090231.html|title=COVID-19 {{!}} Why India must offer more financial stimulus and not just put employers in debt|website=Moneycontrol|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Domestic violence and battery conviction ===\nIn August 2013, the [[San Francisco District Attorney's Office]] (SFDA) charged Chahal with committing acts of domestic violence against his girlfriend.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Newton|date=2014|editor-last=Lee|editor-first=Newton|title=Personal Total Information Awareness|journal=Facebook Nation|language=en|publisher=Springer|pages=305\u2013345|doi=10.1007/978-1-4939-1740-2_15|isbn=978-1-4939-1740-2}}</ref> Chahal proclaimed his innocence<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/crime/article/Internet-mogul-pleads-not-guilty-to-assault-4719376.php|title=Internet mogul pleads not guilty to assault|last=Alexander|first=Kurtis|last2=Ho|first2=Vivian|date=August 8, 2013|website=San Francisco Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref> but nevertheless entered into a [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] plea to one charge of domestic violence battery and one charge of [[battery (crime)|battery]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/internet-mogul-accused-of-domestic-violence-pleads-guilty-to-two-misdemeanors/|title=Internet mogul accused of domestic violence pleads guilty to two misdemeanors|date=April 18, 2014|website=The San Francisco Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> He was sentenced to three years' [[probation]], ordered to pay a fine, and compelled to undergo a 52-week domestic violence training course along with 25 hours of [[community service]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Subsequently, he was fired from his position as CEO of RadiumOne and the company failed to move on with IPO <ref name=\"Fortune2014\">{{Cite web|url=http://finance.fortune.cnn.com/2014/04/25/its-time-for-radiumone-to-fire-its-abusive-ceo/|title=It's time for RadiumOne's abusive CEO to go|last=Primack|first=Dan|date=April 25, 2014|website=Fortune|publisher=CNN Money|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140601064812/http://finance.fortune.cnn.com/2014/04/25/its-time-for-radiumone-to-fire-its-abusive-ceo/|archive-date=June 1, 2014|access-date=March 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Nagle\">{{Cite news|last=Elder|first=Jeff|title=Tech Firm Tried to Save IPO Amid CEO Scandal|date=September 10, 2015|work=Wall Street Journal|issn=00999660|id={{ProQuest|1710603396}}}}</ref>; Chahal has since alleged that his guilty plea was coerced by the board of RadiumOne.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/gurbaksh-chahal-former-ceo-fired-after-domestic-violence-plea-settles-dispute-with-radiumone/|title=Gurbaksh Chahal, former CEO fired after domestic violence plea, settles dispute with RadiumOne|date=July 21, 2014|website=The San Francisco Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/gurbaksh-chahal-blasts-media-board-2014-4|title=RADIUMONE CEO: My Board Betrayed Me, Even Though I Made Them A Fortune|last=Weisenthal|first=Joe|website=Business Insider|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the [[San Francisco County Superior Court]] found Chahal guilty of violating his September 2014 probation, upon another prosecution by SFDA for acts of domestic violence against a second woman with whom he was in a relationship.<ref name=\"sentencing\">{{Cite news|last=Rainey|first=Libby|url=http://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/SF-judge-to-decide-fate-of-Gurbaksh-Chahal-in-9139376.php|title=Tech mogul Gurbaksh Chahal gets 1 year in domestic violence case|date=August 12, 2016|work=San Francisco Chroncile|access-date=November 1, 2016}}</ref> He was sentenced to a year in jail and resigned from his position as CEO of Gravity4.<ref name=\"sentencing\" /> The California State Appeals Court upheld the verdict in April 2018<ref name=\"sfgate.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/Court-upholds-ruling-against-SF-tech-mogul-Chahal-12870668.php|title=Court upholds ruling against SF tech mogul Chahal in domestic violence case|last=Ma|first=Annie|date=April 28, 2018|work=SFGate|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref> and Chahal served six months in [[San Francisco County Jails|San Francisco County Jail]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/ojs-lawyer-and-the-woman-abusing-princeling-of-silicon-valley|title=O.J.'s Lawyer and the Woman-Abusing Princeling of Silicon Valley|first=Michael|last=Daly|date=September 3, 2018|via=www.thedailybeast.com}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''The Dream: How I Learned the Risks and Rewards of Entrepreneurship and Made Millions'', Palgrave Macmillan (October 23, 2008) {{ISBN|0-230-61095-1}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|3223893|name=Gurbaksh Chahal}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gtHZUr3mdlY A panel discussion with Chahal], Conference on Entrepreneurship, [[Stanford University Graduate School of Business]], March 2010\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chahal, Gurbaksh}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American media executives]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:American technology writers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in advertising]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Tarn Taran Sahib]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:American people of Punjabi descent]]\n[[Category:American businessmen of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:21st-century American inventors]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gurbaksh_Chahal"}
{"title_page": "George Stinney", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = George Junius Stinney, Jr.\n| image_name = George Stinney mugshot.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = George Stinney's 1944 mug shot\n| birth_name = George Junius Stinney Jr.\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1929|10|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Pinewood, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1944|6|16|1929|10|21}}\n| death_place = [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]], [[South Carolina]], U.S.\n| apprehended = March 1944\n| conviction = [[First-degree murder]] (overturned)\n| conviction_penalty = Death by [[electric chair]]\n| conviction_status = {{Plainlist|\n* Executed (1944)\n[[Vacated judgment|Conviction overturned]] (2014)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''George Junius Stinney, Jr.''' (October 21, 1929 \u2013 June 16, 1944), was an [[African Americans|African American]] youth who was convicted, in a proceeding later vacated as an unfair trial, of murdering two [[White Americans|white]] girls, ages 7 and 11, in his hometown of [[Alcolu, South Carolina]]. He was executed by electric chair in June of that year.\n\nThe court refused to hear his appeal, and the appeals on his behalf to the governor for clemency were denied.{{Citation needed|reason=No citation for the court refusing to hear an appeal.|date=December 2019}} He is the youngest American to be sentenced to death and executed.<ref name=banner>{{cite news |last=Banner |first=Stuart |date=March 5, 2005 |title=When Killing a Juvenile Was Routine |url=https://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2005/03/05/weekinreview/20050306_BANNER_CHART.html |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=April 12, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412063127/http://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2005/03/05/weekinreview/20050306_BANNER_CHART.html |url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nA re-examination of the Stinney case began in 2004, and several individuals and [[Northeastern University School of Law]] sought a judicial review. His conviction was overturned in 2014, 70 years after he was executed when a court ruled that he had not received a fair trial.\n\n==Incident==\nTwo young white girls, 11-year-old Betty June Binnicker and 7-year-old Mary Emma Thames, were found dead in the company mill town of [[Alcolu, South Carolina]], in March 1944, after they had failed to return home the night before.\n\n==Arrest and prosecution==\nPolice arrested 14-year-old George Stinney as a suspect. They stated that he had confessed to the crime while under custody.<ref name=ins>{{Cite web |title=State Prison Protects Negro after Slaying |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19440327&id=ldM0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=oE4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5724,7818032&hl=en |date=March 25, 1944 |agency=[[International News Service|INS]] |publisher = [[St. Petersburg Times]] |accessdate=October 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=ap>{{Cite web |title=Youth Admits Killing Girls |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1499&dat=19440325&id=AfAZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4356,3574612&hl=en |date=March 25, 1944 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |publisher = [[The Milwaukee Journal]] |accessdate = October 18, 2015}}</ref> There was a written record of his confession in the form of notes provided by an investigating deputy.<ref name=mcveigh>{{Cite news |last = McVeigh |first = Karen |date=March 22, 2014 |title = George Stinney was executed at 14. Can his family now clear his name? |url = https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2014/mar/22/george-stinney-execution-verdict-innocent |newspaper = [[The Observer]] |archive-date= March 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319042807/http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2014/mar/22/george-stinney-execution-verdict-innocent |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNo transcript was recorded of the brief trial. Stinney was convicted of [[first-degree murder]] of the two girls in less than 10 minutes by an [[all-white jury]], during a two hour trial.<ref name=bever>{{cite news |last=Bever |first=Lindsey |date=December 18, 2014 |title=It took 10 minutes to convict 14-year-old George Stinney Jr. It took 70 years after his execution to exonerate him. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/12/18/the-rush-job-conviction-of-14-year-old-george-stinney-exonerated-70-years-after-execution/ |publisher=[[Washington Post]]}}</ref> The court refused to hear his appeal. He was executed that year, still age 14, by [[electric chair]].\n\nIn the decades since Stinney's conviction and execution, the question of his guilt, the validity of his reported confession, and the judicial process leading to his execution have been extensively criticized.<ref name=collins>{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Jeffrey |date=January 18, 2010 |title=SC crusaders look to right Jim Crow justice wrongs |url=http://www.goupstate.com/article/20100118/ARTICLES/100119732 |agency=AP |publisher=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |archive-date=May 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529172647/http://www.goupstate.com/article/20100118/articles/100119732 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA group of lawyers and activists investigated the Stinney case on behalf of his family. In 2013, the family petitioned for a new trial. On December 17, 2014, his conviction was posthumously [[Vacated judgment|vacated]] 70 years after his execution, because the circuit court judge ruled that he had not been given a fair trial; he had no effective defense representation and his [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] rights had been violated.<ref name=wis>{{cite web |last=Turnage |first=Jeremy |date=December 17, 2014 |url=http://www.wistv.com/story/27651255/george-stinney-14-year-old-convicted-of-44-murder-exonerated |title=George Stinney, 14-year-old convicted of '44 murder, exonerated |publisher=[[WIS (TV)|WIS]] |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223031/http://www.wistv.com/story/27651255/george-stinney-14-year-old-convicted-of-44-murder-exonerated |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=mccloud>{{cite news |last=McCloud |first=Harriet |date=December 17, 2014 |title=South Carolina judge tosses conviction of black teen executed in 1944\n |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-south-carolina-idUSKBN0JV25320141217 |agency=[[Reuters]] |archive-date=December 22, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222110718/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-south-carolina-idUSKBN0JV25320141217 |url-status=live }}</ref> The judgment noted that while Stinney could have committed the crime, the prosecution and trial were fundamentally flawed.<ref name=mcveigh /> Judge Mullen ruled that his confession was likely coerced and thus inadmissible. She also found that the execution of a 14-year-old constituted \"[[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|cruel and unusual punishment]].\"<ref name=barbato />\n\n==Case background==\nIn 1944, George Junius Stinney, Jr. lived in [[Alcolu, South Carolina|Alcolu]], [[Clarendon County, South Carolina]]. The 14-year-old lived with his father, George Stinney Sr., mother Aim\u00e9, brothers  John, 17, and Charles, 12, and sisters Katherine, 10, and Aim\u00e9, 7. George Sr. worked at the town's sawmill, and the family resided in company housing. Alcolu was a small, working-class mill town, where white and black neighborhoods were separated by railroad tracks. The town was typical of small Southern towns of the time. Given segregated schools and churches for white and black residents, there was limited interaction between them. <ref name=mcveigh />\n\nThe bodies of Betty June Binnicker, age 11, and Mary Emma Thames, age 7, were found in a ditch on March 23, 1944, on the African American side of Alcolu, during a search after they had not returned home the night before.<ref name=collins /> George Stinney Sr. helped in the search. The girls had been beaten with a weapon, variously reported as a piece of blunt metal or a railroad spike.<ref name=bever /> The girls were last seen riding their bicycles looking for flowers.\n\nAs they passed the Stinneys' property, they had asked young George Stinney and his sister, Aim\u00e9,<ref name=mcveigh /> if they knew where to find \"[[Passiflora incarnata|maypops]]\", a local name for passionflowers.<ref name=ap /> According to Aim\u00e9, she was with George at the time the police later established for the murders.<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nAccording to an article reported by the wire services on March 24, 1944, and published widely, with the mistake of the boy's name preserved, the sheriff announced the arrest and said that \"George Junius\" had confessed and led officers to \"a hidden piece of iron.\"<ref name=ins /><ref name=ap /> Both girls had suffered [[Blunt trauma|blunt force trauma]] to the face and head.<ref name=jones>{{cite book |last=Jones |first=Mark R. |title=South Carolina Killers: Crimes of Passion |url=https://archive.org/details/southcarolinakil00jone |url-access=registration |accessdate=November 24, 2014 |year=2007 |publisher=[[The History Press]] |isbn=978-1-59629-395-3 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/southcarolinakil00jone/page/38 38]\u201342 |chapter=Chapter Five: ''Too Young to Die: The Execution of George Stinney Jr.'' (1944)}}</ref>\n\nReports differed as to what kind of weapon had been used.<ref name=berkeley/> According to a report by the medical examiner, these wounds had been \"inflicted by a blunt instrument with a round head, about the size of a hammer.\" Both girls' skulls were punctured. The medical examiner reported no evidence of sexual assault to the younger girl, though the genitalia of the older girl were slightly bruised.<ref name=\"crrj\">{{cite press release |url=http://nuweb9.neu.edu/civilrights/crrj-brings-justice-to-youngest-person-executed-in-us-history/ |title=CRRJ Brings Justice to Youngest Person Executed in US History |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103223902/http://nuweb9.neu.edu/civilrights/crrj-brings-justice-to-youngest-person-executed-in-us-history/ |archivedate=January 3, 2015 |accessdate=January 3, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=mclaughlin>{{cite web|last=McLaughlin |first=Eliot C.|date=January 23, 2014 |title=New trial sought for George Stinney, executed at 14 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/21/us/george-stinney-hearing/ |website=[[CNN]] |archive-date=April 10, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410224104/http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/21/us/george-stinney-hearing/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=independent>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Tim |date=January 22, 2014 |title=George Stinney: After 70 years, justice in sight for boy America sent to electric chair |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/after-70-years-justice-in-sight-for-boy-america-sent-to-electric-chair-9078460.html |website=[[The Independent]] |archive-date=March 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305021418/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/after-70-years-justice-in-sight-for-boy-america-sent-to-electric-chair-9078460.html |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nGeorge Stinney and his older brother Johnny were arrested on suspicion of murdering the girls. Johnny was released by police, but George was held. He was not allowed to see his parents until after his trial and conviction.<ref name=mcveigh /> According to a handwritten statement, the arresting officer was H.S. Newman, a Clarendon County deputy, who stated, \"I arrested a boy by the name of George Stinney. He then made a confession and told me where to find a piece of iron about 15 inches were [sic] he said he put it in a ditch about six feet from the bicycle.\" No confession statement signed by Stinney is known to exist. The 14 year old claimed that the arresting officers starved him and then bribed him with food to confess.<ref name=mcveigh /><ref name=mclaughlin />\n\nGeorge was reported to have gotten into fights at school, including a fight where he scratched a girl with a knife. This assertion by Stinney's seventh-grade teacher, who was African American, was disputed by Aime Stinney Ruffner when it was reported in 1995. A local white woman who remembered Stinney from childhood said in 2014 that Stinney had threatened to kill her and her friend the day before the murder, and that he was known as a bully.<ref name=mcveigh /><ref name=behre>{{Cite web |last=Behre |first=Robert |date= January 17, 2014 |title=Family, friends of 1944 murder victim wary of reopening George Stinney\u2019s death penalty case |url= http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140117/PC1610/140119506 |website=[[The Post and Courier]] |archive-date=June 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603111624/http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140117/PC1610/140119506 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing George's arrest, his father was fired from his job at the local sawmill, and the Stinney family had to immediately vacate their company housing. The family feared for their safety. The community as well as the police threatened to lynch their other children if they did not leave immediately.{{cn|date=December 2019}} His parents did not see George again before the trial. He had no support during his 81-day confinement and trial; he was detained at a jail in Columbia 50 miles from Alcolu, due to the risk of lynching.<ref name=collins /> Stinney was questioned alone, without his parents or an attorney.<ref name=bever /> Although the [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] guarantees legal counsel, it was not until 1963 ''[[Gideon v. Wainwright]]'' that explicitly required representation through the course of criminal proceedings.<ref name=bever />\n\n==Trial==\nThe entire proceeding against Stinney, including jury selection, took one day. Stinney's court-appointed defense counsel was Charles Plowden, a tax commissioner campaigning for election to local office. Plowden did not challenge the three police officers who testified that Stinney confessed to the two murders, despite this being the only evidence against him.\n\nHe did not challenge the prosecution's presentation of two differing versions of Stinney's verbal confession. In one version, Stinney was attacked by the girls after he tried to help one girl who had fallen in the ditch, and he killed them in self defense. In the other version, he had followed the girls, first attacking Mary Emma and then Betty June. There was no physical evidence linking him to the murders.<ref name=mcveigh /> There is no written record of Stinney's confession apart from Deputy Newman's statement.<ref name=collins />\n\nStinney's trial had an [[all-white jury]], as was typical at the time. As most blacks were still [[Disfranchisement after Reconstruction era|disenfranchised]] and prohibited from voting, they could not be selected as jurors. More than 1,000 whites crowded the courtroom, but no blacks were allowed.<ref name=collins />\n\nOther than the testimony of the three police officers, at trial prosecutors called three witnesses: Reverend Francis Batson, who discovered the bodies of the two girls, and the two doctors who performed the post-mortem examination. Conflicting confessions were reported to have been offered by the prosecution. The court allowed discussion of the \"possibility\" of rape although the medical examiner's report had no evidence to support this. Stinney's counsel did not call any witnesses, did not cross-examine witnesses, and offered little or no defense. The trial presentation lasted two and a half hours.<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nThe jury took less than ten minutes to [[jury deliberation|deliberate]], after which they returned with a guilty verdict. Judge [[Philip H. Stoll]] sentenced Stinney to death by electrocution. There is no transcript of the trial. No appeal was filed by his defense attorney.<ref name=collins />\n\nStinney's family, churches, and the [[NAACP]] appealed to Governor [[Olin D. Johnston]] for clemency, given the age of the boy. Others urged the governor to let the execution proceed, which he did.<ref name=jones /> Johnston wrote in a response to one appeal for clemency that \n\n<blockquote>It may be interesting for you to know that Stinney killed the smaller girl to rape the larger one. Then he killed the larger girl and raped her dead body. Twenty minutes later he returned and attempted to rape her again, but her body was too cold. All of this he admitted himself.</blockquote>\n\nBetween the time of Stinney's arrest and his execution, Stinney's parents were allowed to see him once, after the trial when he was held in the Columbia penitentiary. Under the threat of lynching, they were not allowed to see him any other time. <ref name=mcveigh />\n\n==Execution==\nGeorge Stinney was executed at the Central Correctional Institution in Columbia, South Carolina on June 16, 1944, at 7:30 p.m. At 7:25 pm, standing 5 feet 1 inch tall and weighing just over 90 lbs three police officers approached the cell where George was being held, one officer entered and took him out of his cell. The officers escorted him to the execution room where they placed him in the electric chair, using a Bible he was carrying as a booster seat because George was so small.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/george-stinney-jr-black-14-year-old-boy-exonerated-70-years-after-he-was-executed-9932429.html|title=He was 14 when he was executed. More than 70 years later, this boy has been exonerated|date=2014-12-18|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> George was then restrained by his arms, legs, body to the chair. His father was allowed to approach George to say his final words to his son. An officer asked George if he had any last words to say, but George just shook his head. George Stinney could only whimper and take big deep breaths as one of the officers pulled a strap from the chair and placed it over his mouth, causing George to break into tears. They then placed the face mask over his face, which did not fit him, as George continued sobbing. When the lethal electricity was applied, the mask covering George's face slipped off, revealing George's burned scalp and tears streaming down his face, saliva dripping from his mouth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/12/18/the-rush-job-conviction-of-14-year-old-george-stinney-exonerated-70-years-after-execution/|title=It took 10 minutes to convict 14-year-old George Stinney Jr. It took 70 years after his execution to exonerate him.|last=Bever|first=Lindsey|date=2014-12-18|work=Washington Post|access-date=2019-09-24|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> {{Citation needed span|text=George Stinney was declared dead after eight minutes. George's teeth were smoking and he had one eye missing. The next day (Saturday, June 17, 1944) he was buried by his family at Sumter, South Carolina. For a long time, his body was in an unmarked grave in hopes that the anonymity would allow him to forever rest in peace.|date=September 2019|reason=}}\n\n==Reopening of case and vacatur of conviction==\nIn 2004, George Frierson, a local historian who grew up in Alcolu, started researching the case after reading a newspaper article about it. His work gained the attention of South Carolina lawyers Steve McKenzie and Matt Burgess.<ref name=mcveigh /> In addition, Ray Brown, attorney James Moon, and others contributed countless hours of research and review of historical documents, and found witnesses and evidence to assist in exonerating Stinney. Among those who aided the case were the [[Civil Rights and Restorative Justice Project]] (CRRJ) at [[Northeastern University School of Law]], which filed an ''amicus'' brief with the court in 2014.<ref name=barbato>{{cite web |last=Barbato |first=Lauren |date=December 17, 2014 |title=The Youngest Person Executed In America, George Stinney Jr., Almost Certainly Wasn't Guilty |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/54488-the-youngest-person-executed-in-america-george-stinney-jr-almost-certainly-wasnt-guilty |website=[[Bustle.com]]}}</ref> Frierson and the ''pro bono'' lawyers first sought relief through the Pardon and Parole Board of South Carolina.\n\nMcKenzie and Burgess, along with attorney Ray Chandler representing Stinney's family, filed a motion for a new trial on October 25, 2013.<ref name=ebony>{{cite news |last= Braswell | first= Kristin | title= Film to Explore George Stinney Jr. Execution | url= http://www.ebony.com/news-views/film-to-explore-george-stinney-jr-execution-405 | date=February 28, 2014 | work= [[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]] |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304131221/http://www.ebony.com/news-views/film-to-explore-george-stinney-jr-execution-405 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n \n{{quote|If we can get the case re-opened, we can go to the judge and say, 'There wasn't any reason to convict this child. There was no evidence to present to the jury. There was no transcript. This case needs to be re-opened. This is an injustice that needs to be righted.' I'm pretty optimistic that if we can get the witnesses we need to come forward, we will be successful in court. We hopefully have a witness that's going to say \u2014 that's non-family, non-relative witness \u2014 who is going to be able to tie all this in and say that they were basically an alibi witness. They were there with Mr. Stinney and this did not occur.<ref name=edwards>{{Cite news |last=Edwards |first=David |date=October 3, 2011 |url=http://www.rawstory.com/rs/2011/10/03/new-evidence-could-clear-14-year-old-executed-by-south-carolina/ |title=New evidence could clear 14-year-old executed by South Carolina |work=[[The Raw Story]] |archive-date=May 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530003313/http://www.rawstory.com/2011/10/new-evidence-could-clear-14-year-old-executed-by-south-carolina/ |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|Steve McKenzie}}\n\nGeorge Frierson stated in interviews, \"there has been a person that has been named as being the culprit, who is now deceased. And it was said by the family that there was a deathbed confession.\" Frierson said that the rumored culprit came from a well-known, prominent white family. A member, or members, of that family had served on the initial coroner's inquest jury, which had recommended that Stinney be prosecuted.<ref name=edwards />\n\nIn its ''amicus'' brief, the CRRJ said:\n<blockquote>There is compelling evidence that George Stinney was innocent of the crimes for which he was executed in 1944. The prosecutor relied, almost exclusively, on one piece of evidence to obtain a conviction in this capital case: the unrecorded, unsigned \"confession\" of a 14-year-old who was deprived of counsel and parental guidance, and whose defense lawyer shockingly failed to call exculpating witnesses or to preserve his right of appeal.<ref name=barbato /></blockquote>\n\nNew evidence in the court hearing in January 2014 included testimony by Stinney's siblings that he was with them at the time of the murders. In addition, an affidavit was introduced from the \"Reverend Francis Batson, who found the girls and pulled them from the water-filled ditch. In his statement he recalls there was not much blood in or around the ditch, suggesting that they may have been killed elsewhere and moved.\"<ref name=mcveigh /> Wilford \"Johnny\" Hunter, who was in prison with Stinney, \"testified that the teenager told him he had been made to confess\" and always maintained his innocence.<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nThe solicitor for the state of South Carolina, who argued for the state against [[exoneration]], was Ernest A. Finney III. He is the son of [[Ernest A. Finney Jr.]], who was appointed as South Carolina's first African American State Supreme Court justice since Reconstruction.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robertson |first=Campbell |date=December 18, 2014 |title=South Carolina Judge Vacates Conviction of George Stinney in 1944 Execution |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/us/judge-vacates-conviction-in-1944-execution.html |publisher=New York Times |archive-date=December 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212132153/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/us/judge-vacates-conviction-in-1944-execution.html |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRather than approving a new trial, on December 17, 2014, [[circuit court]] Judge Carmen Mullen [[Vacated judgment|vacated]] Stinney's conviction. She ruled that he had not received a fair trial, as he was not effectively defended and his [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] right had been violated.<ref name=mccloud/><ref name=wis /> The ruling was a rare use of the legal remedy of ''[[coram nobis]]''. Judge Mullen ruled that his confession was likely coerced and thus [[Inadmissible Evidence|inadmissible]]. She also found that the execution of a 14-year-old constituted \"cruel and unusual punishment\", and that his attorney \"failed to call exculpating witnesses or to preserve his right of appeal.\"<ref name=barbato /> Mullen confined her judgment to the process of the prosecution, noting that Stinney \"may well have committed this crime.\" With reference to the legal process, Mullen wrote, \"No one can justify a 14-year-old child charged, tried, convicted and executed in some 80 days,\" concluding that \"In essence, not much was done for this child when his life lay in the balance.\"<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nFamily members of both Betty Binnicker and Mary Thames expressed disappointment at the court's ruling. They said that although they acknowledge Stinney's execution at the age of 14 is controversial, they never doubted his guilt. The niece of Betty Binnicker claimed she and her family have extensively researched the case, and argues that \"people who [just] read these articles in the newspaper don't know the truth.\"<ref name=berkeley/> Binnicker's niece alleges that, in the early 1990s, a police officer who had arrested Stinney had contacted her and said: \"Don't you ever believe that boy didn't kill your aunt.\"<ref name=berkeley>{{cite news |last=Gaskins |first=Nikki |date=March 1, 2014 |title=Goose Creek woman, others hope George Stinney murder conviction sticks |url=http://www.berkeleyobserver.com/2014/03/01/goose-creek-woman-others-hope-george-stinney-murder-conviction-sticks/ |newspaper=Berkeley Observer |archive-date=March 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322113343/http://www.berkeleyobserver.com/2014/03/01/goose-creek-woman-others-hope-george-stinney-murder-conviction-sticks/ |url-status=live}}</ref> These family members said that the claims of a deathbed confession from an individual confessing to the girls' murders have never been substantiated.<ref name=berkeley />\n\n== Books and films about Stinney's case ==\n*[[David Stout]] based his first novel ''Carolina Skeletons'' (1988) on this case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-07-24/books/bk-10393_1_david-stout |title=Fried at 14, but Was He Guilty? : CAROLINA SKELETONS: by David Stout (Mysterious Press: $16.95; 305 pp.; 0-89296-264-X) |date=24 July 1988 |access-date=20 August 2018 |newspaper=[[LA Times]] |first=Andrew |last=Jaffe |author-link=Andrew Jaffe}}</ref> He was awarded the 1989 Edgar Award for Best First Novel ([[Edgar Allan Poe Award]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/05/16/books/edgar-awards-for-mysteries.html |date=May 16, 1989|title=Edgar Awards for Mysteries |page=C18 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 28, 2010 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref> Stout suggests in the novel that Stinney, whom he renames Linus Bragg, was innocent. The plot revolves around a fictitious brother of Stinney/Bragg, who unravels the truth about the case decades later.\n*The novel was adapted as a 1991 television movie of the same name directed by John Erman, featuring [[Kenny Blank]] as Stinney/Bragg.<ref>{{cite book |last=Devine |first=Jeremy M. |title=Vietnam at 24 Frames a Second: A Critical and Thematic Analysis of 360 Films About the Vietnam War |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WKYyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT378 |publisher=[[McFarland Publishing]] |date=25 August 2017 |page=378 |isbn=9781476605357}}</ref> [[Lou Gossett Jr.]] played Stinney's/Bragg's younger brother James.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Connor |first=John J. |author-link=John J. O'Connor (journalist) |date=September 30, 1991 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/30/news/review-television-reopening-the-wounds-of-an-old-murder-case.html |title=Review/Television; Reopening the Wounds Of an Old Murder Case |page=C16 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date= February 28, 2010 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref>\n*As of February 2014, another movie about the Stinney case, ''83 Days'', was planned by Pleroma Studios, written and produced by Ray Brown with [[Charles Burnett (director)|Charles Burnett]] as director.<ref name=ebony /><ref>{{cite news |last=Brinson |first=Ron |date=January 24, 2014 |title=George Stinney trial is a reminder of justice not served |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/opinion/george-stinney-trial-is-a-reminder-of-justice-not-served/article_d1ed428d-e649-5e75-921e-f5d4d1e67cd2.html |newspaper=[[The Post and Courier]] |access-date=20 August 2018 |publisher=Evening Post Industries}}</ref>\n*An opera, ''Stinney,'' was written in 2015 by Frances Pollock, who had just earned her master's degree at Peabody Institute. It was performed to a full house at 2640 Space in Baltimore MD the same year. Several cousins of George Stinney from Baltimore and other parts of Maryland attended opening night. <ref>https://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bal-stinney-new-opera-about-1944-execution-of-teen-delivers-jolt-20150519-story.html</ref>\n*The novel \u2018\u2019Billy\u2019\u2019 by Albert French was inspired by these events\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people executed in South Carolina]]\n*[[List of wrongful convictions in the United States]]\n*[[Hannah Ocuish]], twelve-year-old girl believed to be the youngest person to be executed in the United States\n*[[Wrongful_execution#United_States|Wrongful executions in the United States]]\n*[[List of unsolved murders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news\n|title=Pursuing Justice for All\n|first=Charles M.\n|last=Blow\n|date=December 21, 2014\n|newspaper=New York Times\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/22/opinion/charles-blow-pursuing-justice-for-all.html?mcubz=3&_r=0}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stinney, George}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:People from Clarendon County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People executed by South Carolina by electric chair]]\n[[Category:Executed children]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against boys]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Juvenile offenders executed by the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Wrongful executions]]\n[[Category:Executed African-American people]]\n[[Category:History of South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People wrongfully convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Executed people from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Pinewood, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:1944 in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:1944 in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = George Junius Stinney,Jr.\n| image_name = George Stinney mugshot.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = George Stinney's 1944 mug shot\n| birth_name = George Junius Stinney Jr.\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1929|10|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Pinewood, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1944|6|16|1929|10|21}}\n| death_place = [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]], [[South Carolina]], U.S.\n| apprehended = March 1944\n| conviction = [[First-degree murder]] (overturned)\n| conviction_penalty = Death by [[electric chair]]\n| conviction_status = {{Plainlist|\n* Executed (1944)\n[[Vacated judgment|Conviction overturned]] (2014)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''George Junius Stinney, Jr.''' (October 21, 1929 \u2013 June 16, 1944), was an [[African Americans|African American]] youth who was convicted, in a proceeding later vacated as an unfair trial, of murdering two [[White Americans|white]] girls, ages 7 and 11, in his hometown of [[Alcolu, South Carolina]]. He was executed by electric chair in June of that year.\n\nThe court refused to hear his appeal, and the appeals on his behalf to the governor for clemency were denied.{{Citation needed|reason=No citation for the court refusing to hear an appeal.|date=December 2019}} He is the youngest American to be sentenced to death and executed.<ref name=banner>{{cite news |last=Banner |first=Stuart |date=March 5, 2005 |title=When Killing a Juvenile Was Routine |url=https://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2005/03/05/weekinreview/20050306_BANNER_CHART.html |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=April 12, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412063127/http://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2005/03/05/weekinreview/20050306_BANNER_CHART.html |url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nA re-examination of the Stinney case began in 2004, and several individuals and [[Northeastern University School of Law]] sought a judicial review. His conviction was overturned in 2014, 70 years after he was executed when a court ruled that he had not received a fair trial.\n\n==Incident==\nTwo young white girls, 11-year-old Betty June Binnicker and 7-year-old Mary Emma Thames, were found dead in the company mill town of [[Alcolu, South Carolina]], in March 1944, after they had failed to return home the night before.\n\n==Arrest and prosecution==\nPolice arrested 14-year-old George Stinney as a suspect. They stated that he had confessed to the crime while under custody.<ref name=ins>{{Cite web |title=State Prison Protects Negro after Slaying |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19440327&id=ldM0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=oE4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5724,7818032&hl=en |date=March 25, 1944 |agency=[[International News Service|INS]] |publisher = [[St. Petersburg Times]] |accessdate=October 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=ap>{{Cite web |title=Youth Admits Killing Girls |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1499&dat=19440325&id=AfAZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4356,3574612&hl=en |date=March 25, 1944 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |publisher = [[The Milwaukee Journal]] |accessdate = October 18, 2015}}</ref> There was a written record of his confession in the form of notes provided by an investigating deputy.<ref name=mcveigh>{{Cite news |last = McVeigh |first = Karen |date=March 22, 2014 |title = George Stinney was executed at 14. Can his family now clear his name? |url = https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2014/mar/22/george-stinney-execution-verdict-innocent |newspaper = [[The Observer]] |archive-date= March 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319042807/http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2014/mar/22/george-stinney-execution-verdict-innocent |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNo transcript was recorded of the brief trial. Stinney was convicted of [[first-degree murder]] of the two girls in less than 10 minutes by an [[all-white jury]], during a two hour trial.<ref name=bever>{{cite news |last=Bever |first=Lindsey |date=December 18, 2014 |title=It took 10 minutes to convict 14-year-old George Stinney Jr. It took 70 years after his execution to exonerate him. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/12/18/the-rush-job-conviction-of-14-year-old-george-stinney-exonerated-70-years-after-execution/ |publisher=[[Washington Post]]}}</ref> The court refused to hear his appeal. He was executed that year, still age 14, by [[electric chair]].\n\nIn the decades since Stinney's conviction and execution, the question of his guilt, the validity of his reported confession, and the judicial process leading to his execution have been extensively criticized.<ref name=collins>{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Jeffrey |date=January 18, 2010 |title=SC crusaders look to right Jim Crow justice wrongs |url=http://www.goupstate.com/article/20100118/ARTICLES/100119732 |agency=AP |publisher=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |archive-date=May 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529172647/http://www.goupstate.com/article/20100118/articles/100119732 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA group of lawyers and activists investigated the Stinney case on behalf of his family. In 2013, the family petitioned for a new trial. On December 17, 2014, his conviction was posthumously [[Vacated judgment|vacated]] 70 years after his execution, because the circuit court judge ruled that he had not been given a fair trial; he had no effective defense representation and his [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] rights had been violated.<ref name=wis>{{cite web |last=Turnage |first=Jeremy |date=December 17, 2014 |url=http://www.wistv.com/story/27651255/george-stinney-14-year-old-convicted-of-44-murder-exonerated |title=George Stinney, 14-year-old convicted of '44 murder, exonerated |publisher=[[WIS (TV)|WIS]] |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223031/http://www.wistv.com/story/27651255/george-stinney-14-year-old-convicted-of-44-murder-exonerated |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=mccloud>{{cite news |last=McCloud |first=Harriet |date=December 17, 2014 |title=South Carolina judge tosses conviction of black teen executed in 1944\n |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-south-carolina-idUSKBN0JV25320141217 |agency=[[Reuters]] |archive-date=December 22, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222110718/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-south-carolina-idUSKBN0JV25320141217 |url-status=live }}</ref> The judgment noted that while Stinney could have committed the crime, the prosecution and trial were fundamentally flawed.<ref name=mcveigh /> Judge Mullen ruled that his confession was likely coerced and thus inadmissible. She also found that the execution of a 14-year-old constituted \"[[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|cruel and unusual punishment]].\"<ref name=barbato />\n\n==Case background==\nIn 1944, George Junius Stinney, Jr. lived in [[Alcolu, South Carolina|Alcolu]], [[Clarendon County, South Carolina]]. The 14-year-old lived with his father, George Stinney Sr., mother Aim\u00e9, brothers  John, 17, and Charles, 12, and sisters Katherine, 10, and Aim\u00e9, 7. George Sr. worked at the town's sawmill, and the family resided in company housing. Alcolu was a small, working-class mill town, where white and black neighborhoods were separated by railroad tracks. The town was typical of small Southern towns of the time. Given segregated schools and churches for white and black residents, there was limited interaction between them. <ref name=mcveigh />\n\nThe bodies of Betty June Binnicker, age 11, and Mary Emma Thames, age 7, were found in a ditch on March 23, 1944, on the African American side of Alcolu, during a search after they had not returned home the night before.<ref name=collins /> George Stinney Sr. helped in the search. The girls had been beaten with a weapon, variously reported as a piece of blunt metal or a railroad spike.<ref name=bever /> The girls were last seen riding their bicycles looking for flowers.\n\nAs they passed the Stinneys' property, they had asked young George Stinney and his sister, Aim\u00e9,<ref name=mcveigh /> if they knew where to find \"[[Passiflora incarnata|maypops]]\", a local name for passionflowers.<ref name=ap /> According to Aim\u00e9, she was with George at the time the police later established for the murders.<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nAccording to an article reported by the wire services on March 24, 1944, and published widely, with the mistake of the boy's name preserved, the sheriff announced the arrest and said that \"George Junius\" had confessed and led officers to \"a hidden piece of iron.\"<ref name=ins /><ref name=ap /> Both girls had suffered [[Blunt trauma|blunt force trauma]] to the face and head.<ref name=jones>{{cite book |last=Jones |first=Mark R. |title=South Carolina Killers: Crimes of Passion |url=https://archive.org/details/southcarolinakil00jone |url-access=registration |accessdate=November 24, 2014 |year=2007 |publisher=[[The History Press]] |isbn=978-1-59629-395-3 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/southcarolinakil00jone/page/38 38]\u201342 |chapter=Chapter Five: ''Too Young to Die: The Execution of George Stinney Jr.'' (1944)}}</ref>\n\nReports differed as to what kind of weapon had been used.<ref name=berkeley/> According to a report by the medical examiner, these wounds had been \"inflicted by a blunt instrument with a round head, about the size of a hammer.\" Both girls' skulls were punctured. The medical examiner reported no evidence of sexual assault to the younger girl, though the genitalia of the older girl were slightly bruised.<ref name=\"crrj\">{{cite press release |url=http://nuweb9.neu.edu/civilrights/crrj-brings-justice-to-youngest-person-executed-in-us-history/ |title=CRRJ Brings Justice to Youngest Person Executed in US History |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103223902/http://nuweb9.neu.edu/civilrights/crrj-brings-justice-to-youngest-person-executed-in-us-history/ |archivedate=January 3, 2015 |accessdate=January 3, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=mclaughlin>{{cite web|last=McLaughlin |first=Eliot C.|date=January 23, 2014 |title=New trial sought for George Stinney, executed at 14 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/21/us/george-stinney-hearing/ |website=[[CNN]] |archive-date=April 10, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410224104/http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/21/us/george-stinney-hearing/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=independent>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Tim |date=January 22, 2014 |title=George Stinney: After 70 years, justice in sight for boy America sent to electric chair |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/after-70-years-justice-in-sight-for-boy-america-sent-to-electric-chair-9078460.html |website=[[The Independent]] |archive-date=March 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305021418/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/after-70-years-justice-in-sight-for-boy-america-sent-to-electric-chair-9078460.html |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nGeorge Stinney and his older brother Johnny were arrested on suspicion of murdering the girls. Johnny was released by police, but George was held. He was not allowed to see his parents until after his trial and conviction.<ref name=mcveigh /> According to a handwritten statement, the arresting officer was H.S. Newman, a Clarendon County deputy, who stated, \"I arrested a boy by the name of George Stinney. He then made a confession and told me where to find a piece of iron about 15 inches were [sic] he said he put it in a ditch about six feet from the bicycle.\" No confession statement signed by Stinney is known to exist. The 14 year old claimed that the arresting officers starved him and then bribed him with food to confess.<ref name=mcveigh /><ref name=mclaughlin />\n\nGeorge was reported to have gotten into fights at school, including a fight where he scratched a girl with a knife. This assertion by Stinney's seventh-grade teacher, who was African American, was disputed by Aime Stinney Ruffner when it was reported in 1995. A local white woman who remembered Stinney from childhood said in 2014 that Stinney had threatened to kill her and her friend the day before the murder, and that he was known as a bully.<ref name=mcveigh /><ref name=behre>{{Cite web |last=Behre |first=Robert |date= January 17, 2014 |title=Family, friends of 1944 murder victim wary of reopening George Stinney\u2019s death penalty case |url= http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140117/PC1610/140119506 |website=[[The Post and Courier]] |archive-date=June 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603111624/http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140117/PC1610/140119506 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing George's arrest, his father was fired from his job at the local sawmill, and the Stinney family had to immediately vacate their company housing. The family feared for their safety. The community as well as the police threatened to lynch their other children if they did not leave immediately.{{cn|date=December 2019}} His parents did not see George again before the trial. He had no support during his 81-day confinement and trial; he was detained at a jail in Columbia 50 miles from Alcolu, due to the risk of lynching.<ref name=collins /> Stinney was questioned alone, without his parents or an attorney.<ref name=bever /> Although the [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] guarantees legal counsel, it was not until 1963 ''[[Gideon v. Wainwright]]'' that explicitly required representation through the course of criminal proceedings.<ref name=bever />\n\n==Trial==\nThe entire proceeding against Stinney, including jury selection, took one day. Stinney's court-appointed defense counsel was Charles Plowden, a tax commissioner campaigning for election to local office. Plowden did not challenge the three police officers who testified that Stinney confessed to the two murders, despite this being the only evidence against him.\n\nHe did not challenge the prosecution's presentation of two differing versions of Stinney's verbal confession. In one version, Stinney was attacked by the girls after he tried to help one girl who had fallen in the ditch, and he killed them in self defense. In the other version, he had followed the girls, first attacking Mary Emma and then Betty June. There was no physical evidence linking him to the murders.<ref name=mcveigh /> There is no written record of Stinney's confession apart from Deputy Newman's statement.<ref name=collins />\n\nStinney's trial had an [[all-white jury]], as was typical at the time. As most blacks were still [[Disfranchisement after Reconstruction era|disenfranchised]] and prohibited from voting, they could not be selected as jurors. More than 1,000 whites crowded the courtroom, but no blacks were allowed.<ref name=collins />\n\nOther than the testimony of the three police officers, at trial prosecutors called three witnesses: Reverend Francis Batson, who discovered the bodies of the two girls, and the two doctors who performed the post-mortem examination. Conflicting confessions were reported to have been offered by the prosecution. The court allowed discussion of the \"possibility\" of rape although the medical examiner's report had no evidence to support this. Stinney's counsel did not call any witnesses, did not cross-examine witnesses, and offered little or no defense. The trial presentation lasted two and a half hours.<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nThe jury took less than ten minutes to [[jury deliberation|deliberate]], after which they returned with a guilty verdict. Judge [[Philip H. Stoll]] sentenced Stinney to death by electrocution. There is no transcript of the trial. No appeal was filed by his defense attorney.<ref name=collins />\n\nStinney's family, churches, and the [[NAACP]] appealed to Governor [[Olin D. Johnston]] for clemency, given the age of the boy. Others urged the governor to let the execution proceed, which he did.<ref name=jones /> Johnston wrote in a response to one appeal for clemency that \n\n<blockquote>It may be interesting for you to know that Stinney killed the smaller girl to rape the larger one. Then he killed the larger girl and raped her dead body. Twenty minutes later he returned and attempted to rape her again, but her body was too cold. All of this he admitted himself.</blockquote>\n\nBetween the time of Stinney's arrest and his execution, Stinney's parents were allowed to see him once, after the trial when he was held in the Columbia penitentiary. Under the threat of lynching, they were not allowed to see him any other time. <ref name=mcveigh />\n\n==Execution==\nGeorge Stinney was executed at the Central Correctional Institution in Columbia, South Carolina on June 16, 1944, at 7:30 p.m. At 7:25 pm, standing 5 feet 1 inch tall and weighing just over 90 lbs three police officers approached the cell where George was being held, one officer entered and took him out of his cell. The officers escorted him to the execution room where they placed him in the electric chair, using a Bible he was carrying as a booster seat because George was so small.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/george-stinney-jr-black-14-year-old-boy-exonerated-70-years-after-he-was-executed-9932429.html|title=He was 14 when he was executed. More than 70 years later, this boy has been exonerated|date=2014-12-18|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> George was then restrained by his arms, legs, body to the chair. His father was allowed to approach George to say his final words to his son. An officer asked George if he had any last words to say, but George just shook his head. George Stinney could only whimper and take big deep breaths as one of the officers pulled a strap from the chair and placed it over his mouth, causing George to break into tears. They then placed the face mask over his face, which did not fit him, as George continued sobbing. When the lethal electricity was applied, the mask covering George's face slipped off, revealing George's burned scalp and tears streaming down his face, saliva dripping from his mouth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/12/18/the-rush-job-conviction-of-14-year-old-george-stinney-exonerated-70-years-after-execution/|title=It took 10 minutes to convict 14-year-old George Stinney Jr. It took 70 years after his execution to exonerate him.|last=Bever|first=Lindsey|date=2014-12-18|work=Washington Post|access-date=2019-09-24|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> {{Citation needed span|text=George Stinney was declared dead after eight minutes. George's teeth were smoking and he had one eye missing. The next day (Saturday, June 17, 1944) he was buried by his family at Sumter, South Carolina. For a long time, his body was in an unmarked grave in hopes that the anonymity would allow him to forever rest in peace.|date=September 2019|reason=}}\n\n==Reopening of case and vacatur of conviction==\nIn 2004, George Frierson, a local historian who grew up in Alcolu, started researching the case after reading a newspaper article about it. His work gained the attention of South Carolina lawyers Steve McKenzie and Matt Burgess.<ref name=mcveigh /> In addition, Ray Brown, attorney James Moon, and others contributed countless hours of research and review of historical documents, and found witnesses and evidence to assist in exonerating Stinney. Among those who aided the case were the [[Civil Rights and Restorative Justice Project]] (CRRJ) at [[Northeastern University School of Law]], which filed an ''amicus'' brief with the court in 2014.<ref name=barbato>{{cite web |last=Barbato |first=Lauren |date=December 17, 2014 |title=The Youngest Person Executed In America, George Stinney Jr., Almost Certainly Wasn't Guilty |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/54488-the-youngest-person-executed-in-america-george-stinney-jr-almost-certainly-wasnt-guilty |website=[[Bustle.com]]}}</ref> Frierson and the ''pro bono'' lawyers first sought relief through the Pardon and Parole Board of South Carolina.\n\nMcKenzie and Burgess, along with attorney Ray Chandler representing Stinney's family, filed a motion for a new trial on October 25, 2013.<ref name=ebony>{{cite news |last= Braswell | first= Kristin | title= Film to Explore George Stinney Jr. Execution | url= http://www.ebony.com/news-views/film-to-explore-george-stinney-jr-execution-405 | date=February 28, 2014 | work= [[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]] |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304131221/http://www.ebony.com/news-views/film-to-explore-george-stinney-jr-execution-405 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n \n{{quote|If we can get the case re-opened, we can go to the judge and say, 'There wasn't any reason to convict this child. There was no evidence to present to the jury. There was no transcript. This case needs to be re-opened. This is an injustice that needs to be righted.' I'm pretty optimistic that if we can get the witnesses we need to come forward, we will be successful in court. We hopefully have a witness that's going to say \u2014 that's non-family, non-relative witness \u2014 who is going to be able to tie all this in and say that they were basically an alibi witness. They were there with Mr. Stinney and this did not occur.<ref name=edwards>{{Cite news |last=Edwards |first=David |date=October 3, 2011 |url=http://www.rawstory.com/rs/2011/10/03/new-evidence-could-clear-14-year-old-executed-by-south-carolina/ |title=New evidence could clear 14-year-old executed by South Carolina |work=[[The Raw Story]] |archive-date=May 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530003313/http://www.rawstory.com/2011/10/new-evidence-could-clear-14-year-old-executed-by-south-carolina/ |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|Steve McKenzie}}\n\nGeorge Frierson stated in interviews, \"there has been a person that has been named as being the culprit, who is now deceased. And it was said by the family that there was a deathbed confession.\" Frierson said that the rumored culprit came from a well-known, prominent white family. A member, or members, of that family had served on the initial coroner's inquest jury, which had recommended that Stinney be prosecuted.<ref name=edwards />\n\nIn its ''amicus'' brief, the CRRJ said:\n<blockquote>There is compelling evidence that George Stinney was innocent of the crimes for which he was executed in 1944. The prosecutor relied, almost exclusively, on one piece of evidence to obtain a conviction in this capital case: the unrecorded, unsigned \"confession\" of a 14-year-old who was deprived of counsel and parental guidance, and whose defense lawyer shockingly failed to call exculpating witnesses or to preserve his right of appeal.<ref name=barbato /></blockquote>\n\nNew evidence in the court hearing in January 2014 included testimony by Stinney's siblings that he was with them at the time of the murders. In addition, an affidavit was introduced from the \"Reverend Francis Batson, who found the girls and pulled them from the water-filled ditch. In his statement he recalls there was not much blood in or around the ditch, suggesting that they may have been killed elsewhere and moved.\"<ref name=mcveigh /> Wilford \"Johnny\" Hunter, who was in prison with Stinney, \"testified that the teenager told him he had been made to confess\" and always maintained his innocence.<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nThe solicitor for the state of South Carolina, who argued for the state against [[exoneration]], was Ernest A. Finney III. He is the son of [[Ernest A. Finney Jr.]], who was appointed as South Carolina's first African American State Supreme Court justice since Reconstruction.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robertson |first=Campbell |date=December 18, 2014 |title=South Carolina Judge Vacates Conviction of George Stinney in 1944 Execution |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/us/judge-vacates-conviction-in-1944-execution.html |publisher=New York Times |archive-date=December 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212132153/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/us/judge-vacates-conviction-in-1944-execution.html |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRather than approving a new trial, on December 17, 2014, [[circuit court]] Judge Carmen Mullen [[Vacated judgment|vacated]] Stinney's conviction. She ruled that he had not received a fair trial, as he was not effectively defended and his [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] right had been violated.<ref name=mccloud/><ref name=wis /> The ruling was a rare use of the legal remedy of ''[[coram nobis]]''. Judge Mullen ruled that his confession was likely coerced and thus [[Inadmissible Evidence|inadmissible]]. She also found that the execution of a 14-year-old constituted \"cruel and unusual punishment\", and that his attorney \"failed to call exculpating witnesses or to preserve his right of appeal.\"<ref name=barbato /> Mullen confined her judgment to the process of the prosecution, noting that Stinney \"may well have committed this crime.\" With reference to the legal process, Mullen wrote, \"No one can justify a 14-year-old child charged, tried, convicted and executed in some 80 days,\" concluding that \"In essence, not much was done for this child when his life lay in the balance.\"<ref name=mcveigh />\n\nFamily members of both Betty Binnicker and Mary Thames expressed disappointment at the court's ruling. They said that although they acknowledge Stinney's execution at the age of 14 is controversial, they never doubted his guilt. The niece of Betty Binnicker claimed she and her family have extensively researched the case, and argues that \"people who [just] read these articles in the newspaper don't know the truth.\"<ref name=berkeley/> Binnicker's niece alleges that, in the early 1990s, a police officer who had arrested Stinney had contacted her and said: \"Don't you ever believe that boy didn't kill your aunt.\"<ref name=berkeley>{{cite news |last=Gaskins |first=Nikki |date=March 1, 2014 |title=Goose Creek woman, others hope George Stinney murder conviction sticks |url=http://www.berkeleyobserver.com/2014/03/01/goose-creek-woman-others-hope-george-stinney-murder-conviction-sticks/ |newspaper=Berkeley Observer |archive-date=March 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322113343/http://www.berkeleyobserver.com/2014/03/01/goose-creek-woman-others-hope-george-stinney-murder-conviction-sticks/ |url-status=live}}</ref> These family members said that the claims of a deathbed confession from an individual confessing to the girls' murders have never been substantiated.<ref name=berkeley />\n\n== Books and films about Stinney's case ==\n*[[David Stout]] based his first novel ''Carolina Skeletons'' (1988) on this case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-07-24/books/bk-10393_1_david-stout |title=Fried at 14, but Was He Guilty? : CAROLINA SKELETONS: by David Stout (Mysterious Press: $16.95; 305 pp.; 0-89296-264-X) |date=24 July 1988 |access-date=20 August 2018 |newspaper=[[LA Times]] |first=Andrew |last=Jaffe |author-link=Andrew Jaffe}}</ref> He was awarded the 1989 Edgar Award for Best First Novel ([[Edgar Allan Poe Award]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/05/16/books/edgar-awards-for-mysteries.html |date=May 16, 1989|title=Edgar Awards for Mysteries |page=C18 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 28, 2010 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref> Stout suggests in the novel that Stinney, whom he renames Linus Bragg, was innocent. The plot revolves around a fictitious brother of Stinney/Bragg, who unravels the truth about the case decades later.\n*The novel was adapted as a 1991 television movie of the same name directed by John Erman, featuring [[Kenny Blank]] as Stinney/Bragg.<ref>{{cite book |last=Devine |first=Jeremy M. |title=Vietnam at 24 Frames a Second: A Critical and Thematic Analysis of 360 Films About the Vietnam War |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WKYyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT378 |publisher=[[McFarland Publishing]] |date=25 August 2017 |page=378 |isbn=9781476605357}}</ref> [[Lou Gossett Jr.]] played Stinney's/Bragg's younger brother James.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Connor |first=John J. |author-link=John J. O'Connor (journalist) |date=September 30, 1991 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/30/news/review-television-reopening-the-wounds-of-an-old-murder-case.html |title=Review/Television; Reopening the Wounds Of an Old Murder Case |page=C16 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date= February 28, 2010 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref>\n*As of February 2014, another movie about the Stinney case, ''83 Days'', was planned by Pleroma Studios, written and produced by Ray Brown with [[Charles Burnett (director)|Charles Burnett]] as director.<ref name=ebony /><ref>{{cite news |last=Brinson |first=Ron |date=January 24, 2014 |title=George Stinney trial is a reminder of justice not served |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/opinion/george-stinney-trial-is-a-reminder-of-justice-not-served/article_d1ed428d-e649-5e75-921e-f5d4d1e67cd2.html |newspaper=[[The Post and Courier]] |access-date=20 August 2018 |publisher=Evening Post Industries}}</ref>\n*An opera, ''Stinney,'' was written in 2015 by Frances Pollock, who had just earned her master's degree at Peabody Institute. It was performed to a full house at 2640 Space in Baltimore MD the same year. Several cousins of George Stinney from Baltimore and other parts of Maryland attended opening night. <ref>https://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bal-stinney-new-opera-about-1944-execution-of-teen-delivers-jolt-20150519-story.html</ref>\n*The novel \u2018\u2019Billy\u2019\u2019 by Albert French was inspired by these events\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people executed in South Carolina]]\n*[[List of wrongful convictions in the United States]]\n*[[Hannah Ocuish]], twelve-year-old girl believed to be the youngest person to be executed in the United States\n*[[Wrongful_execution#United_States|Wrongful executions in the United States]]\n*[[List of unsolved murders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news\n|title=Pursuing Justice for All\n|first=Charles M.\n|last=Blow\n|date=December 21, 2014\n|newspaper=New York Times\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/22/opinion/charles-blow-pursuing-justice-for-all.html?mcubz=3&_r=0}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stinney, George}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:People from Clarendon County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People executed by South Carolina by electric chair]]\n[[Category:Executed children]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against boys]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Juvenile offenders executed by the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Wrongful executions]]\n[[Category:Executed African-American people]]\n[[Category:History of South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People wrongfully convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Executed people from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Pinewood, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:1944 in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:1944 in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "CyanideCrayon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Stinney"}
